<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-St.Patrick'sShooting     07-28 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-St. Patrick's Shooting,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Kills Man Accused Of Robbery Outside St. Patrick's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man robbed a tourist at gunpoint on crowded
Fifth Avenue outside St. Patrick's Cathedral, then was shot and
killed Wednesday when he tried to escape in a car driven by an
off-duty correction officer, police said.
   During a struggle inside the car, the correction officer fired
his gun, striking the robbery suspect three times in the chest,
said a police spokesman, Sgt. Maurice Howard.
   The suspect, Angel Santiago, 22, of Queens died later in the
afternoon at Bellevue Hospital, Howard said.
   The correction officer, John Bonilla, 33, also shot himself in
the foot during the struggle and was in stable condition at
Bellevue, Howard said.
   Santiago fired no shots, but police recovered a revolver,
believed to be Santiago's, that contained five live rounds, Howard
said.
   Bonilla's 5-year-old son, also named John, was in the car at the
time of the 5 p.m. shooting but was not injured, Howard said.
   A second robbery suspect was still at large, Howard said.
   Joe Ashcraft of Muncie, Ind., said he was visiting midtown
Manhattan with his family, standing on the sidewalk photographing
the historic Roman Catholic cathedral, when two men pulled up in a
car and one got out and demanded his video camera.
   ``He said if you don't give me your camera and take it over and
put it in that car right now I'm going to shoot you. At that point
I didn't believe he had a gun,'' said Ashcraft.
   ``But then he pulled the gun and when he pulled the gun I gave
him the camera,'' Ashcraft said.
   As the robbers tried to speed off, their car collided with a
taxi and then slammed into the side of a bus. The pair then jumped
out of their car and fled on foot before Santiago got into
Bonilla's car, police said.
   The gun used by Bonilla was his personal revolver, which he was
authorized to carry, Howard said.
   Ashcraft recovered his video camera from the robbery suspects'
car, where they had left it behind when they fled, Howard said.
   ``We've been riding the subways every place we go and not had a
fear in the world,'' said Ashcraft, who was with his wife, their
6-year-old daughter and 9-year-old son and Mrs. Ashcraft's uncle.
Now, he said, ``I'm a little afraid.''
   But he said he wouldn't consider New York City ``a bad place.
It's just one incident.''
</TEXT>
