<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IrelandPilgrimage     07-28 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland Pilgrimage,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O'Connor Disagrees With Koch On British In N. Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John J. O'Connor, breaking with fellow
peace pilgrim Mayor Edward I. Koch, said Wednesday that Britain
should remove its ``occupying forces'' from Northern Ireland
``within a reasonable time.''
   ``I cannot imagine there will be lasting peace ... until all
British troops have withdrawn,'' he told reporters as he left
Ireland after a six-day peace pilgrimage.
   O'Connor had said at the start of the pilgrimage that he'd come
to pray, not to talk politics. But the cardinal broke his silence
after Koch, his pilgrimage companion, reversed himself and endorsed
the British presence in Ulster.
   O'Connor, who returned Wednesday afternoon to John F. Kennedy
Airport, called on British officials to announce ``a phased
withdrawal'' _ one the cardinal said was supported by most people
in the province.
   Asked if it should begin immediately, O'Connor replied, ``That's
not for me to say.''
   Before leaving Dublin on Tuesday, Koch said a day in Northern
Ireland had convinced him the British do not deserve ``the
castigation that many of us, myself included, have heaped upon
them. The British army is not an `occupation force,' (but rather) a
guardian of peace.''
   The British army has patrolled Northern Ireland since the early
1970s, when a Catholic civil rights movement came under attack by
Protestant police and paramilitary groups.
   But the Protestant violence also revitalized the Irish
Republican Army; since then, the primary opponents have been the
British and the IRA, which wants to unite the island.
   In recent years many British troops have been withdrawn, and
their duties assumed by members of Ulster's army reserve.
   About two-thirds of Northern Ireland's population is Protestant,
and surveys indicate that a majority of the province's residents _
including many Catholics _ favor union with Britain.
   O'Connor said his own 24 hours in Ulster convinced him there is
``an environment of increasing understanding'' between Catholics
and Protestants, and that ``an overwhelming number'' of both want
the troops out.
   Although O'Connor said he based his conclusion on talks with
Protestants, he did not meet with militants in either community
during his visit.
   The mayor's comments drew a heated response from Irish-American
politicians, including Nassau County Comptroller Peter King, who
called the remarks ``senseless and ridiculous.''
   O'Connor was more circumspect. He said he was not angry with
Koch, and felt that because Koch did not grow up as an
Irish-American, he failed to realize the British have been calling
themselves peacemakers in Northern Ireland for centuries.
</TEXT>
