<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Murder-Suicide     07-28 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder-Suicide,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Actress And Parents Dead In Apparent Murder-Suicide</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA10, 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A child actress who starred in last summer's
``Jaws IV: The Revenge'' was killed with her mother Wednesday in an
apparent murder-suicide initiated by her father, who also died,
authorities said.
   The coroner had not yet identified the couple and the child, but
neighbors said the girl was Judith Barsi, 11, who starred in the
third sequel to the series about a man-eating shark.
   Miss Barsi also appeared in the partly fact-based television
movie ``Fatal Vision,'' playing a daughter of Dr. Jeffrey
MacDonald, who was convicted of killing his pregnant wife and both
his daughters at Fort Bragg, N.C., in 1970.
   Miss Barsi's father apparently shot the girl and the mother in
their heads, set the inside of the house on fire, then turned the
gun on himself, police said. The fire caused extensive damage to
the interior of the home.
   A researcher at Universal Studios confirmed Miss Barsi starred
in ``Jaws IV: The Revenge'' as a character called ``Thea.'' She
also performed in several commercials and had appeared in the
television show ``Growing Pains,'' neighbors said.
   ``She was adorable ... quite precocious, blonde and blue-eyed,''
said former neighbor Adrienne Conway. She said the mother and
father had been having marital problems.
   Neighbors said they heard an explosion at 8:30 a.m., then saw
flames shooting out of a front window of the tan, single-story
house on a quiet street. One neighbor tried to douse the flames
with water from a garden hose until firefighters arrived.
   Officers at the scene said the father, identified by neighbors
as Joe Barsi, apparently doused the interior of the couple's home
with gasoline and set it ablaze before shooting himself in the head.
   The mother, Maria Barsi, estimated to be about 40, was found in
the hallway and the body of Miss Barsi in a bedroom, officials
said. Both had been burned, said Fire Battalion Chief Jack Monroe.
   Los Angeles Police Lt. Warren Knowles said the man was found
still holding the gun.
   Neighbors said the girl had an extremely protective father.
   ``The child was not allowed to go anywhere, very few places
alone,'' said neighbor Linda Williams. ``Even when she came to our
home, it always had to be OK'd by Dad before she came up the street
because apparently he was afraid she would run away.''
</TEXT>
