<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DadeTeachers     07-28 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dade Teachers,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Board Approves Raising Teachers' Top Pay To $64,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teacher contract that significantly boosts
salaries in the nation's fourth-largest school system and pays
$64,000 to some veteran educators won unanimous approval Wednesday
from the Dade County School Board.
   The three-year contract increases average teacher pay for the
upcoming academic year 28 percent to $33,066, more than $5,000
above the national median.
   ``The excuse that teachers could not do their jobs because of
low pay is no longer an excuse in this school system,'' said
Michael Krop, chairman of the seven-member school board. ``Many
school systems have talked about programs like this, but we did
something about it.''
   Krop said Dade has already received more applicants because of
publicity about the pay proposal.
   Dade County School Superintendent Joseph A. Fernandez said he
hoped the pay increase will raise the status of teaching in the
minds of students making career choices.
   ``We want young people making their professional decisions to
not look at teaching as a dead-end profession,'' Fernandez told the
school board.
   Dade County's system, with about 255,000 students and more than
15,200 teachers, is the nation's fourth-largest behind New York,
Los Angeles and Chicago.
   Under the contract, a first-year teacher would receive $23,000
annually and $64,000 a year would be paid to an educator with 14
years experience, a doctorate and who teaches summer school.
   The average salaries would increase to $36,042 the second year
and $39,646 the third year, said Dade County schools spokesman Andy
Gollan.
</TEXT>
