<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GoetzAppeal     07-28 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Goetz Appeal,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Agrees To Hear Goetz Gun Charge Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Court of Appeals, New York's
highest court, agreed Wednesday to hear Bernhard Goetz's appeal of
his conviction on charges that he illegally possessed the gun he
used to shoot four young men on a New York City subway in 1985.
   Without comment, Judge Joseph Bellacosa granted the appeal and
scheduled arguments for Oct. 17, said Court of Appeals spokesman
Walter Mordaunt.
   Goetz's original sentence on the gun possession charges had been
ruled illegal by a Manhattan appeals court and his resentencing is
set for Oct. 22 in Manhattan.
   Goetz's lawyers claim that state Supreme Court Justice Stephen
Crane, the trial judge, erred in his instructions to the jury and
that the gun conviction should be overturned.
   Crane had originally sentenced Goetz to six months in jail, a
$5,000 fine, 280 hours of community service, five years probation
and psychiatric counseling. The Manhattan appeals court allowed all
but the jail term to stand.
   The appeals court ruled that Crane should give Goetz an
undeterminate sentence or, if sentencing was going to be under New
York's gun control laws, a definite one-year term without probation.
   Goetz, 40, was convicted last summer of third-degree illegal
possession of a gun in connection with the December 1984 shooting
aboard a subway of four teen-agers he said were trying to rob him.
The young men claimed they were panhandling for money.
   Goetz was acquitted of all but the gun charge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
