<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0611 07-28 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0611,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Khmer Rouge Obstructing Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with Cambodia prime minister
quoted as saying Khmer Rouge trying to obstruct talks. Picks up 2nd
graf pvs, `The enduringly ...' Edits thereafter to conform and
trim. Changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOR, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's prime minister was quoted
Thursday as saying Khmer Rouge guerrilla delegates tried to
obstruct agreements at talks on ending Cambodia's civil war.
   The Jakarta Post quoted Prime Minister Hun Sen of the
Vietnamese-installed government as saying he would hold a third
round of separate peace talks with resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk in Paris in October.
   Sihanouk's forces are allied with the communist Khmer Rouge and
Son Sann's Khmer People's National Liberation Front in a coalition
fighting Vietnamese troops that invaded Cambodia in late 1978.
   Hun Sen, the guerrilla groups, Vietnam, Laos and the six-member
Association of Southeast Asian Nations on Thursday began their
fourth day of informal peace talks in Bogor.
   The Jakarta Post reported that Hun Sen said Khieu Samphan, the
Khmer Rouge representative, ``was not forthcoming to the point of
acting obstructive when it came to nailing down some specific
points of agreement.''
   On Wednesday, Sihanouk urged all factions to agree on a plan for
ending the ``miseries and humiliations'' that have afflicted
Cambodia since the Indochina war ended in 1975.
   The enduringly popular leader, who ruled Cambodia until 1970,
made the remarks in Jakarta, where he has tried to influence
developments in a meeting of the four factions at Bogor, about 40
miles south of the capital. All factions agree that Sihanouk, 65,
should have a central role in the future leadership.
   ``I ask you not to leave Indonesia without having signed
together a joint communique which shall tell our people and the
world that the four Cambodian factions are at least capable to
understand each other on certain essential points ... leading us
towards the end of a long and dark tunnel,'' Sihanouk said.
   Evoking the glories of Cambodian history, he said: ``Allow me to
recall that you all pretend to be the dignified descendants of the
very glorious builders of the world famous monuments of Angkor.
   ``If, like dignified descendants of the builders of Angkor, our
four factions wish to rapidly get rid of the last Vietnamese units
from our soil, they will only succeed to do so by achieving
national reconciliation and unity.''
   Angkor, in northwestern Cambodia, was the capital of the Khmer
Empire from the 9th century to the 15th. Its most imposing
monuments are Angkor Wat, a temple complex built in the 12th
century by King Suryavariman II, and Angkor Thom, built about 1200
by King Jayavarman VII.
   Sihanouk said, speaking in English, that it is handy to blame
Vietnam for all Cambodia's troubles, ``but it is not less true that
some Khmer (Cambodian) factions are equally heavily responsible for
these miseries and humilations.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and ousted the Khmer
Rouge regime of Pol Pot, which gained control at the end of the war
and had killed hundreds of thousands of Cambodians.
   More than 100,000 Vietnamese soldiers remain in Cambodia,
fighting the resistance coalition Sihanouk formerly led. Hanoi has
said it will withdraw all its troops by early 1990.
   The prince called for an interim government of the four factions
under ``a collegial system perfectly equal,'' and proposed that
fighting units be kept intact under a general staff representing
all factions. Each government department would have four
co-ministers.
   An international conference convened under the auspices of the
U.N. secretary-general would supervise withdrawal of foreign
forces, guarantee the nation's neutrality and help organize free
elections.
   Sihanouk resigned earlier this month as head of the resistance
coalition and is in Jakarta as a guest of President Suharto, which
allows him to participate in the peace talks indirectly.
   Hun Sen presented his own peace plan at Bogor on Monday, and
Sihanouk said his proposals include some of its points.
   ``I think my proposal is the most realistic,'' he said. ``The
very solution is in my proposals, not those of the charming Hun
Sen. I have to reject all other proposals in favor of mine.''
   He and Hun Sen negotiated in Paris last December and January
without finding a formula for peace.
   Son Sann said he supported Sihanouk's plan but the other
participants were not available for comment. Foreign Minister
Nguyen Co Thach of Vietnam told a news conference Wednesday that
working groups would be formed to prepare for further negotiations.
   No conclusive agreement had been expected from the Bogor
conference, which was considered a success for merely taking place.
</TEXT>
