<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-HefnerMarriage     07-28 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hefner Marriage,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Playboy Talks Of Giving Up Bachelorhood</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kimberley is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playboy empire founder Hugh Hefner said he
chose to give up life as a pajama-clad swinging single and marry
model Kimberley Conrad because ``it will make the relationship
better.''
   Hefner proposed to Ms. Conrad Playboy magazine's Miss January
1988, on Saturday over the wishing well at the Playboy Mansion,
where many other women have shared his life but never completely
captured his heart.
   ``I always had the feeling before that there was something else,
some further personal adventure waiting over the hill,'' he said in
a telephone interview Wednesday.
   But in this case, he said: ``It is inconceivable that there
could be something else that could be comparable or better.''
   Hefner, 62, described his fiancee as ``a homebody,'' who despite
the age difference holds similar interests in things like animals
and spending evenings talking and watching old movies.
   Ms. Conrad, who turns 26 next week, said she thought about
Hefner's proposal for a minute, then said ```Yes' because I can't
imagine life without him.''
   She plans to give up modeling. ``I'd rather be at home with Hef.
He's my priority,'' she said.
   Ms. Conrad's family apparently is supporting the marriage,
planned for sometime next year at the mansion.
   ``I wish them all the luck in the world,'' her grandmother Lila
Aldridge said Wednesday from her home in Moulton, Ala., where her
granddaughter was born.
   Hefner said he has never proposed marriage to anyone ``nor ever
really considered marriage'' since his 1958 divorce from his first
wife.
   ``I am doing it as much for myself as for her,'' he said. ``It
is going to make the relationship better, that security, that
continuity, that reaffirmation.''
   Ms. Conrad, who met Hefner last summer during a photo shooting,
moved into the Playboy Mansion with two dogs and cat shortly after
Hefner's longtime flame Carrie Leigh moved out in January.
   Earlier this year, Ms. Leigh, Playboy's 1983 cover girl,
attempted to bring a $35 million palimony action against Hefner
after their affair soured, but it later was dropped.
   Ms. Leigh said Wednesday through manager Joseph Battig: ``I hope
that he's finally happy at 62 years of age.''
</TEXT>
