<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Blackout,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blackout Blamed On Leftist Guerrillas Hits Capital Before Garcia
Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blackout hit the capital and most of coastal
Peru Wednesday night, hours before President Alan Garcia was to
give his state-of-the-union address.
   Leftist guerrillas may have sabotaged power lines and caused the
blackout, said Jose Acevedo, spokesman for the state power company
Electro-Peru.
   Shining Path guerrillas and a smaller rebel group, the pro-Cuban
Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, have caused dozens of blackouts
in Peru and used the cover of darkness to launch attacks.
   Radio Programas, Peru's leading news station, said people heard
explosions in several parts of the capital. Police told The
Associated Press they had no reports of guerrilla violence during
the power outage.
   The blackout at 8:15 p.m. affected Lima, cities along the 600
miles of the central Peruvian coastline and the highland city of
Huancayo, 125 miles east of Lima, Acevedo said.
   Power was restored to most areas within an hour, but areas south
of Lima were still without electrticity late Wednesday night,
Acevedo said.
   Garcia planned to speak midday Thursday and is expected to
address growing violence by leftist guerrillas.
   The government says more than 12,000 people have been killed in
the violence connected to the 8-year-old insurgency of the Shining
Path, a Maoist guerrilla group.
