<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ForeignInvestment     07-28 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Investment,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Sees Dramatic Climb in Foreign Investment in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign investment in American companies, real
estate and other assets has increased dramatically in recent years
and is likely to keep climbing through the year 2000, according to
a new study.
   The private study, released Wednesday by the Congressional
Economic Leadership Institute, said direct foreign investment in
the United States has jumped by more than 215 percent since 1980,
while American investment abroad increased by only one-fifth that
rate.
   And the study said the pace of foreign investment is expected to
accelerate, with foreign buyouts in 1988 expected to make up as
much as 20 percent of all U.S. acquisitions, up from 5 percent in
1987.
   However, the report said that in absolute terms, foreign
investments still account for only 5 percent to 6 percent of total
U.S. assets.
   The study said seven nations account for nearly 85 percent of
the foreign investment in the United States. They are Britain, with
$75 billion in cumulative investments by 1987; the Netherlands, $47
billion; Japan, $33 billion; Canada, $22 billion; West Germany, $20
billion; Switzerland, $14 billion; and France, $10 billion.
   Other findings include:
   _Foreign investors now own 10 percent of the U.S. manufacturing
base, with majority interest in the concrete and consumer
electronics industries and significant portions of machine tools,
chemicals and auto parts.
   _Most foreign outlays in the United States are to acquire
existing businesses rather than to establish new ones.
   _Jobs of nearly 3 million Americans are dependent on foreign
investment, up from just 1.1 million 10 years ago. Foreign
affiliates account for 7 percent of U.S. manufacturing jobs.
   _More than 25 percent of all commercial and industrial loans in
the United States are owed to foreign banks.
   _More than 12.5 million acres of farm land in 49 states are
owned by foreigners, about 1 percent of the U.S. total.
   The study was compiled with data from the U.S. Commerce
Department and other sources. The institute is a private
organization founded in 1987 to act as a forum on economic policy
for lawmakers and business, labor and educational leaders.
</TEXT>
