<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ParkService     07-28 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Park Service,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes To Make Park Service Director Non-Political</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled House has given the
Reagan administration what amounts to a vote of no confidence for
its handling of America's network of national parks.
   The action came Wednesday as the chamber voted 248-130 for
Democratic legislation to strip political appointees in the
Interior Deparment of their day-to-day power over the National Park
Service.
   The vote capped nearly eight years of friction over a variety of
parks and federal land-use issues between the Republican
administration and Democrats on the House Interior Committee.
   The bill faces an uncertain future in the Senate in the waning
weeks of the 100th Congress. And if it reaches President Reagan's
desk, it will be vetoed, says Rep. Robert Lagomarsino, R-Calif.
   The proposal, sponsored principally by Rep. Bruce Vento,
D-Minn., would make the National Park Service director a
presidential appointee who would be confirmed by the Senate for a
five-year term.
   The director now serves at the pleasure of the White House and
the Interior secretary and can be removed at any time for any
reason. The bill would require a president to show cause before
firing a parks director.
   The legislation would strip the Interior secretary and assistant
secretaries of any authority over the park service except for its
budget, a matter on which Congress has the final word.
   The measure also would create a three-member park system review
board _ appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate _ to
advise the director and Congress on how to improve the national
parks.
   Vento, who leveled no criticism against parks director William
Penn Mott, said the changes are necessary because professionals in
the National Park Service have been ``supplanted by political
decision-making.''
   ``The director of the park service has consistently been ordered
(by superiors) to give political testimony,'' Vento said. ``The
director ought to be free to act, but he is undercut and undermined
constantly by political appointees.''
   He said that political appointees have forced resignations and
transfers of park superintendents they didn't like, changed
performance ratings for parks personnel and required park officials
to obtain clearance for testimony before congressional committees.
   ``It's time to put a stop to this,'' said Vento, who chairs the
Interior national parks and public lands subcommittee.
   Subcommittee member Richard Lehman, D-Calif., said that
``political expediency overrules professional judgment. This occurs
because the secretary of the Interior holds the reins.''
   Lehman said that the secretary cannot serve as the nation's
``chief park ranger'' when his other duties also make him ``the
chief miner, chief oil-driller, chief cattle grazer and chief water
developer.''
   Lagomarsino said the plan is unconstitutional, ``completely
unworkable'' and a ``dangerous precedent'' because it creates a
virtually independent entity within a Cabinet department.
   Rep. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, said that ``this legislation is the
worst kind of micromanagement. The country does not need a law
creating a new bureaucracy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
