<HEAD>Mayor Rescinds Order Saying He Didn't Mean It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WADLEY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayor who told police officers to shoot
youngsters to stop them from brawling with sticks in a city park
rescinded the order Wednesday, saying he simply wanted to get the
attention of the ``hoodlums.''
   Mayor B.A. Johnson said he issued the order to ``shoot from the
waist down'' because youths from Wadley and nearby towns were
turning the 12-acre Hope Williams Memorial Park into a fighting
ring.
   ``I had not intended (for police) to shoot them anyway. It was
issued temporarily. I didn't think it would take very long for
those young people to get the idea we meant business,'' Johnson
said.
   ``It is merely to warn and to threaten and to let them know they
are not going to take over the city.''
   He said he'd learned ``some of my people are embarrassed'' by
the order. ``All and all, it is a thing that will fade away,'' he
added.
   Johnson, who once ordered police to shoot burglars and also
ordered them to shoot stray dogs, said as part of the attempt to
stop brawls in the park the fine for fighting was going to be
increased from $71.50 to $125.
</TEXT>
