<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Crash-DrugRunning     07-28 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Drug Running,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane In Fatal Crash Linked To Drug Running</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cargo plane that crashed last week in
Louisiana, killing three crew members, previously was used to
deliver drugs to Michigan and has been linked to deliveries of aid
to the Contras, a TV station reported Wednesday.
   The four-engine DC-6 plane, which crashed July 20 about 50 miles
south of New Orleans, had been used in a $45 million delivery of
cocaine and marijuana to Grosse Ile, a community near Detroit,
WXYZ-TV reported.
   The station, citing information gained from the federal
government through the Freedom of Information Act, said the plane
was owned by Michael Palmer, an official with Vortex, an aircraft
sales and leasing company that has been linked to shipments of aid
to the Contras, the U.S.-backed rebels in Nicaragua.
   The aircraft was being leased for the flight from San Salvador,
El Salvador, to New Orleans by TACA, a Salvadoran airline.
   It was carrying 22,000 pounds of assorted cargo when it crashed
into a drainage canal, officials said.
   Cargo included seafood, handicrafts, lingerie, plants and
electronics, according to Gary Mascaro, TACA cargo manager at the
New Orleans International Airport.
   TACA said the plane was owned by Universal Air Equipment Leasing
Inc. of Miami and was operated by Fiorelli Crews of Miami. The
three men killed were from Miami.
   Palmer, an official with Vortex, told a Senate hearing in April
that he flew supplies to the Contras under a $96,000 contract
awarded in early 1986 by the Nicaraguan Humanitarian Assistance
Office, part of the State Department.
   Palmer testified at the time that he never worked for the CIA.
   Records from the State Department office show Vortex was one of
about a half-dozen air freight companies used by the State
Department and was first contracted for deliveries on Jan. 10, 1986.
   The Washington Post has reported that Vortex delivered
non-lethal aid directly to the Contras inside Nicaragua on three or
four flights.
   The plane, which has had a number of different identifying tail
numbers, was seized briefly by federal agents in September 1987
after it arrived at Grosse Ile Municipal Airport with a load of
drugs.
   Palmer, a pilot who was on board the plane at the time of the
bust, said he was acting as a government informant to help federal
officials catch drug runners.
</TEXT>
