<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-28 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>B-1B Able To Perform Only Half Its Intended Tasks, Pentagon Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force is scaling back its expectations
for the B-1B bomber after concluding it will probably be able to
only half the job it was designed for, the director of testing for
the Defense Department says.
   John E. Krings told a meeting of two House Armed Services
subcommittees that the new plane, already behind schedule, has
problems in the electronic equipment that enables it to fly close
to the ground and avoid or confuse enemy radar.
   ``It will accomplish about 50 percent in terms of the gross
assessment of what it was supposed to do,'' he testified on
Wednesday.
   Because of the problems combatting radar, the Air Force is
focusing on a narrower range of threats for the 100 B-1Bs it is
buying, hoping to develop reliable performance against enemy
anti-aircraft weapons, he said. ``It's better to have success in a
limited area than no success in a large area,'' he told the panels.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congressional Delegate And Aide Charged In Payroll Fraud Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors are alleging in court papers that
American Samoa's delegate to Congress and his administrative
assistant conspired to defraud the government of more than $130,000
by putting ghost employees on their payroll.
   An eight-page information filed in conjunction with a plea
agreement reached with the two defendants said Fofo I.F. Sunia and
his aide falsely certified to the House finance office that people
living in American Samoa and elsewhere were employed in Sunia's
Washington congressional office.
   The document filed in U.S. District Court on Wednesday said
Sunia and assistant Matthew K. Iuli used the money from the scheme
to entertain constituents, pay election campaign expenses and make
house and car loan payments.
   U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens said in a statement that Sunia and
Iuli will appear in court to enter guilty pleas to the information
``in the very near future.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>NASA Poorly Prepared To Predict Weather For Space Launches, Panel</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Says
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA needs to build a system to more
accurately predict weather conditions at the moment spacecraft are
launched from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida, a new study says.
   The study by the National Research Council released Wednesday
analyzed the system used by the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration to protect its spacecraft from lightning and other
adverse weather. It concluded that major improvements are needed in
organization and in instruments.
   NASA, the panel said, ``has been poorly organized to provide
weather support and the result is a system that is less than
state-of-the-science,'' the report said. It said unless
improvements in the weather forecasting system are made at the
Kennedy center, ``weather will loom larger as a threat to a
rejuvenated and accelerated space flight program.''
   John A. Ernst, director of NASA's weather support office, said
the space agency asked for the study and has taken ``some initial
steps'' on the recommendations.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Passes `Dire Emergency' Money for Remainder of This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has approved $264.4 million in
supplemental spending to prevent a variety of programs from running
out of money in the closing days of fiscal 1988.
   The ``Dire Emergency Supplemental Appropriation'' passed
Wednesday will provide funding for programs ranging from drug
interdiction efforts by the Coast Guard to repairing prisons
damaged by rebellious Cuban prisoners.
   Approved by a 357-54 vote, the measure now goes to the Senate.
   Other programs in line for cash infusions include black lung
disease benefits for former coal miners; Small Business
Administration disaster assistance; flood disaster assistance; and
drought relief administration.
