<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-PLO     07-28 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-PLO,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Leader Calls For Talks With Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent pro-PLO leader from the occupied
territories called for direct talks with Israeli representatives
and said he would even speak with hard-line Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir.
   In a rare dialogue with Israeli peace activists, Faisal Husseini
said the Palestinians' ``dream'' is to have Israel as well as the
occupied lands, but they are willing to compromise and split the
land to end the ``nightmares.''
   ``As a Palestinian, my problem is with the Israelis _ so I must
speak with them,'' Husseini said Wednesday. ``So we're willing to
speak with Shamir, not because he is a a man of peace ... but
because we know this man was chosen by Israel to represent them.''
   As he spoke, dozens of anti-Arab demonstrators stood outside and
protested against the forum, sponsored by the broad-based Israeli
peace movement, Peace Now. The Palestine Liberation Organization is
banned in Israel, and the protesters held signs saying, ``Peace Now
is a knife in the back.''
   The PLO refuses to recognize Israel, but a recent document drawn
up by PLO spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif called for direct talks with
Israel under the auspices of an international conference.
   The document was criticized by extremist factions of the PLO.
   Husseini is a popular figure among residents of the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin once called him the leading PLO representative in the areas.
He seemed to back Abu Sharif's policy.
   Israeli listeners asked him whether Palestinians will be
satisfied with a state alongside Israel and not try to conquer the
Jewish state itself.
   ``Indeed, I do have a dream,'' he said.
   ``But I am not willing to impose my dreams upon my fellow men,''
he said. ``We will have to give up a lot of dreams _ but also a lot
of nightmares.''
   The statements were greeted with loud applause.
   Husseini, director of the East Jerusalem-based Arab Studies
Institute, was released in July from an Israeli jail, where he had
been held without trial for nine months.
   Before the anti-occupation uprising began Dec. 8, he was
involved in clandestine talks with Moshe Amirav, a former member of
the right-wing Likud Party. Likud, which is fiercely opposed to the
PLO, kicked Amirav out of the party over the meetings.
   Amirav, leftist parliamentarian Yair Tzaban and Palestinian
journalist Redwan Abu Ayash, who was also released from jail
without trial recently, addressed the unusual gathering with
Husseini.
   It was the first public dialogue between Israelis and
Palestinians in Israel since the uprising started.
   Tzaban, of the small socialist Mapam party, called on Israel to
acknowledge Palestinian nationalism and negotiate with Palestinian
representatives. He lashed out at Labor party leader Shimon Peres
for speaking as though Israel could simply return the territories
to Jordan.
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East
War.
   In recent weeks, Peres has indicated Israel will speak to the
Palestinians if Jordan's King Hussein is not willing to come to the
negotiating table.
   ``Israel doesn't even need peace with Jordan,'' Tzaban said.
``Israel needs peace with the Palestinians, and you can't get that
by negotiating with Swedes, Americans, Norwegians or Jordanians _
only by negotiating with the Palestinians.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
