<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Drought     07-28 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Drought,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Urges Drought Lawmakers: Drop $300 Million Boon for Dairy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is speeding $6.9 billion in drought
assistance toward President Reagan's desk, with Agriculture
Secretary Richard Lyng calling on lawmakers to jettison a $300
million benefit for milk producers.
   ``We strongly object to the provision which would increase the
price support level for milk and urge the House to strike this
provision from the bill on the floor,'' Lyng said Wednesday.
   In a letter to House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika''
de la Garza, D-Texas, the secretary dismissed dairy industry claims
that the price boost is needed to head off a looming milk shortage.
And he placed the cost of the increase at $300 million _ more than
double the House estimate.
   ``We do not expect milk shortages next year,'' Lyng said as both
the House and Senate prepared to act on their versions of the
measure to provide aid to farmers hard hit by the drought.
   Farm lawmakers plan to meet in a House-Senate conference
committee next week to fashion the final product and send it to
Reagan before Aug. 11, when Congress flees Washington's summer heat.
   At the core of both versions is a payment program that would
provide drought-stricken farmers with compensation equal to 65
percent of crop losses beyond 35 percent of their expected harvest.
The plan also would streamline and expand federal feed benefits for
dairy and livestock producers.
   Under heavy fire from the Reagan administration _ and a host of
rival farm and business groups _ is a House provision that would
increase the dairy price support level on Oct. 1 by 50 cents for
each 100 pounds of milk to $11.10.
   Both bills would cancel a 50-cent cut in the price-support level
that otherwise would be automatic under the farm program.
   Rep. James Jeffords, R-Vt., sponsor of the increase, and Rep.
Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, have been urging the idea as a way of
heading off a milk shortage next year.
   Anticipating an intense fight over the Jeffords provision, dairy
supporters have readied a fallback provision that would put in
place a temporary price-support increase. The plan sponsored by
Reps. Steve Gunderson, R-Wis., and Tim Penny, D-Minn., was
reportedly gaining steam in the House.
   Meanwhile, Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a persistent critic of
excess spending on agricultural programs, called for barring
farmers with $1 million in revenue from receiving drought benefits
provided by the legislation.
   ``I'm suggesting that if they are that successful they probably
don't need a subsidy,'' the Brooklyn lawmaker said. Schumer said
his amendment would deny benefits to farmers if their gross
revenues totaled $1 million, even if their net earnings were far
less.
   Under the relief bill, payments would be made for losses of a
wide variety of crops, including an estimated $150 million for
tobacco.
   Tobacco-state lawmakers acknowledged that it thus represented a
step away from the 1983 compromise between farm lawmakers and
anti-smoking forces under which the tobacco price-support system is
supposed to have no net cost to the taxpayer.
   ``It's because of the special situation of the drought,'' said
Rep. Charles Rose, D-N.C., chairman of the House tobacco and
peanuts subcommittee.
   ``To be providing $150 million because a crop that kills people
is damaged and spending less than 1 percent of that on educating
people about the hazards of tobacco is really an example of having
priorities upside down,'' said John F. Banzhaf II, director of
Action on Smoking and Health, one of the nation's major
anti-smoking organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     07-28 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC-Journal Poll Finds 18-Point Dukakis Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
boosted his lead over George Bush to 18 points following the
Democratic National Convention, according to a new poll.
   The results of the NBC News-Wall Street Journal national survey
released Wednesday showed Dukakis with his biggest lead of the
campaign and followed similar results in polls conducted in the
afterglow of the Democratic convention.
   Dukakis drew 50 percent support to 32 percent for Bush in the
survey of 1,770 registered voters. Dukakis had led by 10 points,
46-36, in a pre-convention NBC-Journal poll.
   The national nominating conventions often provide candidates a
boost in the polls, especially when the conventions proceed as
harmoniously as the Democrats' did last week. The bounce usually
settles as the race proceeds.
   The newest survey has a margin of error of 3 percentage points
in either direction.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Republican Chief Predicts Most Negative Presidential Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican National Committee Chairman
Frank Fahrenkopf predicted in a televised interview that the 1988
presidential race ``could be one of the most negative campaigns in
U.S. history.''
   Fahrenkopf made the comment when asked Wednesday about Democrat
Michael Dukakis' claim that Americans are ``embarrassed and
ashamed'' by the Reagan administration.
   ``People who live in glass houses shouldn't throw stones,'' said
Fahrenkopf. ``The Democrats don't have a lock on honesty in
government any more than our party does, and the American people
know that.''
   Fahrenkopf said that if Dukakis is so upset about conduct of top
Republicans such as resigned Attorney General Edwin Meese III, the
Democratic should also call for the resignation of such prominent
Democrats as House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas.
