<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PinkMutation     07-28 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pink Mutation,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Of Fur Mutation In Mice Could Aid Understanding Of Skin
Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigation of an unusual genetic
mutation that changes the pigmentation of mice could offer insights
into the development of a deadly form of skin cancer in humans, a
researcher says.
   Murray Brilliant, a geneticist at the Jackson Laboratory in Bar
Harbor, said Wednesday the technique he developed to study the
mutation in mice also could be used to study genetic mutations in
humans.
   ``It's a way to get at many mutations of potential medical
importance to humans,'' said Brilliant.
   The mutation in mice affects the pigmentation of cells called
melanocytes. Studies of the mutation may help explain how
melanocytes develop normally, he said.
   ``You have to know how this works normally to know what goes
wrong in cancer,'' said Brilliant, who did the research in
connection with Eva Eicher, another geneticist at Jackson
Laboratory.
   When the growth of melanocytes goes awry in humans, the result
is melanoma, a skin cancer that is often fatal.
   Furthermore, Brilliant said, the study of the mutation in the
melanocyte pigmentation gene could help researchers understand
other genetic defects.
   ``The information from this line of research is being applied to
gain access to a closely linked gene which, when mutated, causes
cleft palate in mice,'' Brilliant said. Whether that will help
explain the occurrence of cleft palate in humans is not known,
Brilliant said.
   The mutation Brilliant studied in mice is called the pink
unstable mutation. It has the highest mutation rate of any gene
known in mammals.
   Up to one in 10 of the offspring of a parent with the pink
unstable mutation will suffer a new mutation of the gene, Brilliant
said.
   The gene is related to pigmentation in the mice. When the gene
is normal, mice are black. When the gene is mutated, the mice are
cream-colored with pink eyes.
   But one in 10 to one in 40 of the offspring of the
cream-colored, pink-eyed mice will have black patches of fur,
Brilliant said, as the gene mutates again, reverting back to its
original form.
   If such mottled mice are bred again, some of their offspring
will be black as the gene further reverts to its normal form.
   Melanoma is caused by mutations in genes that affect the
development of pigment-carrying cells, and thus these mouse studies
may someday help doctors understand how melanoma arises, Brilliant
said.
   Brilliant studied the mutation using a new technique he
developed in which he looks for variations in repeating pieces of
genetic material that are scattered throughout the mouse's genes.
   Similar examination of repeating pieces of genetic material in
human genes can be used to find genetic mutations in humans, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
