<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     07-28 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Plans to `Open Up' Personal Side in Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said in an
interview published today that he plans to ``open up and share''
his personal side in the presidential campaign to counter his image
as an ``Ivy League elitist.''
   Bush, the certain Republican nominee, told the editorial board
of USA Today that his family life has been ``something so private
and so special that I haven't felt like sharing it.''
   ``At this level of American politics, I have to open up a little
and share, so at our convention, you will see five Bush children,
their five spouses and our 10 grandchildren,'' Bush said in the
interview, which took place Wednesday.
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis ``speaks
Spanish. I wish I did,'' Bush said, ``But I have three
grandchildren, my blood coursing through their veins, who are half
Mexican. I've never shared this.''
   He said the thoughts about his family's public role were raised
by the recent Democratic National Convention, where Dukakis, former
contender Jesse Jackson and others spoke of family values and
appeared publicly with relatives.
   ``We saw a good show there in terms of family. Very good, from
the heart, genuine,'' Bush said. ``I haven't felt too comfortable
talking about my family.''
   Bush said the public perceives him as an Ivy League elitist, but
he resists that mold. ``For example, I like pork rinds, but that
doesn't fit the mold. I play horse shoes.''
   Asked about Sen. Edward M. Kennedy's refrain at the Democratic
convention of ``Where was George,'' Bush said he was on the job.
``I was up at the United Nations, laying in perspective what ought
to happen: The Iranians doing that which they had been unwilling to
do, recognize the U.N. resolution and talk peace.''
   Bush represented the United States government last week at a
United Nations Security Council meeting on the U.S. downing of an
Iranian commercial airliner carrying 290 people. Iran has since
said it will recognize a U.N. resolution calling for a cease fire
in the Iran-Iraq war.
   Bush dismissed Democratic criticism of his role in the
Iran-Contra affair as ``politics, nothing more.''
   ``Remember the ridicule about `moderates' in Iran? Now others
are talking about the moderates in Iran,'' Bush told the newspaper.
   The vice president also called Jackson a ``loose cannon'' when
asked whether Jackson should have a role as an envoy to free
hostages in the Middle East.
   ``It shouldn't happen. We're talking about very sensitive
foreign policy. The administration is empowered to conduct those
negotiations at the United Nations. We don't need any loose cannons
rolling around the deck,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
