<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Thatcher     07-28 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Thatcher,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A U.S. of Europe? Prime Minister Says Not In Her Lifetime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said she won't
see a United States of Europe and hopes it will never come to pass,
and she rejected calls for uniform taxes and a central bank for the
12-nation European Economic Community.
   Mrs. Thatcher, in a radio interview Wednesday, said officials
proposing a federal government for Western Europe ``spend far too
much time talking about these airy-fairy ideas.
   ``They say `Let's have European union.' I say `What do you mean,
because I can't see any of you dissolving your own countries into a
United States of Europe','' Mrs. Thatcher said.
   The 62-year-old prime minister said a United States of Europe
would ``never come in my lifetime and I hope never at all.''
   It was her most outspoken criticism yet of what she regards as
impractical overenthusiasm for a European federation. She spoke on
the British Broadcasting Corp.'s ``Jimmy Young Show,'' a mixture of
chatty interviews and popular music aimed mainly at housewives.
   Jacques Delors, president of the European Economic Community's
Brussels-based executive commission, refused to comment on the
interview.
   Delors, in a speech to the European Parliament on July 6,
predicted that within 10 years 80 percent of social and economic
legislation in the EEC area would be passed on a Europe-wide basis
rather than in the national parliaments of the member states.
   But Mrs. Thatcher, long accused of an insular attitude toward
the rest of Europe, said in the Wednesday radio interview: ``I
think he was wrong. I think he went over the top. I don't think he
should have said it.''
   Last week, the prime minister replaced Britain's EEC
commissioner, Lord Cockfield, who was masterminding an alignment of
sales taxes throughout the trading bloc _ a move Mrs. Thatcher
opposed.
   Alignment of taxes is part of preparations for 1992, when the
EEC is due to become a single market without trade barriers.
   As for an EEC central bank, she said, that would mean
surrendering ``fundamental economic decisions to another country. .
.. That I will not do.''
   Mrs. Thatcher argued she is simply being practical about the
limits of a European union, which she said could never function
like the United States.
   ``The whole history of the two places is entirely different,''
she said. ``It is not possible to have a United States of Europe.
What is possible is for the 12 countries of Europe steadily to work
more closely together on things we do better together, so that we
can trade better together.''
   Opinion polls show British voters are less enthusiastic about
closer ties within the EEC than, for example, the West Germans or
the French.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
