<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Teamsters-Mob     07-28 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters-Mob,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: FBI Memo Shows New Teamsters New Leader May Have Had Mob
Links</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Teamsters President William J. McCarthy
said in a 1984 conversation that he needed permission from a
reputed organized crime boss before he could advance in the union,
the Los Angeles Times reported today.
   In addition, McCarthy's name was mentioned at a meeting between
reputed New York mobster Anthony ``Fat Tony'' Salerno and alleged
Cleveland mob figure John ``Peanuts'' Tronolone, in a discussion
secretly monitored by the FBI, the newspaper said.
   The report was the first public indication of any links between
organized crime and McCarthy, who was chosen a few weeks ago by the
union's executive board to succeed Jackie Presser as president.
Presser died this month while under indictment on payroll padding
charges.
   McCarthy had told Presser he wanted to be general
secretary-treasurer of the union, but needed the approval and
backing of Raymond L.S. Patriarca, the late reputed head of the New
England mob, according to an FBI memo obtained by the Times.
   The April 19, 1984, memo was addressed to Oliver B. Revell,
then-assistant director in charge of the FBI's criminal
investigative division. It said that Presser, an informant on mob
matters for 10 years, had told FBI agents that he had the
conversation with McCarthy in early April 1984.
   McCarthy has declined to comment about the matter. A spokesman,
Duke Zeller, said Wednesday that McCarthy may have a statement this
week.
   The FBI memo has remained secret since it was drafted but is
expected to be introduced soon in federal court by government
lawyers to help support a Justice Department lawsuit that seeks the
ouster of top Teamsters leaders on grounds of corruption. The
lawsuit was filed the day Presser died.
   An FBI transcript of the electronically monitored meeting held
in May 1984 quotes Tronolone as telling Salerno that McCarthy might
be worthy of Salerno's support for secretary-treasurer, considered
the second most powerful position in the union, the Times said.
   In this meeting and another FBI-monitored meeting in June 1984,
Salerno listens to brief talk about McCarthy but does not indicate
he has reached any conclusion or will back anybody for the job, the
Times said.
   Presser eventually selected Weldon L. Mathis of Atlanta as
secretary-treasuer. The newspaper, citing unidentified sources,
said Presser personally cleared that appointment with James E.
Moody, an FBI official to whom Presser sometimes reported in his
role as an informant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
