<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-USFilm     07-28 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-US Film,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Officials, Public Get Glimpse of Two Popular U.S. Films</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two popular American films are showing in the
Soviet capital this week as part of a project aimed at improving
understanding between the superpowers at top governmental levels.
   ``E.T.'' got a warm reception when it made its Soviet debut
Wednesday night before a select audience of 450, and also at a
packed showing later for the general public at the 2,400-seat
Oktyabr cinema, said Andrei Semenov of the Soviet Filmmakers Union.
   Members of the Supreme Soviet, the national parliament, were
invited for the first screening of the Steven Spielberg fantasy
about a relationship between a young boy and a displaced alien
creature.
   The second American film, to be screened tonight, is ``Coming
Home,'' in which actor Jon Voight won an Academy Award for his
portrayal of a paraplegic Vietnam War veteran.
   In Washington, members of Congress were invited to watch two
Soviet films that have drawn more than 2 million Soviet viewers
over the past month _ ``The Cold Summer of '53'' and ``Commissar.''
   ``Cold Summer'' depicts the trauma that followed dictator Josef
V. Stalin's death, when political prisoners and criminals alike
were freed in an amnesty. ``Commissar'' was banned in the Soviet
Union for 20 years, presumably for its sympathetic portrayal of a
Jewish family.
   The exchange was arranged by a private group of filmmakers from
both countries who call their joint project the American-Soviet
Film Initiative.
   ``This film exchange is a great opportunity for the leaders of
our two nations to see how films in our respective societies deal
with controversial issues,'' said U.S. director Lawrence J.
Schiller, chairman of the initiative group.
</TEXT>
