<DOCNO> AP880728-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Press     07-28 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Press,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Suspends Plans Requiring Journalists To Register</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today
temporarily suspended regulations that would require some
journalists to register or face penalties that include imprisonment.
   The regulations, which were to take effect Sunday, drew heavy
criticism from media groups here and abroad that accused the white
minority government of making further inroads against press freedom.
   Stoffel Botha, minister of home affairs, said the registration
of journalists ``remains a matter of grave concern for the
government,'' but that the regulations had been temporarily
suspended for ``practical considerations.''
   He said the regulations would be reviewed, but gave no
indication when he would make a final decision.
   The broadly worded strictures say anyone carrying out
``news-agency'' business must register with the government or face
a 10-year prison term or a $8,500 fine.
   Lawyers say the definition of a ``news agency'' is so broad that
major commerical papers that exchange stories, church and political
groups that publish newsletters, and businesses that issue regular
press statements on their operations could be included if the
government so desired.
   South Africa's largest news agency, the South African Press
Association, and all major international agencies, including The
Associated Press, were exempted from the regulations.
   But local journalists who supply news on a part-time basis to
some of the world's major news organizations would be required to
register if they work for more than one employer, which many do.
   Under the regulations, Botha would be able to remove journalists
from the registration list and prevent those people from working in
the profession if he objects to their reporting.
   Botha already has broad censorship powers that allow him to
close down publications and expel foreign journalists.
   The latest regulations appear aimed at the small, local news
agencies around the country. But most news organizations operating
in South Africa receive reports from the local agencies and would
be affected as well.
   Botha has accused the local agencies of endangering public
safety by reporting unfavorably on police activities, forced
removals of poor blacks and labor disputes in rural areas that are
not covered regularly by any other news organizations.
   The Foreign Correspondents Association of South Africa has said
that even journalists not required to register would be
``compromised'' because they would be seen as having favored status
with the government.
   State-of-emergency regulations already in force restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of
detainees, some forms of protest and a broad range of statement the
government considers subversive.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FalseResume     07-28 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-False Resume,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director of Illinois Arts Council Admits False Resume Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive director of the Illinois Arts
Council has admitted making false claims on the resume he used when
seeking the $55,000-a-year post, and has been placed on an unpaid
leave of absence.
   John P. Riley, 38, claimed on the resume that he had been a
``principal dancer'' with New York's Joffrey Ballet, and that he
was a ``guest artist'' on a public television series, ``Dance in
America,'' in the 1970s.
   In an interview with the Chicago Tribune on Wednesday, Riley
initially maintained that he had appeared with Joffrey in national
tours, but later admitted he had never been a member of the company
in any capacity, only attended workshops run by the troupe, the
newspaper reported today.
   ``I was never featured in ``Dance in America,'' he said. ``The
Joffrey was the one that did `Dance in America.' So I lied.''
   Riley was acting director for several months before being named
last month to replace Adrienne Nescott Hirsch, who resigned to work
for the National Endowment for the Arts. Riley had been the
Illinois agency's deputy director since 1985.
   Riley said it was the first time he had used false information
to get a job.
   ``I'm really embarrassed,'' he said. ``I shouldn't have done
it.''
   The board of the state agency put Riley on unpaid leave
Wednesday, officials said.
   ``Truthfulness is the issue,'' said Shirley R. Madigan, board
chairwoman. She said a board executive committee may discuss how to
deal with the matter by Friday.
   The council runs on an annual budget of $8 million, of which
about $6.5 million is distributed to 2,000 individuals and groups
statewide. The 35 members of the council's supervisory board are
appointed by the governor.
   Riley, a Worcester, Mass., native who graduated from Holy Cross
University in 1972, said in A 1985 resume he worked at a Boston
department store as a full-time sales manager during some of the
time he later claimed to be with Joffrey, the Tribune said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
