<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Thailand 1stLd-Writethru a0485 07-28 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Businessman And Ex-General Announces His Nomination
For Premier</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with students calling off
further rallies. Pick up 6th pvs `Chatichai's Chart...'; ADDS 3
grafs at bottom with detail</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative former general and
wealthy businessman today announced his nomination as prime
minister after Prem Tinsulanonda declined to seek a return to the
post he's held for eight years.
   Chatichai Choonhavan, 66, the likely prime minister-to-be, told
a news conference: ``The five political parties that will form the
coalition government have agreed to support the leader of the
largest party and as that party's leader I am pleased to accept the
nomination.''
   Students and others who for three days staged rallies opposing
Prem's non-elected status welcomed Chatichai's announcement and
said they will stop protesting.
   Chatichai, one of five acting deputy prime ministers, said he
met with army chief Gen. Chavalit Yongchaiyudh and ``got military
support.'' He would not elaborate, but the military traditionally
has wielded considerable power in Thai politics.
   If Chatichai succeeds Prem, he is expected to follow a
conservative pro-Western policy and emphasize economic development.
   Prem, 67, made no public statement today. On Wednesday, the
acting prime minister was quoted as saying he was stepping down for
personal reasons.
   He turned down an offer from the leaders of the five key
political parties, which formed a loose pro-Prem coalition after no
single party could capture a majority in Sunday's parliamentary
elections.
   Chatichai's Chart Thai (Thai Nation) Party and the coalition
partners hold 215 of the 357 seats in the lower house of
Parliament. The other four parties in the coalition are the
Democrat Party, the Social Action Party, the Rassadorn Party and
the United Democracy Party.
   Chatichai said he will submit to Parliament a list of 215
coalition signatures that show support for his succession to Prem.
   Parliament President Ukrit Mongkolnavin said the list would be
handed to constitutional monarch King Bhumibol Adulyadej later
today for approval. A royal decree announcing the new prime
minister was expected today or Friday.
   Chatichai held several ministerial portfolios in past
governments, including those of foreign minister and minister of
industry.
   Prem, a former army commander, brought stability during his
tenure and until Wednesday did not say whether he would return or
not. He has been criticized for indecision and a willingness to
fashion compromises.
   Student leader Mana Treelayatewat said there will be no further
anti-Prem demonstrations.
   ``Chatichai represents the people who voted him into the
government and we respect that,'' Mana said.
   Mana, the vice secretary-general of the 100,000-member Students
Federation of Thailand, said in a statement that for the first time
in 10 years ``democracy can be developed and mature in Thailand. We
have reached our goal: premiership from direct elections, not
nominations.''
</TEXT>
