<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShootToStop     07-28 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shoot To Stop,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Rescinds Shoot-to-Stop Order, Says He Didn't Mean It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WADLEY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor who directed police to
``shoot-to-stop'' fighting in a park has rescinded the order,
saying it was a scare tactic to prevent hoodlums from taking over
the city.
   ``I was going to lift the order anyway,'' Mayor B.A. Johnson
said Wednesday. ``I just did it a day early. I think we got our
point across.''
   After a Sunday brawl among youths using sticks as weapons,
Johnson told police officers to ``shoot from the waist down''
anyone caught fighting in the park.
   He said he issued the order to get the attention of ``hoodlums''
from the Wadley area who were making a fighting ring of the 12-acre
Hope Williams Memorial Park in this east-central Georgia city of
2,500 residents.
   Johnson, who once ordered police to shoot burglars and also
ordered them to shoot stray dogs, said as part of the attempt to
stop brawls in the park the fine for fighting was going to be
increased from $71.50 to $125.
   ``Certainly they (police) did not plan to shoot anybody,''
Johnson said Wednesday. ``I had not intended to shoot them anyway.
It was issued temporarily. I didn't think it would take very long
for those young people to get the idea we meant business.
   ``It is merely to warn and to threaten and to let them know they
are not going to take over the city.''
</TEXT>
