<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-US     07-28 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese-Americans Plan Joint MIA Searches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Vietnam appear
ready to intensify efforts to search together and account for 1,761
Americans still missing from the Vietnam War, the U.S. Embassy said
today.
   An embassy statement said experts from both countries meeting
over the past four days discussed plans to work ``on concerted
efforts within the next three months to make significant progress''
to resolve the divisive issue.
   The two sides, which met in Hanoi, reviewed ``arrangements for
joint investigative, survey and excavation activities'' during the
period.
   The statement described the meetings as ``quite productive, and
we look forward to greatly expanded cooperation in coming months.''
   Members of the U.S. team, which returned from Hanoi today, will
discuss implementation of the joint searches in Washington, the
statement said.
   The Vietnam War ended in April 1975 with a communist victory
over the U.S.-backed South Vietnamese government.
   In recent months, Vietnam has made significant moves to resolve
the MIA issue. It said this month that it would try to resolve 70
``priority cases'' this year and welcome more joint excavations of
warplane crash sites.
   Facing a ruinous economy and shunned by the non-communist world
for its invasion of Cambodia, Hanoi has been making efforts at
building some bridges to the United States and other western and
Asian nations.
   Hanoi has withdrawn some of its forces from Cambodia and
participated in the Indonesian-sponsored talks to find a political
solution to the Cambodian conflict.
   The U.S. technical team to the Hanoi talks was led by Lt. Col.
Joe Harvey of the Joint Casualty Resolution Center and was joined
by representatives of the U.S. Central Identification Laboratory.
Both units are based in Hawaii.
   The talks were agreed upon during a meeting at the United
Nations June 8 between Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach of Vietnam
and retired Gen. John W. Vessey, who last August reached an
agreement with Hanoi for an accelerated search for MIAs, especially
the 70 on Washington's priority list.
   The United States in turn promised to consider Vietnam's
humanitarian problems.
   The priority cases are those the United States considers most
easily resolvable because it says the Vietnamese have information
on them. These include cases where there are photographs of airmen
taken after their capture during the war.
   Since the Vessey agreement, Hanoi has on five occasions turned
over to the United States remains it identified as those of U.S.
servicemen killed in the war. The last turnover, involving 25
remains, was on July 13.
   Since the war ended, Vietnam has returned more than 150 sets of
remains that the army laboratory confirmed as those of Americans.
Vietnam says it has returned the remains of 241 Americans and
information on 45 others whose remains were ``determined to be no
longer in existence.''
   Vietnam has denied charges by some American private citizens
that it is holding live Americans as prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0738EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-China     07-28 0134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-China,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Proposes Mainland Chinese Visits To Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official said today that
proposed legislation would allow people from mainland China to
visit Taiwan for two months if their relatives here are gravely ill
or die.
   Director Wang Yuan-jen, director of the Exit and Entry Bureau,
said the proposal would be submitted soon to the Cabinet for
consideration.
   Under the plan, mainland Chinese would be allowed to visit their
spouses, parents and children if their relatives in Taiwan can
present documents to prove illness or death in the family, Wang
said.
   The Nationalists have maintained no official contacts with the
Chinese Communists since 1949 after losing a civil war on the
mainland.
   They eased a ban last year to allow Taiwanese to visit China for
family reunions.
</TEXT>
