<DOCNO> AP880728-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Riots     07-28 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Riots,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Closed Following Student Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities closed one of the nation's
six universities indefinitely following violent clashes between
rival student political groups, police said today.
   At least 10 students at Rajshahi University were injured
Wednesday in the clashes and nearly 100 dormitory rooms were
ransacked, police said. The students also set fire to furniture and
books, they said.
   The trouble erupted when more than 100 supporters of the
fundamentalist Jamaat-e-Islami party raided the campus and clashed
with supporters of an eight-party alliance led by the country's
main opposition leader, Sheikh Hasina, a district official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Jamaat supporters were armed with iron rods, sticks and knives.
Three students were hospitalized, he said. One was reported in
critical condition.
   ``We have closed the university for the safety and security of
the students and the campus,'' Amanullah Ahmed, university vice
chancellor, said by telephone.
   Examinations scheduled for next month were postponed.
   The university at Rajshahi, 168 miles northwest of Dhaka, has
more than 11,000 students.
   Bangladesh's universities often are sites of political unrest.
   Opposition parties have been agitating since November to oust
President Hussain Muhammad Ershad, a former army general who seized
power in a coup in 1982.
</TEXT>
