<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RedCross-FDA     07-28 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Red Cross-FDA,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Cited For Errors At Blood Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Cross laboratory at St. Louis says it
has closed for reorganization after being cited by the Food and
Drug Administration for more than 150 errors, mostly involving AIDS
and hepatitis screening.
   The faults were detected between January 1987 and June 1988,
Brian McDonough, chief operating officer of the Red Cross St. Louis
Bi-State Chapter, said Wednesday.
   He said 152 blood donations collected during the 18-month period
required further investigation and of that total, 96 donors were
re-evaluated for AIDS or hepatitis.
   ``All 96 re-tested negative to initial screening tests, and
medical history evaluations determined that none were involved in
high-risk activities,'' he said. But he said five showed
``indeterminant'' results.
   These donors, and the six patients who received their blood
products, will be monitored for the next few months to determine
any health hazards, McDonough said. He said the donors and patients
involved had been contacted.
   Other FDA citations involved faults in computer systems,
administrative systems and records.
   McDonough said the mistakes were mostly a result of human error
and said disciplinary measures have been taken.
   ``With the help of the FDA we have made appropriate
corrections,'' he said. ``To protect the health of patients who
rely on Red Cross blood, we are committed to a standard of zero
errors.''
   McDonough said the Red Cross will temporarily transfer its lab
work to a private laboratory in Round Lake, Ill., and a quality
control office will be established under the direction of a Red
Cross vice president.
   The Missouri-Illinois region is one of 56 regional blood service
operations in the country.
   The Red Cross supplies half of the nation's need for blood and
blood products, McDonough said. Each year more than 4 million
volunteers donate over 6 million units of blood to more than 1.5
million patients, he said.
</TEXT>
