<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Jordan-WestBank     07-28 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jordan-West Bank,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordan Cancels Big West Bank Development Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it was canceling
a $1.3 billion development plan for the Israeli-occupied West Bank,
which was part of Jordan before 1967.
   The move followed reports in regional newspapers that King
Hussein was dissociating himself from the Palestinian question.
   State-run Radio Jordan said the kingdom also decided to
``dissolve all development and tender committees for this plan.''
   The five-year West Bank development plan was set up in 1986 by
joint agreement between the Jordanian government and the PLO. It
was to provide schools, water and agriculture projects and welfare.
   The West Bank was under Jordanian rule until Israel captured it
during the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. However, Jordan continued to pay
the salaries and pensions of many goverment employees there, and
West Bank representatives sit in the kingdom's Parliament.
   The uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, which began Dec. 8, has given new international
prominence to the Palestinian issue.
   On Wednesday, the Saudi Arabian newspaper Al-Sharq Al-Awsat
quoted Jordanian Prime Minister Zaid Rifai as saying ``decisive
developments'' in Jordanian-Palestinian relations were coming up.
   Rifai was quoted as saying the measures planned would be in
response to the wishes of the Palestine Liberation Organization and
the Arabs and sprang from Jordan's desire to give greater
responsibility to the Palestinians.
   On the same day, the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Qabas said royal court
Minister Marwan Qassem was the strongest candidate to head a new
Jordanian Cabinet at the start of radical changes in the Jordanian
administration.
   The comprehensive changes in Jordan would be made in light of a
decision by Hussein to dissociate himself from the Palestinian
question and let the PLO shoulder the responsibility, said the
newspaper, which is usually well-informed on Jordan.
   Al-Qabas, in its Amman-dated dispatch, said the changes could
include the appointment of Rifai, the prime minister, as personal
representative for the Jordanian monarch.
   The newspaper, in line with earlier reports in the Arab news
media, reported that Hussein would dissolve the two houses of
Parliament. The 60-member upper house includes 30 members from the
West Bank.
</TEXT>
