<2ND_LINE>PM-Polo Injury,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon Gets $6.3 Million For Hand Injured In Polo Lesson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beverly Hills oral surgeon who injured his
right hand in a fall from a horse during a polo lesson has accepted
a $6.3 million settlement.
   Dr. Andrew Glassman, 37, agreed to the terms Tuesday as his suit
against the operators of Los Angeles Equestrian Center was to be
heard by a jury. Attorney Tom Girardi said Glassman can no longer
practice surgery.
   Glassman was taking a private polo lesson in 1984 when he fell
off his rented horse. In the suit, he claimed that the center was
negligent because a saddle strap snapped and the saddle loosened as
he tried to hit the ball.
   The strap that broke had been repaired earlier with a staple
instead of stitching, the suit charged.
   Glassman's right hand suffered so much nerve damage that he can
no longer grasp anything without pain, Girardi said.
   Patrick Hast, an attorney for Equestrian Centers of America,
operator of the city-owned facility, said an economist and an
accountant were ready to testify that Glassman would have earned $7
million to $8 million during his lifetime if not for the injury.
