<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LandTrade 1stLd-Writethru a0435 07-28 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Land Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House OKs Land Swap _ Florida Swampland For Piece Of Downtown
Phoenix</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last 3 grafs pinpointing where Florida land is.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, over the protests of two
subcommittee chairmen, has given its blessing to a land deal that
would bring taxpayers 108,000 acres of Florida swampland for a
valuable piece of downtown Phoenix.
   Sent to the Senate on Wednesday was legislation to authorize the
exchange, which was negotiated initially by the Interior Department
and redrawn by Arizona lawmakers to bring their state a slice of
the action.
   The deal could cost the Treasury some $100 million, according to
Reps. Sidney Yates, D-Ill., chairman of the Appropriations interior
subcommitee, and George Miller, D-Calif., chairman of the Interior
water and power resources subcommittee.
   Miller and Yates came up on the losing end of the 281-125 vote
that approved the legislation sponsored principally by Interior
Committee chairman Morris Udall, D-Ariz., normally allied with
Miller on committee issues.
   The bill would authorize the Interior Department to complete a
complex deal to dispose of the 111-acre site of the Phoenix Indian
School, which the Reagan administration wants to close because of
declining enrollments.
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative wing of
Congress, has described the Phoenix land as perhaps the most
valuable undeveloped piece of urban real estate in the West.
   Under the plan, the Collier family interests of Florida would
get 68.4 acres of the Phoenix property in exchange for the Florida
acreage and a cash payment of at least $34.9 million.
   The transaction also calls for the Veterans Administration to
get 11.5 acres of the school property to expand its Phoenix
hospital; Phoenix to get 20 acres for a park; and Arizona to get
4.5 acres for a veterans home. The rest of the land is tied up in
road rights-of-way.
   The money paid by the Colliers would be placed into a trust fund
for the education of Indians in Arizona.
   Yates and Miller argued that taxpayers would get a better deal
if the property were sold on the open market.
   They said at least one appraiser has set the value of the
Phoenix land at $100 million more than the value attached to it in
the proposed exchange.
   ``This is a sweetheart deal between the Colliers and the federal
government,'' Miller said. ``We're being asked to ratify a great
deal for the Colliers and a terrible deal for U.S. taxpayers.''
   Miller argued that while the Florida land is environmentally
sensitive and a good federal acquisition, it already is protected
from any damaging development by federal law.
   ``This is a cushy, cozy deal for the Colliers,'' said Yates.
``If it were not Mo Udall's bill, it would be laughed off the
floor. ... It's a very bad bill.''
   The bill would give the Colliers three years to decide whether
to exercise an option on the Phoenix property. If they did, other
developers would have 90 days to submit bids, which the Colliers
would be allowed to top.
   Miller and Yates argued that this procedure favors the Colliers
because competitors would not be able to come up with the
development plans and financing within a short time.
   They tried to convince the House to send the bill back to the
Interior Committee with instructions to revise it to include an
open competitive bidding process. Their recommittal motion lost
279-133.
   In the Senate, the Indian Affairs and Energy and Natural
Resources committees took testimony on the issue on Monday but have
not drafted legislation of their own.
   The Florida property is in Collier County in Southwest Florida.
The bulk of the 108,000 acres lies immediately north of the Big
Cypress National Preserve, which borders Everglades National Park
on the park's northwest side.
   Another parcel, of 5,000 acres, is adjacent to the Fakahatchee
Strand State Preserve, known home to perhaps a fifth of the 30 to
50 Florida panthers believed left in the wilderness. The state
preserve is west of the national preserve.
   And 19,620 acres is next to the state's Cape Romano-Ten Thousand
Islands Aquatic Preserve, on the Gulf coast south of Naples and
west of Everglades City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
