<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BuriedAlive 1stLd-Writethru a0552 07-28 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Buried Alive, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0552,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worker Dies After Falling Into Bin of Dry Cement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead to CLARIFY.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A worker who fell off a 60-foot tower into a
huge bin of dry cement gasped for air for nearly two hours while
firefighters tried to pull him out, authorities said. He died
shortly after his rescue.
   ``This stuff is like talcum powder and quicksand _ the faster
you move in it, the more you sink,'' said Bruce Savage, a division
chief with the Fire Department.
   Michael LaGrand, 34, fell into the 20-foot steel hopper
Wednesday. Workers at the concrete-mixing site secured him man by
looping a rope under his armpits. Rescuers wrapped more ropes
around him and gave him an air mask.
   ``He was buried all the way up to his face,'' said Fire Capt.
Roy Billington. ``All you could see was the top of his head, his
face and his hands.''
   About a dozen firefighters tried to pull out the 250-pound
worker. He sank below the surface several times, then slipped out
of sight for the last time. He was pulled from the funnel-shaped
hopper about 15 minutes later, authorities said.
   He died an hour later at Tampa General Hospital.
</TEXT>
