<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Labor-HHS 1stLd-Writethru a0433 07-28 0887</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Labor-HHS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Opposes Abortion Funding for Rape, Incest Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last two grafs with those voting against, and not
voting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion-rights advocates hailed the Senate's
lopsided vote to extend Medicaid funding to abortions for rape and
incest victims as a breakthrough, but the plan still faces
skepticism in the House and hostility from the White House.
   The Senate's 73-19 vote Wednesday marked the first departure by
either chamber from the restrictive abortion policies of the past
seven years.
   Current law, in effect since 1981, limits payments to abortions
in which the life of the mother is endangered.
   Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., sponsor of the expansion, said the
vote Wednesday represented ``a clear change'' from recent tradition.
   ``What is terribly important is just to break that chain'' of
restrictive regulations, he said. ``It's a first small start.''
   The abortion provision was part of a $140 billion appropriations
bill passed 80-16 Wednesday evening after a day of frenzied votes
and shifting tactics on abortion, family planning and AIDS issues.
   The bill will keep the departments of Labor, Health and Human
Services, and Education in business during fiscal 1989 beginning
Oct. 1. Its highlights include $7.1 billion for employment and
training; $1.2 billion for AIDS research, treatment, prevention and
education, and $4.2 billion for tutoring and other services to
disadvantaged students.
   In a June 28 statement, the Office of Management and Budget
urged the Senate to strike its Medicaid abortion provision, saying
it ``diverges from longstanding policy on this issue. ... The
president's senior advisers would recommend that he veto this bill,
solely based on the inclusion of this language provision.''
   The abortion provision adopted by the Senate is more restrictive
than the simple extension Weicker sponsored during the committee
process. Federal money would only be available in promptly reported
rape or incest cases, and states could retain the existing, more
limited eligibility if they so desire.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., sponsor of the modified version, said
it reflects ``the middle ground'' on a difficult issue. Weicker
said it had a better shot at surviving negotiations with House
members, who did not include a Medicaid expansion in their version
of the appropriations bill.
   Asked about the possibility of a veto, Weicker replied,
``Considering everything else that's in the bill and that it's an
election year, it could be overridden.''
   But Doug Johnson, legislative director of the National Right To
Life Committee, said he was confident the final product would not
contain the Medicaid abortion expansion.
   ``The House is strongly committed to the current law. So is the
president,'' said Johnson. In any case, he said, his group
considers the Exon amendment ``a very good outcome'' because it
gives states some leeway and eliminates the possibility of rape
claims six months into a pregnancy.
   There was little controversy over money allocations in the bill,
which was drawn up in accordance with the budget framework agreed
to last year by Congress and the Reagan administration. But there
were enough AIDS, abortion and family planning amendments to
prolong debate for three days.
   In a confusing series of events, senators three times rejected
attempts by Sen. Jesse Helms to renew an expiring ban on federal
funds for AIDS education materials that promote or encourage
homosexuality.
   Instead they adopted an amendment described by its sponsor, Sen.
Alan Cranston, D-Calif., as a pre-emptive strike against the Helms
ban. While it bans federal funds for materials that directly
promote or encourage homosexuality, at the same time it says the
materials must provide accurate information on how to avoid getting
and transmitting AIDS.
   Some senators disavowed their votes last year in favor of the
Helms restrictions, saying they wrongly believed the restrictions
were toothless.
   ``It is a fact that effective materials have been shelved and
vital proposals have been tabled because of the fear of what this
amendment might do,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman
of the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee.
   Nevertheless, after embracing the Cranston amendment 61-37, the
Senate later passed another amendment _ this one containing the
Helms restrictions as well as a phrase saying federally funded AIDS
materials cannot ``use words stating that homosexuality is
`normal,' `natural' or `healthy.'''
   The Senate voted 48-45 to kill a Helms amendment banning federal
money to school-based clinics that distribute contraceptives or
provide abortion counseling or referral services.
   Later lawmakers by voice vote approved a more limited version of
the same amendment, one which dropped the contraceptives section
but retained the ban relating to abortion services.
   School-based clinics are set up by local school boards to
provide health services that sometimes include family planning.
Some receive Medicaid funds and money from block grants funneled
through states.
   Voting against the abortion proposal were Sens. Bill Bradley,
D-N.J., John Breaux, D-La., Alan Cranston, D-Calif., Dennis
DeConcini, D-Ariz., Wendell Ford, D-Ky., John Glenn, D-Ohio, Howell
Heflin, D-Ala., Jesse Helms, R-N.C., Bennett Johnston, D-La., Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., Carl Levin, D-Mich., John McCain, R-Ariz.,
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., Bob Packwood, R-Ore., Harry Reid, D-Nev.,
Donald Riegle, D-Mich., Richard Shelby, D-Ala., Alan Simpson,
R-Wyo., and Tim Wirth, D-Colo.
   Not voting were Sens. Brock Adams, D-Wash., Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, Joe Biden, D-Del., Tom Daschle, D-S.D., Wyche Fowler,
D-Ga., Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., Steven Symms, R-Idaho and John Warner,
R-Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
