<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru   07-28 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0487,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curfew Imposed After Riot Leaves One Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Amnesty International
urging investigation. Pick up 3rd graf pvs: `The government...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A town north of Rangoon was under curfew
today after mobs destroyed Moslem-owned tea shops and attacked
police with stones and catapults, leaving one person dead and five
wounded, sources said.
   It was not certain whether the violence was related to this
week's national leadership changes in which hard-line former army
general Sein Lwin assumed the positions of president and head of
the only political party.
   Also today, Amnesty International urged Burma's leaders to
investigate alleged brutality by authorities who quelled riots in
which scores of people died.
   The government said 43 people died in March unrest, including 41
who suffocated in a packed police van as they were being driven to
prison. Unofficial reports put the death toll at more than 100.
   ``These investigations should lead to the bringing to justice of
those responsible for human rights violations,'' the London-based
human rights organization said in response to a query by The
Associated Press.
   The government news agency said Wednesday that the curfew was
imposed and all demonstrations banned Tuesday in Myede, 220 miles
north of Rangoon, after rioters attacked police with catapults and
stones.
   The official News Agency Burma said police had to shoot to
disperse the crowd and order was restored after several hundred
rioters destroyed two tea shops and a third building.
   The mob first set upon the Moslem-owned tea shops and then went
on a looting spree, said the sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity. The sources believed the incident was a spillover of
riots in nearby Prome.
   Prome has been under martial law since July 22, after six days
of mob violence that reportedly started with an argument between a
Buddhist customer and a Moslem tea shop owner. Most Burmese are
Buddhist.
   In recent months, several minor quarrels have turned into major
and bloody anti-government riots, including one last March in
Rangoon in which more than 100 people were reported killed. That
riot also began with a tea shop quarrel.
   Some analysts believe that the outbursts reflect popular
resentment of the government and dissatisfaction with deteriorating
economic conditions. Tea shops are popular informal gathering
places for the Burmese.
   Sein Lwin, who ruthlessly suppressed dissidents over the last 26
years, on Tuesday became chairman of the Burma Socialist Program
Party and on Wednesday became the nation's president.
   Western diplomats said his rise could fan the fires of political
protest that have erupted three times since last October, leaving
dozens dead, universities closed and student resentment at a
boiling point.
   Leaflets have appeared in Rangoon in recent days urging
continued anti-government agitation.
   In addition to naming Sein Lwin president, Wednesday's one-day,
emergency session of also elected former deputy prime minister Tun
Tin to the post of prime minister. Vice President Aye Ko remained
in his post.
   Defense Minister Kyaw Htin moved to the No. 3 government
position as head of the Council of State. In all, eight of the 22
major government positions were changed.
   The changes appeared to herald a continuation of the hardline,
one-party system begun by strongman Ne Win 26 years ago, although a
number of liberal economic reforms were endorsed.
   Ne Win, 77, said he was retiring, but doubt remains among
Western and Burmese analysts over whether he will fade away or
remain a behind-the-scenes director of events.
   Kya Htin and Tun Tin, however, both are regarded as relatively
liberal on issues of economic reform and dealing with dissent in
the country. Kyaw Htin also moved up to a top party post.
</TEXT>
