<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1041EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PearThrips     07-28 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pear Thrips,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont Governor Calls For Program To Combat Thrips Infestation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Thrips with an `s' is both plural and singular.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An insect that attacks the buds of maple
trees has defoliated or stunted one-sixth of Vermont's forests,
threatening its $15 million-a-year maple syrup industry and its
eye-popping foliage, officials say.
   ``This is serious. This is something we don't know very much
about and this is something we have to learn as much as we can
about as fast as possible to prevent a reoccurence,'' Gov.
Madeleine Kunin said Wednesday.
   Kunin said she would seek about $200,000 in state and federal
funding for a research and management program to combat the
insects, called pear thrips. She said the insect has attacked
466,000 acres in every county in Vermont.
   Western Massachusetts, New Hampshire and New York have also
reported thrips damage, but Conrad Motyka, Vermont director of
forests, said Vermont has been hit the hardest.
   The infestation is so severe in some of Vermont's southern
counties that experts may recommend that sugarmakers leave some
maple trees untapped next year.
   ``Maple in Vermont is the most prominent tree that we have,''
Motyka said. ``It could tremendously affect not just our industry
but our very way of life. If you took all the maples away, it would
look very different in Vermont.''
   State officials said they have no estimate of the damage to the
timber industry or to tourism. Vermont's brilliant fall foliage
draws thousands of tourists.
   In the past, thrips were only known to attack fruit trees, but
in the last decade they have started defoliating trees of the
forest.
   ``I think there is national and international concern that this
may be part of the death of some of our forests and that we've got
to put all our resources that we have to work,'' Kunin said.
   Kunin said she would ask the state's Emergency Board to allocate
$93,950 to research the thrips damage. The board includes Kunin and
leaders of the Legislature and handles some financial matters while
lawmakers are out of session.
   Kunin said she would also ask for a $60,000 federal grant as
well as $46,500 from other sources.
</TEXT>
