<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan     07-28 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomats Say Soviets Taken Over Defense of Kabul Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western diplomats said today that
Soviet troops have taken over the defense of the airport in
Afghanistan's capital and are deploying heavy military equipment
around it.
   The diplomats, speaking on the usual condition of anonymity,
said several Soviet armored vehicles were deployed around the
airport in Kabul. They said these included mechanized infantry
combat vehicles _ a smaller version of Western armored personnel
carriers but with greater firepower.
   Afghan guerrilla attacks from the northeast have been
particularly heavy, diplomats said. Soviet response has been to
deploy armored vehicles to a security post on the eastern edge of
the airport, as well as on a small hill overlooking the airport and
at the main gates of the international arrival and departure
buildings, they said.
   The diplomats said the airport has been the target of frequent
rocket attacks by guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's Soviet-backed
government.
   An attack Sunday missed the mark and rockets landed in a
residential area, killing 17 people.
   In late June, a rocket attack destroyed eight Soviet jet
fighters at the airport.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to back the
government in its war with the guerrillas, who are based in
Pakistan and supported by the United States and Pakistan. Under
terms of an accord signed in April, the Red Army troops began
withdrawing in May and are to be out by February 1989.
</TEXT>
