<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GoldFlute     07-28 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gold Flute,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$50,000 Gold Flute, Other Art Objects Returned by `Fence'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $50,000 gold and wood flute stolen from an art
gallery has been returned by a ``fence'' who realized it was ``too
hot'' to handle.
   Emmett Day, the artist who made the one-of-a-kind instrument
with 21-karat gold keys, springs and mouthpiece, said Wednesday the
recovery was ``amazing.''
   ``Everything that happened to it has canceled out the evil of
that original impulse (the theft),'' Day said.
   The flute has been played by such musicians as James Galway, Day
said. The flute and other works by Day were stolen July 8 from the
Northwest Gallery of Fine Woodworking. No one has been arrested,
police said.
   On Tuesday, ``we got a call from an attorney in Tacoma who said
`if your name is Emmett Day, this is your lucky day,''' Day said.
   His wife, Therese, said the thief had sold the art works for
$3,500 to a dealer in stolen goods ``who read about the theft in
the paper and realized he shouldn't destroy them, and he couldn't
resell them because they were too hot.''
   The ``fence'' then contacted the lawyer, she said. Except for
some small scratches, the flute and other articles ``were not
really hurt,'' Ms. Day said.
   Day said he's unsure whether he will put the flute on display
again.
</TEXT>
