<2ND_LINE>PM-Lightning Strike,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Knocked Unconscious By Lightning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bolt of lightning from a cloudless
sky struck eight youngsters playing softball, critically injuring
one boy and melting his sneakers, witnesses and authorities said.
   ``It was just one bolt, but it was so strong and so fierce that
it hit those two boys and all the others got the aftershock,'' said
Bexar County Sheriff's patrolman Rick Talamentez.
   ``The kids were just walking around in a daze, except for the
two of them that were unconscious.''
   Hugo Arauz, 13, was in critical condition at Brooke Army Medical
Center today. Kevin Epps, 15, was in good condition, a hospital
spokesman said. The other youngsters suffered minor injuries,
authorities said.
   Arauz, whose sneakers were melted, apparently was hit directly
by the bolt Wednesday, said Sheriff's Patrolman Jesse Ambriz.
   ``The bad thing about it was they said it was sunny. No rain, no
clouds, no nothing,'' said Thomas Brooks Sr. Two of his sons were
with the group but were not injured.
   The National Weather Service said there was a strong
thunderstorm about four miles away at the time. ``Lightning can
travel for long distances even though the cloud may seem far away
from you,'' said meteorologist Cristy Mitchell.
</TEXT>
