<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Irish 2ndLd-Writethru   07-28 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0560,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Man Buried In Ceremony Tinged With remorse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Hanna funeral. Pick up
10th graf pvs: `Davison's coffin...' DELETES grafs 17 and 18 to
conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish Republican Army man
was buried today in a ceremony tinged with remorse over a series of
IRA blunders that have killed 17 people since November.
   The latest victims _ a Protestant couple and their 6-year-old
son blown up in their car _ were buried later in their hometown of
Hillsborough, outside Belfast.
   The first of the day's two funerals was that of 33-year-old
Brendan Davison, shot to death on his doorstep Monday by the Ulster
Volunteer Force, an outlawed Protestant group.
   Davison, whom the IRA claimed as one of its own, was widely
believed to have been killed in reprisal for the death of
contractor Robin Hanna, his wife Maureen, and their son David.
   The IRA admitted triggering the bomb that killed the Hannas as
they drove across the border from Ireland to Northern Ireland on
Saturday after a vacation. It says its intended victim was a
Belfast Catholic judge, Ian Higgins.
   Police guarded the approaches to Belfast's Catholic Milltown
cemetery but kept their distance from the funeral. The ceremony
passed peacefully, with none of the IRA ceremonials that have
sparked clashes with security forces in the past.
   Danny Morrison, second-in-command of the outlawed IRA's legal
political wing, Sinn Fein, delivered the eulogy.
   ``For the past number of months we have come through very, very
bleak conditions. It has been a very, very bad time, when it seems
as if everything the IRA has touched has turned to tragedy and it
has been very, very rough for many people,'' Morrison told several
hundred mourners standing in the rain.
   Sending condolences to the Hannas' two surviving teen-age
children, he said: ``We share in their tragedy. What happened was
terrible. It was regrettable. We want to see all deaths end,
including the deaths of our enemies in uniform. We want to see
peace in this country.''
   At the Hannas' funeral, Bishop Gordon McMullan of the Church of
Ireland pleaded with the killers on both sides of the conflict to
``recognize what this cult of violence is doing to your own moral
and spiritual condition.''
   Responding to the IRA's condolences, he said: ``The spokesmen
who represent the killers have made their excuses and expressed
their regret. But the fact is that Robin, Maureen and David Hanna
are dead ... the plotters planned death and death was what ensued.''
   Davison's coffin was draped in the Irish tricolor, and the IRA
said in a statement Tuesday night that it had paid its ``final
tribute'' by firing a volley of shots over a nationalist mural in
Catholic west Belfast.
   It was the first IRA funeral since March 19, when Catholics
following the cortege of a slain guerrilla attacked two British
soldiers who reportedly blundered into the procession.
   The soldiers were dragged from their car, severely beaten and
shot by IRA gunmen.
   Security forces had stayed away from that funeral at the request
of church and political leaders.
   The IRA says it is conducting an inquiry into why five recent
operations have been botched, starting with a bomb in November that
was meant to hit soldiers but killed 11 Protestant civilians at a
war memorial service in Enniskillen.
   Other blunders have since included a bomb on a schoolbus that
injured a dozen teen-agers, a bomb at a Belfast swimming pool that
killed two Catholics, and the shooting of a Protestant woman. In
all cases the IRA has apologized, saying the intended targets were
security forces or judicial personnel.
   The IRA said the Hannas were victims of a ``wronged
description'' of the judge's car. Judge Higgins, his wife Bridget
and daughter Cait were returning from Dublin on the same road.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Pakistan 2ndLd-Writethru a0565 07-28 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Pakistan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0565,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Recants: Soviets Are Leaving Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new to include results of meeting with Schultz;
picks up 9th graf pvs, The United States.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan's foreign minister today allayed
concerns that the Soviet Union was reneging on its pledge to
withdraw the Red Army from Afghanistan.
   ``This impression has just been dispelled,'' Sahabzada Yaqub
Khan said after a meeting with Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
``Our position and that of the United States in regard to the
withdrawal is no longer divergent.''
   The pace of the pullout and U.S. hopes for fair elections in
Pakistan were topics for discussion during the foreign minister's
visit.
   There are an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops in Afghanistan.
Half are supposed to be withdrawn by Aug. 15. Pakistani President
Mohamnad Zia al-Haq raised concerns last week that the Soviets were
replenishing them with new troops.
   But Yaqub Khan said ``the Soviets are carrying out the
withdrawal.''
   Through Pakistan, the United States armed Afghan rebels fighting
the Red Army and the pro-Soviet government in Kabul.
   U.S. officials said this week that Moscow had sent new
assurances that the Soviets would fulfill their commitment in the
Geneva accords of last May to withdraw half the troops by Aug. 15.
   The report that they would be replaced was traced to the Soviet
military commander in Kabul, who apparently did not have the
backing of his superiors in Moscow.
   Shultz, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and Yaqub Khan are
comparing notes on how to monitor the Soviet withdrawal _ and on
Afghanistan's future after the troops are gone. One question is
whether the rebels then would be able to bring down President
Najibullah. Another is the kind of government that would follow.
   Several of the rebel leaders would like to install a
fundamentalist Moslem regime akin to the government in neighboring
Iran.
   ``It is extremely important we look beyond Afghanistan and
continue close cooperation with the United States in the interest
of peace and security in the region,'' Yaqub Khan said.
   The United States has close ties to Pakistan, which gave refuge
to millions of Afghan refugees besides funneling covert U.S.
support to the rebels.
   U.S. officials are hoping the elections Zia has set for Nov. 16
will be fair, but there is a question how much pressure Shultz
might try to apply.
   ``We will stress that elections should be free and fair, but it
is not up to the U.S. government to prescribe how they should be
held,'' said an official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Zia dismissed his civilian government in May, but did not call
for elections within the 90 days prescribed by the Pakistani
constitution.
   He also barred candidates from running with party labels. Zia
took the position that party-based elections could mislead the
voters.
   Critics say this will focus attention on local issues and work
against Zia's main national opposition, the Pakistan People's
Party. It is headed by Benazir Bhutto, whose father was ousted in
1977 in a coup led by Zia and executed.
   On another touchy issue, President Reagan must certify in
October that Pakistan does not possess a nuclear explosive device
in order for U.S. aid to continue. Reagan will see Yaqub Khan
briefly on Friday.
   The Reagan administration last year fought off a drive in
Congress to shelve U.S. military aid to Pakistan amid indications
the country was trying to develop a nuclear bomb.
   Pakistan has denied making such an attempt. It is receiving $260
million in military aid this year and $380 million in U.S. economic
assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
