<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hodel-Fires 1stLd-Writethru a0545 07-28 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hodel-Fires, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Forest Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with additional comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel, just back
from touring fire-scorched Yellowstone National Park, said today
firefighters are now fighting all new outbreaks. But one official
said it's still possible that some new fires might be left to burn.
   ``Yellowstone is not in danger. ... We're not going to let
Yellowstone be damaged by this,'' Hodel said on ABC-TV's ``Good
Morning America'' program.
   Fighting all new outbreaks has always been a possibility in the
usual ``let it burn'' policy of the National Park Service, Chief
Ranger Walt Dabney said afterward.
   Both Dabney and the secretary defended the post-1972 policy of
fighting only fires that threaten developed areas or that could
spread out of the park into timbering operations on adjacent Forest
Service lands.
   The Forest Service and the Bureau of Land Management follow
similar policies in their wildnerness areas because fires are
important in generating healthy ecosystems.
   ``The fact is that Yellowstone has about 3 percent currently
burning. ... But they've had a sufficient area under their
fire-management plan that their policy now is to fight new fires
that break out,'' Hodel said.
   Dabney said in an interview the secretary was right in his
facts, and all recent outbreaks had been attacked with a view of
keeping the fires small, but the policy was unchanged _ decisions
will be made case by case, and the action taken will depend on
where the fire is and what is threatened, how many firefighters are
available and how dangerous it would be to commit them.
   A few firefighters can knock down a small blaze that might be
impossible to control if left alone, he noted.
   Any fire that breaks out in remote areas might well be left
alone now, he said. Any fire near the park boundaries probably
would be attacked.
   Crews have begun using flame throwers to start backfires against
fires that have so far scorched some 109,000 of the park's 2.2
million acres. The fires had moved to within six miles of Old
Faithful and forced the closing of one of the park's main entrances.
   ``In Yellowstone specifically we're fighting probably six or
eight large fire areas right now,'' Dabney said.
   Hodel flew over some of the damaged forest land Wednesday and
voiced confidence afterwards in the policy of allowing remote areas
to burn. In his comments today, the interior secretary said the
flames had gone far enough.
   ``What they tell me is we've got standing timber that is as dry
or drier than kiln-dried lumber. That makes it just take off like
crazy when you have a fire,'' he said. ``In these conditions
there's very little control we can have over these fires.''
   Dabney said the damage could even help naturalists learn more
about the forest by providing a close look at how large-scale fires
clear old brush for new wildlife habitat.
   ``What we're looking at probably occurred naturally in the
Yellowstone area every 200 to 400 years,'' he said. ``We've never
really had the chance to see wildfire on this scale in the
Yellowstone ecosystem, so we're going to look at it very closely
from a research standpoint and know a lot more specifically about
the benefits of what's going on there now.''
   About 80 percent of Yellowstone is lodgepole pine in a
``fire-dependent ecology,'' he said. Natural fires ``Are very
important to keep species diversified. Many wildlife species will
leave an area that's too thick and stagnant.''
   New trees and a wealth of wildlife-attracting vegetation grow in
the open areas created by fires, whose ashes act as a natural
fertilizer, he said.
</TEXT>
