<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-US-ChemicalWeapons     07-28 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Chemical Weapons,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Discloses Production Sites of Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. delegate to the Conference on Disarmament
today declared the location of the United States' chemical weapons
production facilities.
   Delegate Max Friedersdorf said he hoped the declaration would
``contribute both to greater confidence and to the negotiation of
related provisions'' of a convention banning the production,
stockpiling and use of chemical weapons.
   The Geneva conference has been negotiating such a convention for
20 years. This year's summer session began July 7.
   ``The declaration we are making today is unprecedented,''
Friedersdorf told the 40-nation conference.
   ``We urge other countries that possess chemical weapons
production facilities to declare the locations of their facilities
and to outline how the facilities would be destroyed,'' he said.
   He said no other conference member had provided information on
chemical weapons production facilities. The United States and
Soviet Union are the only two members of the conference who have
acknowledged possessing chemical weapons.
   The United States has said it believes about 15 nations possess
such weapons, but it has refused to name them.
   The production facilities declared by the United States are
Rocky Mountain Arsenal, in Colorado; the Pine Bluff Arsenal in
Arkansas; Muscle Shoals in Alabama; Newport Army Ammunition Depot
in Indiana; and Aberdeen Proving Ground in Maryland.
   The Soviet Union has declared the amount of its stockpiles, but
not their location nor the location of production sites.
   The Soviet Union said in December that its chemical weapons
stocks total 50,000 tons, but Western experts have estimated that
the actual total is much higher.
   The United States also submitted to the conference ideas for
ways to destroy chemical weapons under an eventual ban.
   Delegates have drafted many parts of a chemical weapons ban. The
main unresolved issue is how to guard against cheating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
