<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Evangelicals     07-28 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Evangelicals,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sees Resurgence In Religion, Family Values</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today the nation is
regaining its ``religious and moral bearings'' but must do more to
overcome promiscuity, drug use, pornography and a drifting away
from church and family values.
   ``An overwhelming nine out of 10 Americans pray,'' Reagan said.
``Audiences for religious books are growing. The modern
communications media are being used for evangelism.''
   In a speech to the Student Congress on Evangelism at the
Washington Convention Center, the president said his administration
``has worked hard to reflect this return to basic values.''
   Reagan ticked off a host of steps in recent years, including
enactment by Congress of the Equal Access Act of 1984, giving
voluntary religious groups the right to meet after school on the
same basis as other groups. He also cited longstanding
administration positions in support of returning prayer to the
classroom and reversing the Supreme Court decision that legalized
abortions.
   Reagan seldom goes to church, but has said he prays frequently.
   In his speech today, he said that ``I am not going to preach a
sermon.''
   At another point, the president talked to the young men and
women about the pressures teen-agers feel to have sex out of
wedlock.
   ``I'm sure that each of you believes that someday you'll find
someone to fall in love with _ and you will,'' he said. ``Sometimes
you may get frustrated and, yes, finding the right one may take
longer than you thought.
   ``But don't worry. It will happen,'' Reagan said. ``And that's
why it's so important for you not to pay any attention at all to
those who say that promiscuity is somehow stylish and rewarding.
No, the right thing to do is to wait for that one special person _
beginning now.''
   Reagan said that ``we must admit that in recent years, America
did seem to lose some of her religious and moral bearings.''
   He said pornography spread unchecked and was ``available
virtually on every magazine rack in every drugstore or shop in the
land.''
   Reagan said drug abuse ``spread through the nation like a fever,
attracting children as well as adults and involving drugs that were
once unheard of _ drugs like LSD and PCP.''
   While the president said those problems remain, ``I believe
there's been a change.''
   ``Now, although we Americans have done much to put our national
life back on the firm foundation of traditional values, there is
still a great deal to be done,'' he said. ``And so today, I want to
challenge you young people to see that our nation does still more _
still more to return to the life-giving values of faith and
family.''
</TEXT>
