<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0585 07-28 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0585,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Nominee On The Road Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Secaucus in dateline and 2nd and 4th
grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis launched a seven-state
presidential campaign swing today after spending three days tending
to his duties as Massachusetts governor _ including signing off on
the final piece of a plan to balance his fiscal 1988 state budget.
   Dukakis met early today with fund-raisers and with supporters of
Jesse Jackson in Newark, then headed for Secaucus where he was to
visit a high-tech office park surrounded by a shopping center.
   One of the Jackson supporters, Newark Mayor Sharpe James, was
accompanying him, and Dukakis aides said the Democratic
presidential nominee would meet later in the campaign trip with
others who supported Jackson's presidential bid.
   In a speech prepared for delivery in Secaucus, Dukakis restated
the major points of his acceptance speech at the Democratic
National Convention last week.
   ``There are some who say we can't have a strong economy and
create opportunity for all our citizens,'' he said. ``Well, I know
from my experience in Massachusetts that equal opportunity and
economic growth go hand in hand. ... It begins with the recognition
that a strong economy needs three things: investment, innovation
and teamwork.''
   Dukakis ended his day Wednesday by attending the 30th annual
convention of the Pancretan Association of America, a group of
Greek-Americans who trace their roots back to the island of Crete.
   There, Dukakis repeated an Athenian pledge to public service he
frequently adds to campaign speeches, and then left the stage to
join a Greek dance.
   After New Jersey, Dukakis was heading to Cleveland and then to
Michigan, Wisconsin, Illinois and Kentucky on Friday and Kentucky
and North Carolina on Saturday.
   The Democratic nominee resumed stumping a day after a poll was
released showing him with an 18-point lead over Republican George
Bush, the largest margin of the campaign and an sign of the boost
Dukakis received from last week's Democratic National Convention.
   Dukakis drew 50 percent support to 32 percent for Bush in the
NBC News-Wall Street Journal national survey of 1,770 registered
voters. He had led by 10 points, 46-36, in a pre-convention
NBC-Journal poll. The latest poll, conducted by telephone Saturday
through Monday, had a margin of error of three points.
   Before leaving the Statehouse, Dukakis signed a number of bills
passed by the Legislature before it broke for a summer recess.
   Among them was a $124 million spending plan to close the books
on the fiscal year that ended June 30. The money was largely for
underfunded entitlement programs such as Medicaid and Aid to
Families with Dependent Children.
   Also signed into law by the governor was legislation to help
ease prison overcrowding through the purchase of modular units
containing 1,000 beds and a measure restoring a child-pornography
law struck down by the state Supreme Court. He also announced
distribution of $7.8 million in state and federal grants for victim
assistance programs.
   Dukakis dismissed Bush's repeated criticism of a Massachusetts
furlough program that, until it was amended, allowed passes to
first-degree murderers, including a man who escaped from a furlough
and raped a Maryland woman.
   ``I've got a record,'' Dukakis said, referring to statistics
showing his state's crime rate had dropped 13 percent in the past
four years. ``I don't know what the vice president's record is.''
   Dukakis was to spend the first half of next week at the
Statehouse before taking a Western campaign swing, during which
aides said he planned to interview several Jesse Jackson backers
interested in joining the Dukakis fall effort.
   Jackson himself should resume campaigning ``very shortly,'' said
Joseph Warren, Dukakis' general election coordinator and campaign
secretary.
   Dukakis also plans to campaign during the Republican National
Convention next month, although no itinerary was available.
   ``We do not plan any fishing or hunting trips during that
period,'' said Susan Estrich, Dukakis' campaign manager, referring
to a fishing trip Bush took with Treasury Secretary James A. Baker
during the first few days of the Democratic convention. ``We plan
to campaign.''
</TEXT>
