<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Aldermen-Smokers     07-28 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aldermen-Smokers,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Aldermen Puff Away Despite Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The smoke-filled room is dying hard in Chicago.
   Some City Council members who opposed the new ban on smoking in
public places continue to light up in council chambers.
   ``How can they be so rude as to ignore a city law?'' asked
Alderman Raymond A. Figueroa, sponsored the clean air act that went
into effect Sunday.
   Alderman Thomas W. Cullerton, a smoker, started a hearing on the
matter during Wednesday's Council meeting. ``Wherever I put this
ashtray will be a designated smoking area,'' he said. ``I said it,
and I stand by it.''
   Alderman Victor Vrdolyak puffed away while fellow Council
members argued and insisted the ban does not apply to the meeting
room in City Hall. ``This is not a public area, period,'' Vrdolyak
said.
   The ordinance law bans smoking in enclosed public areas like
meeting rooms and taxicabs and requires restaurants with 40 seats
or more to set aside smoking and non-smoking areas. Bars and
private meeting rooms are exempt.
