<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CandyStoreKilling     07-28 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candy Store Killing,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Murderer After Emotional Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge reminisced about the candy stores of
his youth, then sentenced a man convicted of murdering a candy
store owner to life in prison.
   Douglas County District Judge James Murphy on Wednesday
sentenced Christopher Bazer, 19. Bazer could have been sentenced to
death for the Feb. 18 shooting death of Mary Jirsak, 78.
   Bazer pleaded guilty to first-degree murder in June, saying he
shot Miss Jirsak in the head during a robbery at her store. Two
other men convicted in the killing are awaiting sentencing.
   ``When I first heard about this case ... I thought back to the
time that I was 6 or 7 years old. In those days, they had a candy
store almost next to every school,'' Murphy said before the
sentencing.
   ``In the fall, October, I'd stop in a candy store. The sun would
come in that window. Light from the sun, the polished glass, would
light up my whole world.''
   Murphy shook his head, stood and strode out of the courtroom.
Bazer sat in silence with the lawyers and spectators until the
judge returned three minutes later.
   ``In any event, those memories have been spoiled by what
happened to Mary Jirsak,'' Murphy said, without mentioning his
absence.
   He then left the bench to embrace Karen Kojdecki, Miss Jirsak's
niece.
   ``Karen, judges care so much,'' he told her.
   Returning to the bench, Murphy addressed Bazer.
   ``I think what you did was deplorable, especially because of the
kind of person who was killed,'' the judge said.
   Bazer told the judge: ``I'm sorry about what happened, and if I
could change it I would.''
   The prosecutor and defense lawyer said they had never seen a
judge show such emotion in court.
   ``It was magnificent, wasn't it?'' asked Deputy Douglas County
Attorney Gerald Moran.
   ``The emotion was obvious,'' defense lawyer Alan Stoler said.
``I felt for the judge as much as I felt sorry for the family.''
</TEXT>
