<2ND_LINE>PM-St Patrick's Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0528,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robbery Suspect Shot Dead Outside St. Patrick's Cathedral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with second suspect
arrested; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `The officer ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man robbed a family of tourists of their video
camera as they filmed St. Patrick's Cathedral, then tried to get
away in an off-duty jail guard's car but was shot to death on a
nearby crowded street, police said.
   The holdup occurred at evening rush hour Wednesday on
fashionable Fifth Avenue, ending when the correction officer fired
his gun inside his car, striking the robbery suspect three times in
the chest, said a police spokesman, Sgt. Maurice Howard.
   Angel Santiago, 22, died later in the afternoon at Bellevue
Hospital, Howard said. A second suspect, Frank Felix Rodriguez, 19,
turned himself in this morning and was charged with robbery and
attempted robbery, police said.
   The officer, John Bonilla, 33, also shot himself in the foot
during the struggle and was in stable condition at Bellevue, Howard
said. The thief's body slumped over Bonilla's 5-year-old son in the
front seat of the car, but the boy was uninjured, police said.
   Joe Ashcraft of Muncie, Ind., said he was standing across the
avenue from St. Patrick's Cathedral with his family at about 5
p.m., his video camera trained on the landmark church. Despite the
midtown crowds, two men pulled up in a car, one got out and
demanded Ashcraft's camera, he said.
   ``He said if you don't give me your camera and take it over and
put it in that car right now I'm going to shoot you,'' said
Ashcraft. ``At that point I didn't believe he had a gun.
   ``But then he pulled the gun and when he pulled the gun I gave
him the camera,'' Ashcraft said.
   As the robbers tried to speed off, police said, their car
collided with a taxi and then slammed into the side of a bus. The
pair then jumped out of their car and fled.
   One suspect, Santiago, ran onto a nearby street and tried to
escape by scrambling into Bonilla's car through an open window
before he was shot, said a police spokesman, Sgt. Maurice Howard.
Police believe Santiago was the thief who grabbed Ashcraft's camera.
   The gun used by Bonilla was his personal revolver, which he was
authorized the carry, Howard said.
   Police said Ashcraft recovered his video camera from the robbery
suspects' car, which they had left behind when they fled.
</TEXT>
