<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven people died of gastroenteritis or
cholera in New Delhi on Thursday, and 1,106 new cases of the two
diseases were reported.
   Thursday's deaths raised the total number of victims nationwide
to 466 since monsoon rains began late last month. The rains set off
flooding that has caused sewers to overflow and contaminate the
drinking water in wells.
   In New Delhi, a city of 8 million people, at least 182 people
have died since the two diseases caused epidemics in early July.
   ``Our anti-cholera operation is on, but still we are getting
large numbers of new cases,'' health officer Brijendra Kumar said.
   Kumar said 1,106 new cases of the diseases were reported in New
Delhi on Thursday, and 34 of the cases were confirmed to be cholera.
