<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SugarQuota     07-28 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sugar Quota,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Imported For Cake Decorating Demonstration Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a sweet decision indeed that will
enable two British cake decorators to show their talents their own
way at a convention here.
   June Melendy on Wednesday picked up an 88-pound box of specially
milled powdered sugar and other supplies from federal officials.
``It's in the back of my car and I'm not going to let it out of my
sight,'' she said.
   Authorities who on July 19 blocked importation of powdered
sugar, syrup and molasses said the shipment violated the U.S. sugar
import quota of 1.06 million tons.
   ``It seems like a relatively small thing,'' said Charles Conroy,
spokesman for the U.S. Customs Department in Houston. ``But we have
to protect U.S. sugar manufacturers and employees. If we allow
this, then someone will want to ship in, say, a couple of tons.
Then the U.S. industry would be in jeopardy.''
   But officials later determined that more sugar could be imported
this year without harm to the domestic industry, and the U.S.
Department of Agriculture gave Ms. Melendy the supplies, Conroy
said.
   Ms. Melendy, a spokeswoman for the International Cake
Exploration Society's Convention and Cake Show scheduled in Tulsa
next month, was trying to help British confectioners prepare their
demonstration at the convention when she originally ran afoul of
the law.
   Elaine MacGregor and Nicolas Lodge of Sussex, England, shipped
their supplies for the convention expected to draw 1,500 cake
decorators Aug. 11-14, Ms. Melendy said.
   ``They're artists,'' Ms. Melendy said. ``They use a very fine,
extra-refined sugar. They don't like our sugar. They're just like a
sculptor or painter. They prefer using their own equipment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
