<DOCNO> AP880728-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Fashion     07-28 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Fashion,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Givenchy Shows Sexy Luxury As Couture Showings Wind Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sexy luxury at Givenchy and casual luxury at Per
Spook were the keynotes of fashion Thursday, winding up the couture
showings for winter.
   Following Spook's show, a committee of 24 international fashion
writers awarded this season's Golden Thimble prize for all-around
excellence to Dior's couturier, Marc Bohan.
   Many of the designers came to the Palais Galliera fashion museum
with a few models wearing their designs, to participate in the
Golden Thimble ceremonies.
   ``Dior's mink-trimmed taupe suits actually made me jealous,''
said couturier Louis Feraud, a top-rated designer himself. ``They
were perfectly cut and made.''
   Givenchy's suits shown in the morning were also perfectly
tailored, with nipped waists, most narrow skirts short to an inch
or two above the knee. Givenchy has been an advocate of short
skirts, but also showed some longer lengths.
   There were bursts of color, even in the fabulous furs that went
with the dresses and suits. Fox, mink and sable were dyed ruby,
violet, pastel blue and yellow to go with outfits in different
dazzling tones.
   Cloth coats were usually luxurious cashmere, of course. One
model looked great in lavender with a dark purple windowpane plaid.
Bicolored suede and satin outfits were other appealing highlights _
royal blue or amethyst with a rust belt and toque, for instance.
   There were a few pants for daytime or evening, more often than
not dressed up with neat matador boleros and Spanish grandee hats.
   Givenchy's late-day wear was more siren-bright than usual,
though a few black beaded and sequined numbers cropped up. More
frequent were the satin dresses with sashes in tones like pink and
raspberry or emerald and magenta.
   Feathers, beehive-ruffled sleeves, black velvet appliques on
bicolored stretch jersey dresses added up to coquettish looks.
   Givenchy lenghthened a few hemlines to mid-calf, though the
dressy strapless-topped models were usually clinging to the torso,
flared below the knee.
   Givenchy's funny hats were remarkable, too. Besides boaters,
there were ripple or wave shapes, lace-edged tiny cones or
jigsaw-puzzle shapes, big fur rims on wide-brimmed hats.
   Ball gowns were sumptuous as always, whether slim and with
plunging decolletes or strapless with full taffeta skirts, some
with an iridescent effect.
   Per Spook chose some short styles _ minis and full shorts, even
though they were for the fall _ or much longer skirts and pants.
   As usual, the Norwegian-born designer presented
color-coordinated groups of clothes from day to evening, all
walking out at once, an appealing way of showing a modestly winning
collection.
   Combinations of champagne and ivory, royal blue and gray,
raspberry and green and sunny yellow and brown were lively rather
than loud.
   A soft mohair boxy coat topped a full chocolate brown cashmere
skirt, the smocked silk crepe blouse echoing the tones of the
outfit.
   There was plenty of luxury in this charming collection that
featured details such as sequined bodices over full leather skirts,
fitted and piped tweed military jackets, double-flounced clinging
suede dresses, excellent flannel pants with embroidered bolero
jackets, intricate seaming on bodices and hems of evening dresses.
   Spook's strapless ballerina-length gowns and the tiered silk
dresses in white and pink ribbons looked great for young debs or
sweethearts of Sigma Chi. These final adorable dresses were
appropriately called ``La Vie en Rose.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Prices     07-28 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Prices,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Soar In China For Brand Name Cigarettes, Spirits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government raised the base prices of its best
cigarettes and liquors Thursday in an effort to break up a thriving
black market, and it allowed state-run stores to set the retail
prices for the first time.
   Store managers said that on Friday they will raise the prices
even higher.
   The cost of a pack of a popular brand of cigarettes went up
nearly 400 percent, and the price of a fifth of a bottle of spirits
shot up 750 percent. But consumers were used to paying at least
that much anyway.
   The black market holds a virtual monopoly on top-quality
cigarettes and liquor in China. Private sellers bribe store
managers to sell them the goods wholesale and then resell them to
the public at inflated prices.
   On Thursday, brand-name cigarettes and liquors surfaced in
stores for the first time in about 15 years. Business was brisk.
   At the Xidan Market in west Beijing, manager Liu Dajiang said he
sold 1,500 cartons of cigarettes in two hours during the morning.
   ``We could have sold more, but we're saving them for tomorrow to
see what price they'll fetch,'' he said.
   China, the world's largest producer and consumer of tobacco, has
300 million smokers.
   Across town at the Guandong Market, manager Zhen Ciping said
wines and cigarettes had been selling fast.
   ``Today we're experimenting, seeing which brands the masses
like,'' she said. ``Tomorrow we'll raise the prices of the popular
ones.''
   Customers complained the prices were too high, but they bought
anyway.
   ``The prices are the same as you can get from the private
sellers and that's too high,'' said customer Zhang Zhiping, holding
four cartons of popular Zhonghua cigarettes at the Xidan Market.
   The cigarettes went up almost 400 percent from 49 cents to $1.90
a pack.
   Thursday's price increases mainly affected 13 name-brand
cigarettes and 13 famous-brand spirits, although the costs of some
B-grade items also jumped.
   China is experiencing its highest inflation since 1949. Consumer
prices last month were 19 percent higher than in June 1987. Last
year, the previous high, inflation hit 7.2 percent.
   In May, the government raised the prices of vegetables, pork,
sugar and eggs as part of a far-reaching economic reform program to
end state controls of prices. Economists hope to increase
production and raise the standard of living.
   In announcing the increases Monday, the State Council, or
Cabinet, said it would let the price of the 26 brands be determined
by the market.
   Managers in state-run stores said that meant they could set
prices and reap a profit from their sales, something unheard of a
few years ago.
   According to the managers, the government set a base price. If a
store is able to sell the items for more, it can keep the
difference.
   At Guandong Market, manager Zhen said she planned to let the
workers share the profit. At Xidan, Liu said it would be invested
in the store.
   Managers said Thursday they would have no problem selling some
items for a profit.
   ``We're not even selling Maotai yet,'' Ms. Zhen said, referring
to China's popular sorghum liquor whose base price rose 750 percent
Thursday from $5.40 to $40.50 for a fifth of a gallon. ``We're
waiting to see what the market will bear.''
   But several problems were immediately apparent with the
government's plan to price the profiteers out of business.
   Only a few stores had the name-brand goods, and they had enough
for just a few days.
   Also, prices in the state-run stores still were generally below
those of the black market. Store managers said they expected
profiteers to continue to buy large quantities of cigarettes and
liquor at the state-run stores.
   ``Then they'll turn around and make a profit on our goods once
we run out,'' a shop manager said. ``This problem won't be solved
in a flash.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
