<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MesserExecution     07-28 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Messer Execution,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Inmate Nears Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for James Messer Jr. turned to the
U.S. Supreme Court after a federal appeals court refused to block
his execution tonight for the beating and stabbing death of his
8-year-old niece.
   The application for a stay of execution was filed today with
Justice Anthony Kennedy.
   The Georgia Board of Pardons and Paroles also considered a
clemency appeal.
   Messer, 34, was scheduled to die in the electric chair at 7 p.m.
for the 1979 slaying of Rhonda Joan Tanner.
   Prosecutors said he abducted his niece from school by telling
officials her father had been hurt in a construction accident, then
attempted to molest her. He attacked the girl when she fought him
and left her to bleed to death.
   Messer would be the 13th person executed in Georgia's electric
chair since the state resumed executions in 1983.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals earlier today refused to
stop the execution.
   Messer's lawyers have contended that he is mentally incompetent
and thus, under a U.S. Supreme Court ruling, cannot be put to death.
   Officials at the Georgia Diagnostic and Classification Center
near here moved Messer to a holding cell next to to the death
chamber Wednesday afternoon, said John Siler, spokesman for the
Corrections Department.
   Messer came within 15 hours of execution two years ago but won a
stay from the U.S. Supreme Court.
