<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BogusTrafficTickets     07-28 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bogus Traffic Tickets,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Office Writes Bogus Tickets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city patrolman with a heart says he has
been writing one or two bogus traffic tickets a week in the names
of non-existent motorists for about 18 months.
   ``I just could not bring myself to write tickets,'' said
Patrolman Michael Ghrist. ``I started seeing the human beings
behind the drivers' wheels.''
   Ghrist, 36, a 17-year veteran, has been suspended for 25 days.
   Police Chief Richard Dotson concluded that Ghrist wrote
fictitious tickets to maintain ``high enforcement statistics.''
   Chief Jefferson District Judge Donald Smalley said this week
that a computer listing of all the tickets Ghrist has written since
1981 shows that more than 1,000 are in the names of people for whom
state transportation employees could not find Kentucky driver's
licenses.
   ``We have to assume that almost all of them are fictitious,''
Smalley said.
   However, the official letter from Dotson to Safety Director
Thomas Kuster recommending Ghrist's suspension says only what
Ghrist has admitted _ that he wrote one or two phony tickets per
week over a year and a half.
   Kuster said Wednesday that he was unaware that more than 1,000
questionable tickets had been written.
   And Lt. Col. John Aubrey said the police internal affairs unit's
investigation of Ghrist would be reopened because of that
information.
   Each person who gets a traffic ticket is sent a letter by
District Court notifying him of his court date. If the person fails
to show up, a second letter is sent.
   If two court appearances are missed, the court sends the ticket
to the state Transportation Cabinet. That agency sends the ticketed
driver a letter warning he will lose his license if the ticket
isn't resolved within 20 days, said cabinet spokesman Mark McDaniel.
   This year, for the first time, the cabinet began sending tickets
that don't match driver's licenses back to District Court, Smalley
said.
   In a batch of about 50 returned by the state in March, clerks
discovered that Ghrist had written 29, police Maj. Hank Rausch then
asked them to do a more extensive check, Smalley said.
   Checking tickets that Ghrist wrote since 1981 for people whose
names began with the letters A through C, the clerks found about
250 for which the state had been unable to locate drivers'
licenses, Smalley said.
   He said the clerks made another check of tickets that Ghrist had
written that were never resolved and found 1,050.
   Ghrist said he admitted writing the fictitious tickets when
called to Dotson's office a few weeks ago. He said he also wrote
legitimate tickets.
   In his letter, Dotson said he considered recommending that
Ghrist be fired, but decided to be more lenient because Ghrist was
not motivated by greed. For example, he did not receive special pay
given to officers for court appearances.
   ``Rather, Officer Ghrist seems to have been motivated by a
self-imposed peer pressure to maintain high enforcement
statistics,'' Dotson wrote.
   Assistant City Law Director Paul Guagliardo said Ghrist may have
violated state law. However, Guagliardo said he never determined
which statute Ghrist could have violated because District Court
officials told Dotson they didn't wish to prosecute.
   Since January, Ghrist has been assigned to drive a vehicle that
cruises expressways to help stranded motorists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LifeAbroad-India'sMonsoon 1stLd-Writethru a0607 07-28
0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Life Abroad-India's Monsoon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: New Delhi's Monsoon _ A Time for Rejoicing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, More than ... them children, to update death
figures. Original moved in advance as b0410.</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports by
Associated Press correspondents on people, places and things in
other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI,India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the dusty days of summer, when
temperatures hover above 100 degrees for days on end, New Delhi
rejoices at the coming of the monsoon and its cooling rains.
   ``In the West, the rains are depressing. In India they are a
time of great joy, release, beauty and romance,'' says Khushwant
Singh, a noted author and journalist.
   As the rains come, the dust settles. Parched gardens suddenly
turn green. Temperatures come soothingly down and so do tempers.
   But the monsoon has its sad side.
   The rains that started early in July ended two years of drought
in northern India, promising good crops at last, but they also
unleashed floods that three weeks later had left at least 370
people dead around the country of drowning or disease spread by
contaminated water. The death toll in New Delhi from contaminated
water approached 100. A city official said more than 7,100 others
had been treated in hospitals for cholera or gastroenteritis.
   For New Delhi, the downpour broke the stifling heat, but
telephones went dead, potholes multiplied or grew deeper, and
disease became a danger as tainted water seeped into pipes and
wells.
   At the first delicious moment of the monsoon, though, the
nourishing rain kept such troubles distant.
   ``The monsoon ... for most Indians ... is not only the source of
life, but also their most exciting contact with nature,'' says
author-journalist Singh.
   When the clouds first burst open over New Delhi, dozens of
half-naked children danced gleefully in the downpour and splashed
in puddles in one impoverished neighborhood along the Yamuna River.
   ``It's always like this,'' said Gulab, an elderly woman watching
the fun. ``The children love to play in the rain, but they
invariably get sick.''
   More than 5,300 people have been treated this year for
gastro-enteritis and cholera in New Delhi. At least 182 have died,
most of them children.
   Maya Rao, a university teacher who has lived in New Delhi for
many years, described New Delhi's monsoon this way:
   ``There is muck and mud all over, mosquitoes attack you in
hordes, diseases spread like vice. It's impossible to get to places
on time, given the state of the roads, and calling people on the
phone is such a nuisance _ half the phones are dead.''
   Then, she added, there's the humidity.
   ``The moment the rain stops, you sweat to death.''
   Even so, Ms. Rao went on, she can't imagine life without the
monsoon.
   ``What could be more delightful than eating `bhutta' (roasted
corn-on-the-cob) on your terrace as the grey-purple skies melt into
rain?''
   One city official, who insisted on anonymity, said he could do
no work during the monsoon.
   ``It's too beautiful just to relax, sit and watch the rain,'' he
said, as he sat watching the rain stream down his office window.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Vanity     07-28 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Vanity,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government May Sell Vanity License Plates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has announced a new scheme to help
finance its car licensing department _ the sale of vanity plates.
   The hottest item, says Transport Secretary Paul Channon, may be
D1 ANA, which would appeal to fans of Princess Diana, wife of the
heir to the throne.
   Other likely attractions are DAV 1D, F1 RST, CHR 1S, F111 JET,
and F1 DEL.
   Because such plates must have at least one digit, zeroes pass
for the letter O, 1 for I and 5 for S.
   Channon told Parliament on Wednesday the plates will go on
auction in an effort to cut $1.7 million per year from vehicle
registration costs.
   Unlike American motorists, who for a fee can order the license
plate lettering of their choice, British drivers now depend on the
computer to churn out lucky combinations of letters and digits.
   Some of the plates slip through the system, however, and 70,000
change hands each year, some fetching thousands of dollars. Private
dealers advertise the so-called ``cherished'' plates in newspapers
and auto magazines.
</TEXT>
