<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0447 07-28 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Complain of White House `Set Up'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 6 grafs, senators complain of ``set up''; pick ups
2nd graf pvs, Both Sen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman and senior Republican on the
Senate Intelligence Committee today accused the White House of
trying to ``set up'' Congress to make it appear a news leak about a
covert action plan for Panama began on Capitol Hill.
   In fact, said Sens. David Boren, D-Okla., and William Cohen,
R-Maine, they were receiving inquiries from reporters on Tuesday
even before the CIA briefing on the plan got under way.
   ``I think the matter was handled in such a way as to set up
members of Congress to make them appear the source of the leak,''
said Cohen. ``I am offended by it.''
   Cohen said he suspected the tactic may have been designed to
damage chances for legislation opposed by the administration to
require notification of the House and Senate intelligence
committees within 48 hours of any covert action plan signed by the
president.
   The bill stemmed from last year's Iran-Contra investigation and
is designed to tighten current law, which requires only that
unspecified ``timely notice'' be given to congressional overseers.
   Boren said he also believed the leak could have been designed to
give the appearance that the Reagan administration is doing
something about the situation in Panama, which has become a
political liability for GOP presidential candidate George Bush.
   Both Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and Rep. Patricia Schroeder,
D-Colo., suggested Wednesday that the administration may have
leaked the purported plan to the news media to create the illusion
of a stepped-up campaign against Noriega.
   The reported plan was first disclosed by the Washington Post and
the Los Angeles Times, but neither newspaper provided details.
President Reagan and administration spokesmen were uniformly silent
Wednesday when asked about it by reporters.
   Informed comment about the alleged plan was scarce, and even
D'Amato and Schroeder admitted their remarks were speculative
because they had not received an official briefing.
   Published and broadcast reports said the activities fall short
of a paramilitary operation, such as kidnaping Noriega to bring him
to the United States, where he faces drug charges.
   D'Amato suggested that news leak came from the White House
``during this political season'' to create the impression that the
administration is doing something about Noriega and drug
trafficking in Panama.
   Schroeder also said Reagan authorized the activity to give the
appearance of stepping up the campaign against Noriega.
   ``It's politically motivated,'' she said.
   Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, who broke with the Noriega-led
government in February, said in an interview he is pleased that the
administration has maintained a no-negotiations policy toward
Noriega since the collapse of a U.S. bid in May to encourage him to
surrender power.
   But Sosa, who shares the administration view that ousted
Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle is the legitimate leader
in Panama, said he had not been briefed on the reported covert
action plan. This contradicted a source quoted in The Washington
Post.
   Sosa also said he doubted widespread reports that President
Reagan had informed Delvalle of the plan during a telephone
conversation on July 15.
   ``As far as I know, the conversation did not touch on that,''
said Sosa, who continues to serve at Panama's embassy here in
defiance of the Panamanian government's efforts to appoint its own
envoy.
   The administration has frozen Panamanian government assets in
the United States as part of broad policy of economic denial
against Panama. At one point, the administration was considering
dropping the drug charges against Noriega if he would leave Panama,
but talks with the military strongman broke down in May.
   The administration then withdrew its proposals and said it would
not take part in further negotiations.
   Offers by Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo and former
Venezuelan President Carlos Andres Perez to start up an alternate
negotiating process have not borne fruit.
   Noriega has refused to discuss Panama's political future since
the collapse of the U.S. initiative.
   The administration had hoped to negotiate Noriega's surrender of
power by Aug. 12, the fifth anniversary of his ascension as
commander of the Defense Forces.
   Asked what he expects Noriega to do on that day, Sosa said the
Panamanian leader will either do nothing or he will step down and
announce his candidacy for presidential elections set for next May.
   Any such elections, Sosa said, ``obviously will be a farce'' if
they are under Noriega's control.
</TEXT>
