<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish Stowaway, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0562,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-Age Irish Stowaway Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede NORFOLK, Va.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with girl turned over to Naval
investigator for trip home. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish teen-ager who stowed away on a
trans-Atlantic Navy destroyer with the alleged help of five U.S.
sailors was turned over to a Naval investigator today to be
escorted home.
   ``I just want to go home,'' Suzanne Twomey, 16, of Cork,
Ireland, told Wake County Judge Fred M. Morelock, who placed her in
the investigator's custody for a flight to New York's Kennedy
Airport and then on to Ireland later today.
   Miss Twomey had apparently slipped onto the USS Conyngham while
it was on a courtesy call in Cork Harbor and was discovered aboard
the guided missile destroyer Saturday when it returned to Norfolk,
Va., after a 10-day crossing.
   She was found in a 2{-foot-wide, 15-foot-long, 3-foot-high
compartment above a refrigeration unit that she shared with
electrical wiring and pipes.
   Five sailors accused of helping her stowaway were jailed at the
Norfolk Naval base. If charged and convicted, they could receive up
to five years in prison and a $2,000 fine for aiding an illegal
entry into the United States.
   ``There are no options but for her to return to Ireland,'' said
Daire O'Criodain, a spokesman at the Irish embassy in Washington.
   O'Criodain said Miss Twomey is a minor and has no passport.
``She is in legal limbo. ... Our course is to get her out of this
limbo as quickly as possible and get her home.''
   Miss Twomey was released Wednesday from Rex Hospital after being
treated for an undisclosed ailment. She was being taken to Atlanta
for a return flight when she became ill, forcing an emergency
landing here, authorities said.
   Assistant District Attorney J. Franklin Jackson told the judge
today that Miss Twomey was a runaway and would be considered an
undisciplined child under the American court system. The prosecutor
wished Miss Twomey luck.
   ``I need it,'' she said.
   Miss Twomey, who originally told Navy officials she was
orphaned, is the eldest of four children and has run away several
times _ once having to be returned from Spain, said a Dublin police
spokesman, who would not give his name.
   Her parents, John and Christine Twomey, had reported her
missing, according to the spokesman.
   Mrs. Twomey told the Cork Examiner newspaper it was ``a pure
disgrace'' that her daughter was able to slip through security and
stay on board. The sailors who kept her hidden ``should not be
allowed to get away with this,'' she said.
   The Navy is investigating how Miss Twomey was able to slip
aboard the destroyer and be undetected for so long, said Lt. Cmdr.
John Lloyd, spokesman for the Atlantic Fleet Surface Force. The
girl did not get into any secure areas, Lloyd said.
   ``We are cooperating with the Navy to keep this as small a black
eye as we can,'' said William Bitner, of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service's Norfolk office.
   Archie Galloway, another fleet spokesman, said the girl was
treated for dehydration Saturday at the Portsmouth Naval Hospital.
He said a full physical found no health problems.
   A Delta Airlines spokesman said the ariline had been asked by
the Navy on Wednesday to take Miss Twomey home but refused.
   ``We don't feel we're medically equipped to handle such a
happening, should the same thing happen ovver the middle of the
Atlantic,'' Billy Berry said in Atlanta, referring to the girl's
illness during the flight to Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
