<DOCNO> AP880728-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1355EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StickyStamps Bjt   07-28 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sticky Stamps, Bjt,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Seeks `Seat Belt' for Stamps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN W. CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service began a 16-month,
$700,000 quest Thursday to lick the problem of stamps that don't
stay stuck, urging industry to produce an adhesive to serve as a
``seat belt for a stamp.''
   Gordon C. Morison, a senior assistant postmaster general, made
it clear during a daylong conference at Battelle Memorial Institute
that the post office was serious about development of a superior,
water-activated adhesive.
   ``Unfortunately, the news that we have made in the last few days
is that we're spending a lot of money on something the press
perceives as insignificant,'' Morison told about 100 adhesive
industry executives and technical experts.
   He said the Postal Service would spend nearly $90 million this
year for stamps, sales of which would generate about $8 billion.
   ``I don't believe there is a private company, including those
that publish newspapers or sell their wares over the airwaves, that
would hesitate to invest $700,000 to lower the cost of their
product while making it perform better. That is exactly what we are
doing,'' Morison said.
   ``We take it seriously because we know how important that stamp
is to every American consumer,'' he told reporters during a break
in the conference. ``We really believe that we have to have a stamp
that operates very well.''
   Adhesive now used by stamp manufacturers performs well when mail
is sorted manually or mechanically. But the arrival of high-speed,
automated processing, in which stamps are coated with a compound
that activates processing equipment, has generated a need for a
stronger adhesive that will keep a stamp on an envelope.
   ``The mail is moving very quickly through our system. In doing
that, you are again putting a great deal of stress on the stamp,''
Morison said.
   He compared it to a speeding car running into a brick wall,
sending a passenger without a seat belt into the windshield.
   ``You have the same thing in sorting mail. The letter is moving
down the processing stream, and all of a sudden it stops. As soon
as it stops, it's that same kind of force as the car hitting the
brick wall,'' Morison said. ``What we are doing is developing an
adhesive that will serve as a seat belt for a stamp.''
   The Postal Service has heard from customers whose letters were
destroyed or returned because the stamps fell off, he said.
   ``The problem ... hasn't reached major proportions. But it is
clear that it will as the speed of mail processing continues to
increase as it must. The time to act is now, and we are turning to
the adhesive industry for help,'' Morison told the conference.
   Dr. Vincent McGinniss, the program project manager at Battelle,
said industries will develop potential new adhesives and supply
samples to the institute for extensive testing and evaluation.
   ``Ultimately, we will print real stamps that ... we will put
into the mail stream. We'll take them back out, find out if they
stuck, and if they stayed on then do the evaluations, a lot more
testing,'' McGinniss said in an interview.
   Battelle, a not-for-profit, multinational research and
development organization, will write adhesive specifications which
the postal service can use in buying the product from suppliers.
   Although the research should produce stickier stamps, no change
in taste is anticipated.
   ``Taste is a very personal thing. What we've always sought in
taste, and where we think we are, is neutral and bland. And we'd
like to stay neutral and bland,'' Morison said. ``Taste is in the
tongue of the users, and this contract really has nothing to do
with that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LandingShuttles Bjt   07-28 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Landing Shuttles, Bjt,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Gets White Sands Space Harbor Ready For Shuttle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronauts flying a jet
modified to act like a space shuttle make steep 19-degree dives
toward the desert floor Mondays through Fridays, flashing at 230
mph 20 feet above a runway of packed, white gypsum.
   Each time, they have to deal with a malfunctioning computer,
broken landing gear, a non-working radio or some other problem
generated by a sophisticated computer aboard the Grumman Gulfstream
II jet.
   In addition to all their other shuttle training, astronauts also
must practice for a possible landing at the alternative runway in
the desert at White Sands.
   ``It would be terrible if you had a good mission and messed it
up with a bad landing,'' said Alex Paczynski, the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration's project manager at White
Sands Space Harbor.
   Shuttle commanders Rick Hauck and shuttle pilot Dick Covey
practiced landings Wednesday in the modified jet.
   ``There's a humongous computer on board that takes the flight
characteristics of the shuttle and the flight characteristics of
the airplane and matches them together,'' Paczynski said.
   The computer can simulate a shuttle bringing back a heavy
payload, or a stiff wind, or a system malfunction or a combination
of problems.
   Hauck and Covey are scheduled to go up on the next shuttle
flight, aboard Discovery, in September or October.
   A simulated countdown leading to a test firing of the shuttle's
main engines ran into a snag Wednesday and was delayed 24 hours.
NASA engineers hope to fix a small gas leak in a vent line
associated with a steering engine without taking Discovery off the
pad and into a hangar, a move that could delay the launch as much
as two months.
   The shuttle's primary landing site is Edwards Air Force Base in
California, a dry lake bed with plenty of room to make up for a
less-than-perfect landing.
   But if it rains at Edwards, Hauck and Covey could end up gliding
down to one of the two dazzlingly white, criss-cross runways at the
White Sands dry lake bed.
   If they land at White Sands, on a dry lake bed between the San
Andreas Mountains and White Sands National Monument, they will use
a runway that has been leveled out a little better since Jack R.
Lousma landed the shuttle Columbia there on March 30, 1982.
   Engineers used lasers to check the smoothness of the runways,
Paczynski said Wednesday as he led reporters on a tour of the
100-square-mile complex in the middle of White Sands Missile Range.
   They also leveled and flattened the surface 300 feet wide on
either side of the 300-foot-wide landing strip, in effect making
the runway 900 feet wide. At 35,000 feet long, the landing strips
are about three times as long as those at commercial airports.
   July, August and September are the rainy months at White Sands,
when half of the annual 12 inches of rain falls. The ``dry'' lake
bed was decidedly wet Wednesday because three-quarters of an inch
of rain had fallen the night before, but it was still firm.
   ``Notice how the bus won't get bogged down when it comes to this
wet spot,'' Paczynski told reporters as their bus approached a
50-yard-long puddle. ``There's a very hard mantle here 2 inches
under the topsoil. That's why you could land an orbiter here even
if (the strip) were underwater. They wouldn't, but they could.''
   When the shuttle lands on the gypsum flats, it's as if it were
landing on a mile-thick, 7-mile-long piece of Sheetrock, the panels
used for interior walls.
   Prevailing southwesterly wind carries gypsum crystals from the
lake bed to the famous dunes shimmering in the distance.
   The wind and the sharp gypsum crystals created havoc the one
time a shuttle landed here.
   The de-service and mating area, where the astronauts disembark
and where the shuttle is hoisted aboard a Boeing 747 for the flight
back to Florida, was so dusty that officials feared for the
vessel's safety. So they've moved the area to a less dusty spot in
the lee of the mountains, Paczynski said.
</TEXT>
