<1ST_LINE>u w AM-USPilots-Drugs     07-28 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US Pilots-Drugs,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Defends Prescription Stimulants For Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon officials on Thursday defended the
use of prescribed stimulants to Air Force pilots on long solo
flights and said no recent crash has been linked to drug use.
   ``None of the crashes in Germany was linked to drug use,'' said
Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman. ``No crashes anywhere have been
related to drug use.''
   A West German television network reported Wednesday that U.S.
Air Force pilots there take Dexedrine to stay alert in flight and
take the sedative Seconal to sleep afterwards.
   Concern has grown in Europe following the crashes of five F-16
jet fighters in West Germany within three months this year.
   The West German network ARD quoted an unidentified U.S. Air
Force officer as saying that pilots take Dexedrine ``so that they
are able to fly when they haven't gotten enough sleep or don't feel
fit enough.''
   Consumer advocate Sidney Wolfe of Public Citizen, appearing on
the ABC-TV program ``Good Morning America, said his group was
concerned about ``a military that has to depend upon using uppers
and downers to perform well.''
   Wolfe said if commercial pilots used such drugs they would be
fired or grounded.
   ``Imagine the scenario of a fighter pilot flying one of these
planes having an hallucination and pressing the wrong button,
particularly if there is a bomb on board,'' he said.
   Hoffman and other officials said U.S. military pilots use such
stimulants on long flights across the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans,
and not on exercises over populated areas.
   ``The Air Force does not routinely prescribe medication to air
crew members, but on long flights where pilot fatigue could present
a significant safety risk, stimulant and sedative medications may
be authorized by the major command surgeon general,'' said Hoffman.
   ``Dispensing of these medications is rigidly controlled. Routine
use of these medications is never advised. The individual crew
member makes the decision to take or not to take the medication,''
he said.
   Such use, he said, was confined almost exclusively to ``long
flights. Dexedrine, Seconal and Temazepam (a stimulant) are
prescribed almost exclusively for transoceanic solo missions in
single-seat aircraft.''
   The Air Force was not considering any changes in the practice,
which has been standard for as long as 30 years, spokesmen said.
   None of the other services, the Army, Navy or Marine Corps,
prescribe such drugs for pilots, Hoffman said.
   And the Navy Medical Command issued a statement saying that it
neither prescribed nor permitted the use of such drugs on flights
by Navy pilots.
   ``The missions and environments in which Navy and Air Force
pilots fly are different,'' the Navy statement said. ``Navy pilots
seldom fly long, uninterrupted flights in single or two-seater
aircraft which Air Force pilots do regularly in deploying aircraft
across the ocean on training exercises.''
   ``As a matter of policy, naval aviators are not given
prescription stimulants or depressants for use during or after
flight,'' the Navy statement said.
   ``Only caffeine in the form of coffee and triptophan in the form
of warm milk are permitted for these purposes,'' the Navy statement
said.
   Col. Russell B. Raymond, chief of the Aerospace Medical
Consultants Division of the Air Force surgeon general's office,
said in an interview on ABC-TV that the service does ``on occasion
prescribe medication to our pilots, but these are under very
special circumstances.
   Raymond said he did not know how often the drugs are taken but
said they have been used for ``25 to 30 years, probably longer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
