<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JusticeNominees     07-28 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice Nominees,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Fears Acting Attorney General Has `Blinders On'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy said Thursday he finds
acting Deputy Attorney General Harold Christensen's optimistic
assessment of Justice Department morale ``somewhat incredible'' and
said he is concerned Christensen ``is going over there with
blinders on.''
   Christensen was the third Justice Department nominee in two days
to reject testimony by former Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns
that the department had been gripped in a ``deep malaise'' when he
resigned March 29 to protest Attorney General Edwin Meese III's
continued tenure.
   At his confirmation hearing before the Senate Judiciary
Committee, Christensen said that when he came to the Justice
Department early last month he quickly saw that its operations were
running effectively.
   ``I think morale is high,'' Christensen testified.
   Kennedy, D-Mass., questioned Christensen's portrayal twice
during the hearing and repeatedly asked the nominee why he hadn't
met with Burns and former criminal division chief William Weld
about their protest resignations stemming from Meese's refusal to
step down in the face of an ongoing criminal investigation.
   Weld said he quit because he felt Meese had committed ethical
violations and probably commited crimes as well.
   Christensen said he found it inappropriate to inquire since he
might be in a position at some point of having to make judgments of
his own.
   Kennedy said that should have prompted Christensen ``to ask more
questions, not fewer.''
   Christensen said he enjoys a close working relationship with
Meese, meeting with him usually two or three times a day, and that
he has formed no judgments of his own about ethical or legal
questions regarding the attorney general.
   Hours after independent counsel James McKay sent an 814-page
report on Meese's activities to a panel of judges on July 5, Meese
announced he would resign, and he plans to leave next month.
   McKay conducted a 14-month inquiry into Meese's actions at the
request of attorney E. Bob Wallach on behalf of scandal-plagued
Wedtech Corp. and a $1 billion Iraqi pipeline project, plus Meese's
tax filings and his stock holdings in Bell telephone companies.
   McKay concluded Meese ``probably'' broke two tax laws and twice
violated a federal conflict-of-interest statute. But McKay decided
not to indict the attorney general. Meese sharply criticized the
findings and said he had been exonerated.
   Kennedy said he found Christensen's comments ``somewhat
incredible'' and added that he is concerned the nominee ``is going
over there with blinders on.''
   The acting deputy attorney general replied, ``I don't think so,
senator.''
   The Justice Department's Office of Professional Responsibility
is conducting an ethics inquiry of Meese's activities in the wake
of the report by McKay, who decided against seeking an indictment
of the attorney general.
   The office could issue a highly critical report of the attorney
general's ethics.
   ``I would expect that office to discharge its responsibility,''
Christensen said. ``I would certainly not interfere with that
office discharging its responsibility.'' At another point in the
hearing he said, ``I would support what they are obligated to do.''
   If confirmed as deputy attorney general, the 62-year-old Salt
Lake City attorney almost certainly will be serving under Richard
Thornburgh, the former Pennsylvania GOP governor whose nomination
for attorney general has been widely praised by Republicans and
Democrats. Thornburgh's confirmation hearing is set for Aug. 5.
   Christensen, who became acting deputy attorney general June 1 _
his first government job _ was president of the Utah State Bar in
1975-76.
   At their confirmation hearing Wednesday for permanent positions,
Francis A. Keating II and Edward S.G. Dennis Jr. said the
department was running well in the final days of Meese.
</TEXT>
