<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criminal mischief charges against actor Sean
Penn were dropped Thursday after he agreed to pay for damage to a
photographer's car.
   Penn, known for running afoul of the law with his fists, was
accused of kicking in the driver's side door of New York Post
photographer Paul Adao's car on July 3. Adao said he was in the
driver's seat of his car, photographing Penn and his wife, pop
singer Madonna, when Penn attacked.
   Adao said it will cost the 27-year-old actor about $800 to fix
the car door. He said Penn will also pay the cost of renting a car
while Adao's auto is being repaired.
   Penn, the star of ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' ``The Falcon
and the Snowman'' and ``Colors,'' was released from jail in Los
Angeles on Sept. 17 after serving more than half a 60-day sentence
for violating probation by punching a movie extra.
    He had been on probation for fighting with a man he accused of
trying to kiss Madonna at a Los Angeles nightclub in 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul McCartney wants to be back in the U.S.S.R.
   The weekly Moscow News says in its July 31 edition that
McCartney's manager, Richard Ogden, approached Soviet officials
about a tour late this year or early next year.
   The former Beatle wants the trip to mark his 30th anniversary as
a musician, the newspaper said.
   McCartney has asked to play several concerts before small groups
rather than in a large arena.
   The McCartney family has asked to stay in a private home where
their cook can prepare vegetarian meals _ arrangements the
newspaper deemed ``unprecedented.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susan Sarandon, whose list of credits ranges
from the cult film ``The Rocky Horror Picture Show'' to this
summer's ``Bull Durham,'' says she never knows how a movie is going
to turn out.
   ``I've gotten fatalistic,'' the 41-year-old actress says in the
August issue of Savvy magazine. ``You hardly ever see a film that
resembles what you thought it would be.
   ``So my policy is, know exactly why you're doing a film _ for
the money, for the script, to work with certain people. And then,
months later, if the film turns out to be good and-or successful
and-or anything like what you thought it would be, that's a bonus.''
   Sarandon's next movie, ``Sweet Hearts Dance'' co-starring Don
Johnson, is due this fall.
</TEXT>
