<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalBriefs     07-28 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Shows National Womens' Group Favors Dukakis 3-to-1 Over Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national group of business women
favors Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis by nearly
3-to-1 over Republican nominee-to-be George Bush.
   A straw poll released Thursday showed Dukakis preferred by 62
percent of the 507 women polled at the National Federation of
Business and Professional Women's Clubs convention in Albuquerque.
   Bush received 23 percent.
   BPW President Betty Forbes said nearly half of those polled are
Republicans and the survey ``shows women this year aren't going to
vote the party lines. They're going to vote the issues that concern
them.''
   Dr. Ethel Klein, a political science professor at Columbia
University, said at the convention that Bush needs to portray a
future different from the past eight years in order to close the
gender gap _ the pattern of women supporting Democrats in greater
proportion than men do.
   ``The key to this election is what the Republicans do to close
that gap and what the Democrats do to sustain it,'' Ms. Klein said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson Seeks Donations To Defray Campaign Debts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson, whose failed Republican
presidential campaign is more than $1 million in debt, has asked
supporters to donate $25 each to pay his bills, a newspaper
reported Thursday.
   In a July 18 fund-raising letter, Robertson wrote that running
for president was more expensive than he first believed, The
Virginian-Pilot and The Ledger-Star of Norfolk reported. He told
supporters that failure to pay off his debts now would result in
``years of struggle'' for Robertson's family.
   ``All of my future work as your champion would then be
injured,'' he wrote.
   Americans For Robertson, the religious broadcaster's campaign
organization, was nearly $1.2 million in debt and had $28,166 as of
June 30, his most recent report to the Federal Election Commission
showed.
   Robertson complained in his letter about the treatment he
received as a candidate.
   ``My faith was ridiculed. My motives and my words were
distorted. Lies were spread about my war record, my education and
my resume. My family was savagely wounded,'' he wrote.
   Returning to campaign rhetoric, he added: ``God does not want us
to turn America over to radical feminists, drug dealers, militant
homosexuals, profligate spenders, humanists, or world communists.''
</TEXT>
