<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AirlinerInvestigation     07-28 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner Investigation,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Team Heads Home After Investigating Downing of Iranian
Jetliner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The six-member team investigating the downing
of Iran Air flight 655 left the Persian Gulf on Thursday for its
home base in Tampa, Fla., and was expected to complete its report
on the incident next week, a Pentagon spokesman said.
   The results are not likely to be announced until mid-August at
the earliest, Pentagon officials said.
   Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty, who heads the team, was to report
to the commander of U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf, Gen. George B.
Crist, at U.S. Central Command headquarters in Tampa.
   Crist, in turn, will give classified and unclassified versions
of the report to the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm.
William J. Crowe, who will pass them, with his comments, to Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci for a final review.
   ``I understand that Adm. Fogarty is prepared to report to Gen.
Crist next week,'' said Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman.
   ``The process involves review by Gen. Crist with his comments,
then Adm. Crowe, and the secretary of defense, and nothing ensues
until that review process is completed. We don't go public until
the process is completed. In short, don't expect anything next
week,'' Hoffman said.
   Pentagon officials have promised to release as soon as possible
an unclassified report on why the USS Vicennes shot down the Iran
Air A300 Airbus with 290 aboard on July 3.
   At the time, Navy officials said the officers on the Vincennes
mistook the airliner for an attacking F-14 fighter.
   The chief Pentagon spokesman, Dan Howard, told reporters
Thursday that officials were trying to avoid a repetition of the
delays experienced in releasing a report on the May 17, 1987,
attack on the USS Stark by an Iraqi fighter.
   ``In the case of the Stark investigation, it was five months
before the report was actually released. We'd like to do a better
job of getting it to you earlier,'' Howard said.
   Howard said it was ``unlikely'' the report would be released
before Carlucci returns Aug. 8 from a trip to the Soviet Union and
Turkey.
   ``I don't have a timetable for release,'' said Howard.
   Fogarty, originally asked to complete his investigation by July
15, was granted an extension through the end of July.
</TEXT>
