<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shultz-Poland     07-28 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Poland,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Leader Meets Shultz, Seeks More Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish Foreign Minister Tadeusz Olechowski met
Thursday with Secretary of State George P. Shultz and said both
sides are determined to work toward further improvements in
Polish-American relations.
   Olechowski, the first Polish foreign minister to visit
Washington in nine years, said he invited Shultz to visit Poland.
The response was one of ``general approval,'' he said but no
details were discussed.
   Polish-American relations hit bottom after Poland imposed
martial law in 1981 and outlawed the independent trade union
Solidarity. The reconciliation process began about two years ago,
highlighted by a visit to Warsaw last October by Vice President
George Bush and the lifting by last year of the economic sanctions
that had been imposed by the United States.
   ``We have normalized our relations,'' Olechowski told reporters
after a two-hour meeting with Shultz and other senior officials
from both sides.
   Although progress in bilateral relations has been made, ``we
certainly hope it's not the end of the road,'' Olechowski said.
   He said the ``ambitions, the interests and the intentions'' of
both countries are extensive and there is ``a determination on both
ends to go ahead.''
   There is room for increased political contacts and economic and
cultural cooperation, he said. ``In all areas, there are
possibilities.''
   One source of friction between the two countries is Poland's
claim that the United States has been providing financial support
to Solidarity.
   Polish authorities also believe that the West has been too slow
in extending credits that would enable Poland to overcome its
economic problems, which include a $40 billion foreign debt, the
largest in Eastern Europe.
   Olechowski's visit was his first trip outside Poland since he
became foreign minister several weeks ago. It occurred a day after
Hungarian Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz met with President
Reagan during an official visit.
   Grosz's visit also was seen as a breakthrough because no
Hungarian leader of that rank had visited Washington since Hungary
became communist 40 years ago.
   Both Hungary and Poland are members of the Soviet-led Warsaw
Pact. Asked why he was visiting Washington instead of Moscow on his
first foreign trip, Olechowski said the visit had been planned by
his predecessor, Marian Orzechowski.
</TEXT>
