<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietExchange     07-28 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Exchange,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Teen-agers Back After Two Weeks In Soviet Georgia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-agers who spent two weeks with Soviet
Georgia families said they are happy they went, but glad to get
home to food they can identify and parents who let them go places
on their own.
   ``I enjoyed visiting and they're ready to have me and my whole
family back, but I don't know if I'd want to live there,'' said
Susan Sugarman, 17. ``I guess because it's so different and I'm
used to everything here.''
   She and nine other high school students returned Tuesday from a
visit with families in Tbilisi, the capital of Soviet Georgia and
the official sister city of the U.S. Georgia's capital. The
privately arranged visit cost $1,400.
   Ten Soviet teen-agers arrive Aug. 12 for a two-week stay with
their counterparts' families.
   Miss Sugarman, who stayed with the vice chairman of the
Communist Party in Soviet Georgia, said her hosts were almost too
generous.
   ``If I liked something it was instantly mine,'' she said. ``They
would buy me everything. If I spent more than 10 seconds looking at
something, it was mine _ necklaces, rings, bracelets. My Soviet mom
gave me all this money. She gave me tons and tons of big coffee
table books about the state of Georgia.
   ``My Georgian grandmother came downstairs one day _ she didn't
speak any English _ and gave me a ring off her finger,'' she said.
``I'm sure it's a family heirloom. I'm totally scared I'm going to
lose it.
   Heather Sharp, 17, said the only money she spent was on a
chocolate ice cream cone in Moscow.
   ``It was the only thing I put in my mouth that I knew what it
would taste like,'' she said. ``I think I ate stuffed eggplant
every single night. It wasn't very good. I can't tell you what the
food was because it was completely different.''
   Miss Sharp said she got along well with her 13-year-old host,
Maia Tsintsadze.
   ``It was this little girl's dream to come to America and she
treated me with a lot of respect,'' she said.
   Miss Sharp said she wasn't impressed with the clothing styles in
the Soviet Union, but neither was her host.
   ``Their clothes were kind of old fashioned,'' she said. ``Not
hoop skirts, not that old. It wasn't trendy like our clothes. We'd
go shopping and she'd say, `You don't want to go to our clothes
stores. They're ugly. Even we don't like them.'''
   Steven Bird, 16, said he cherished the few opportunities he had
to meet people on his own.
   ``Although Russia is supposed to be a classless society, Georgia
has a very strict class system and our hosts were the creme de la
creme of Georgian society,'' he said. ``We didn't get to mix much
with the lower classes.''
   On one visit to a nearby small town, Bird said, ``people in the
street starting gravitating toward us, so we started giving out our
cards and some trinkets and sticks of gum.''
   ``I felt great that the people from this place who were
supposedly our enemies were so loving and kind to us,'' he said.
``They followed us around. The kids were shy, but they were giving
me these things out of the blue because I was there and I was
American.''
</TEXT>
