<HEAD>Canadian Jet Reports Climbing Sharply To Avoid Soviet Military
Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian jetliner with 246 passengers aboard
had to climb sharply to avoid colliding with Soviet military planes
that were intercepted by U.S. and Canadian fighters over the
Atlantic, officials said Thursday.
   ``It was a fairly close call,'' said Transport Canada spokesman
Norm Pascoe.
   The incident happened Wednesday at 12:40 p.m. EDT about 250
miles off the coast of Newfoundland and involved a Worldways Canada
DC-8 airliner, said Worldways Vice President Bill Doucette. He said
the passenger jet was flying from London's Gatwick Airport to
Ottawa and Toronto.
   Doucette said the pilot reported seeing two Soviet planes and
two fighters within 500 to 1,000 feet of his flight path.
   He ``pulled up and pulled right'' to avoid collision, Doucette
said. No one was hurt and the plane landed safely at Ottawa.
   The DC-8 was cruising at 31,000 feet and had no warning of
military traffic in the area, Doucette said.
   Capt. Don Roy of Canada's National Defense Department said two
U.S. F-15 fighters based in Maine and two Canadian CF-18 fighters
from Quebec had been sent to intercept two Soviet Bear-H
reconnaissance aircraft in what he termed a ``normal intercept.''
   The Soviet planes were in international airspace, but Roy said
U.S. and Canadian jets intercept Soviet aircraft that close to the
coast ``to let them know we know they're there.'' It was the 16th
intercept this year.
   He said it was up to civilian air traffic control to inform the
DC-8 of any military traffic in the area.
   The Canadian Aviation Safety Board was expected to investigate
why there was an apparent breakdown in communications.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
