<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     07-28 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says Hamadi Brother Bragged Mohammed Was Involved in
Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness testified Thursday that
Mohammed Ali Hamadi's older brother bragged in a West German bar
shortly after a 1985 TWA hijacking that Mohammed was involved in
seizing the jetliner.
   Another acquaintance of Mohammed Hamadi testified that the
defendant was ``crazy about Khomeini'' (Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, Iran's revolutionary patriarch), and a third said Hamadi
admitted belonging to Hezbollah, the pro-Iranian radical Shiite
Moslem group linked to kidnappings in Lebanon.
   Mohammed Hamadi is accused of being one of the hijackers of TWA
flight 847, which was seized on June 14, 1985 and diverted to
Beirut, Lebanon. The gunmen killed U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem
and held 39 Americans hostage for 17 days.
   A West German court convicted Hamadi's older brother, Abbas, in
April of kidnapping two West Germans in Beirut in an attempt to
force West Germany to free Mohammed.
   Gaazi Yazbeck, a Lebanese man who lives in West Germany and
knows the two Hamadis, was asked in court if Mohammed Hamadi ever
mentioned the hijacking to him.
   ``No, Mohammed said nothing. But his brother, Abbas, said
Mohammed had something to do with the hijacking,'' Yazbeck replied.
``He just said it, he was sort of bragging.''
   Yazbeck said the conversation occurred ``a few weeks after the
airplane was hijacked'' at a bar in Saarland state, where Abbas
Hamadi was then living.
   Another witness, Elfriede Akcura, said she befriended Mohammed
Hamadi while he lived in West Germany from 1982-1984 and they
frequently discussed religion.
   ``He was crazy about Khomeini,'' she said. ``He is a Khomeini
follower.''
   Witness Reinhard Schmid, who shared a cell with Hamadi for six
months in 1987, said that at one point Hamadi admitted to being a
member of Hezbollah.
   Schmid, who was in prison for a drug offense but is now free,
said he asked Hamadi what Hezbollah's goals were and quoted Hamadi
as replying, ``The goal of the Hezbollah is to wipe out the
Zionists even if it takes generations.''
   He said Hamadi told him Hezbollah's enemies were Israel,
``France and those supported by the Americans.''
   Schmid told the court that during their conversations Hamadi
insisted he had nothing to do with the hijacking.
   But he said Hamadi also told him ``he was willing to confess to
anything if his boss in Lebanon told him to, including that he was
in the airplane and shot at Stethem, regardless of the
consequences.''
   Schmid said that after former hostages viewed Hamadi in a lineup
and said they recognized him, Hamadi told him: ``I don't know how
they can recognize me, because I had nothing to do with it.''
   Mohammed Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport on Jan. 13,
1987, after customs officials discovered liquid explosives in his
luggage.
   Two West Germans, Rudolf Cordes and Alfred Schmidt, were
kidnapped shortly after in Beirut.
   Abbas Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport after returning
from Lebanon on Jan. 26, 1987, and was charged with the abductions.
   The kidnappers freed Schmidt in September. Cordes remains a
hostage.
</TEXT>
