<HEAD>New NBC News Chief Jokes About Making News Duller</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael G. Gartner, the new president of NBC
News, might have caused some palpitations among his subordinates
Thursday when he talked about his standards.
   ``My favorite network is the BBC,'' Gartner said in a
closed-circuit broadcast to NBC employees and affiliates, ``and I
think if we just had somebody standing there reading the news, and
could get rid of all this film and everything, it would be far more
palatable.''
   Just kidding, he added, indicating that he had no plans to
drastically change the look of NBC's ``Nightly News.''
   ``I happen to think that in Tom Brokaw and in all the producers
here, we have the greatest news organization in the world. So the
answer is, I like NBC,'' Gartner said.
   Gartner, 49, was appointed Wednesday to replace Lawrence K.
Grossman, who stepped down after four years as head of the news
division. Gartner, a former editor of the Des Moines (Iowa)
Register and The Courier-Journal of Louisville, Ky., was most
recently editor and part-owner of the Ames (Iowa) Daily Tribune and
a general executive of Gannett Co. Inc.
