<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Congress-Drought 1stLd-Writethru a0701 07-28 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drought, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Drought Bill After Scaling Back Dairy Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops with three grafs to update with House passage; pkup 2nd
graf pvs: ``This offers stability ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed 368-29 on Thursday a $5.8
billion relief package for drought-stricken farmers after scaling
back a heavily debated price-support increase for the dairy
industry.
   ``Hold on,'' House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de
la Garza, D-Texas, declared as the House approved the measure.
``Help is coming in a sensible, rational, compassionate way.''
   Approval came after dairy-state lawmakers responded to a
drumroll of criticism by compromising on a plan to increase the
price-support level for milk. The House adopted 217-181 a
scaled-back version that still would leave the cost of the benefit
above the $100 million level.
   ``This offers stability for our dairy farmers,'' Rep. Steve
Gunderson, R-Wis., declared as the House approved his plan to
impose a 50-cent increase in the milk price-support level, but only
for three months.
   The action resolved the most heavily debated issue in the House
version of the drought aid package. The Senate was expected to rush
the measure through with equal dispatch, possibly before the night
was out.
   Both House and Senate were working on highly similar versions of
the bill with an eye toward putting the bill before the president
at least by Aug. 11, when lawmakers are set to flee Washington's
summer heat.
   ``This bill is the most generous disaster relief package ever
considered by the Senate,'' Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick
J. Leahy, D-Vt., said as debate began in that chamber.
   At the core of both bills is a provision that would pay
drought-stricken farmers 65 percent of lost earnings from crop
damage in excess of 35 percent of the harvest expected before
blazing sun and a shortage of rainfall hammered the Midwest.
   Key provisions also would streamline and expand government
programs to aid livestock and dairy producers forced to pay
escalating feed costs because the drought has burned away a
substantial quantity of hay and feedgrains.
   Gunderson and Penny offered their plan to scale back the dairy
provision after the original version came under criticism from the
Reagan administration as excessively costly.
   Sponsored by Rep. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt., the original version
would have imposed an increase in the dairy price support level of
50 cents on Oct. 1 to $11.10 for each 100 pounds of milk. That
would cost consumers, at most, a few cents per gallon in increased
milk prices.
   Dairy-state lawmakers said the cost to the government would be
$145 million, while Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng said in a
letter to the House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de
la Garza, D-Texas, on Wednesday night that the actual cost would be
$300 million.
   Lawmakers said that the Gunderson-Penny plan, limiting the
increase to a three-month period from April through June next year,
would reduce costs by perhaps $30 million.
   Dairy-state lawmakers have been saying that the increase is
warranted to avert a milk shortage looming over the country next
spring and because milk producers have faced greater feed costs
while not receiving the disaster payments that the bill allocates
for crop producers.
   But the increase has come under fire not only from the Reagan
administration but from an array of business groups and even farm
organizations that most often ally themselves with dairymen in
matters involving farm-subsidy legislation.
   ``This is a most dangerous and wrongheaded precedent,'' Rep. Pat
Roberts, R-Kan., told the House in urging it to slash any
price-support increase from the legislation. ``Should those in the
cattle business, in the sheep and the poultry business, be asked to
pay the same high feed costs without some similar subsidy _ that's
not fair.''
   Before taking up the dairy issue, the House approved an
amendment sponsored by de la Garza that would bring the estimate
cost to $5.8 billion. When the measure came to the floor, the price
tag was placed at $6.9 billion by the Agriculture Committee staff.
   The reason was because of a provision that would have required
the Agriculture Department to pay half of the cost of reseeding and
other seeding of drought-burned pastures in 20 states. The measure
sponsored by Rep. Claude Harris, D-Ala., was harnessed to the bill
when the Agriculture Committee was racing to wrap up work and later
estimated to have a $1.2 billion cost.
   De la Garza's amendment reduced the overall cost of the bill by
shrinking the seeding provision.
   Even then, House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, acknowledged
Thursday morning that there was no way to be perfectly sure of
exactly how much the drought bill would cost. Farm lawmakers have
been saying that fiscal watchdogs worried about the spending level
have nothing to complain about because it would be less than
federal savings realized because of the drought.
   But Wright said there was no certainty.
   ``The art of economics is not a precise one,'' Wright said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
