<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Soviet-Africa     07-28 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Africa,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials To Discuss Prospects for Angola Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top Soviet and American officials will meet in
Geneva starting Sunday to exchange views on the prospects for a
negotiated withdrawal of all foreign forces from southwestern
Africa, the State Department said Thursday.
   Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs Chester Crocker
will lead the U.S. delegation and Deputy Foreign Minister Anatoly
Adamyshin will head the Soviet side.
   The two days of talks will take place on the eve of a new round
of negotiations aimed at achieving the withdrawal of foreign forces
from Angola and Namibian independence from South Africa.
   The negotiations, also set for Geneva, involve Cuba, Angola and
South Africa with the United States playing a mediating role. The
talks will be held from Aug. 2-4 with Crocker representing the
United States.
   He has spent seven years attempting to arrange a settlement but,
with five armies involved in the conflict and the negotiations
plagued by mutual distrust among the participants, the task has not
been easy.
   During the last round of talks, Cuba, Angola and South Africa
reached agreement on a statement of principles governing future
negotiations.
   The next round is expected to include discussions on a timetable
for the withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban forces from
Angola, where South Africa also has several thousand troops
deployed in support of a U.S.-backed rebel group.
   The Soviets also play a key role in the conflict because of
their extensive military support for Angola's Marxist government.
In the talks starting Sunday, Crocker is expected ask Adamyshin
about Soviet willingness to encourage a final settlement. In
discussions over the past year, the Soviets have indicated a
positive attitude toward the negotiations and Cuba has been sending
out similar signals.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman also said Crocker and
Adamyshin also will discuss the situation in the Horn of Africa,
where there has been continued civil strife in Ethiopia, the Sudan
and Somalia.
   U.S. officials, insisting on anonymity, said the Soviet-backed
government in Ethiopia has been supporting insurgents in both the
Sudan and Somalia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
