<HEAD>Cher and Boyfriend Say Media Spotlight to Blame for Incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher and her boyfriend angrily denied
Thursday that he tried to run down a photographer with her sports
car, blaming the resulting crash on frustration with being
constantly dogged by the media.
   Robert Camilletti, live-in boyfriend of the
singer-turned-actress, told reporters he lost control of the car
while swerving into the driveway of Cher's home in hopes of ducking
photographers camped outside.
   ``I never had any intention of ever hurting anyone at any
time,'' he said.
   The wreck outside Cher's Benedict Canyon home Wednesday heavily
damaged Cher's Ferrari and the photographer's car, but no one was
injured. Camilletti was arrested and booked for investigation of
felony assualt with a deadly weapon on free-lance photographer
Peter Brandt, 35. No charges have been filed.
   ``He tried to kill me. He tried to run me over at a high rate of
speed,'' Brandt said after the incident. ``I was within my rights.
I would never do anything illegal.''
   Cher, 42, and Camilletti, 24, have been companions since meeting
at a New York nightclub on her 40th birthday. A former New York
bagel maker, pizza chef and bartender, Camilletti is pursuing an
acting career and recently completed shooting of ``Loverboy'' with
Kate Jackson and Kirstie Alley.
   At a news conference closed to most free-lance photographers and
representatives of the tabloid press, the couple discussed a litany
of grievances stemming from the spotlight on their relationship.
Cher, known for her revealing costumes, wore black pants, tunic and
jacket.
   Cher directed most of her anger at the tabloid press, but said
inaccurate stories about her had also been carried by the media in
general.
   ``I know that I have to give up lots of my rights, that people
can write in a magazine that I, you know, don't have my rib cage,
or that this is not my chin, or these are not my cheeks,'' she said.
   Since Cher won an Academy Award for her role in the movie
``Moonstruck,'' various publications have reported that the couple
is due to marry, that she is pregnant, which she denied, and that
she has undergone drastic plastic surgery to maintain her willowy
figure and high cheek bones, she said.
   ``I've been doing this for 25 years, and so I'm pretty much used
to having my private life destroyed and lies told about me,'' said
Cher, who began her public career in the 1960s as half of the
husband-wife duo Sonny & Cher.
   ``It's something that you pretty much have to get used to. After
a while it really bothers you and disrupts your family life. ...
I'm usually pretty good about it. I'm getting really, really
angry,'' she said.
   Cher said she didn't believe her boyfriend was capable of
intentionally hurting anyone.
   ``I know Robert. He is not a violent man. This is not Sean Penn
and Madonna,'' Cher said, referring to the pugnacious actor who's
had a number of well-publicized run-ins with photographers. She
hastened to add that Penn is ``the sweetest boy I've ever known''
and that his outbursts were also triggered by intense media
scrutiny.
   The couple refused to talk about possible legal action against
the photographer, whom they claimed was harassing them, and they
left the news conference without addressing media reports that
marriage was imminent.
   In a statement prepared by the couple's lawyer, Camilletti
called the crash the culmination of weeks of frustration.
   When Brandt and another photographer stepped into the road to
photograph Camilletti, he said he swerved toward the driveway, the
brakes of the Ferrari locked and the car slid into Brandt's Honda.
   Camilletti acknowledged that he smashed Brandt's camera in
frustration after the two photographers fled. Camiletti was
released on $2,000 bond.
</TEXT>
