<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For professional whistler Joel Brandon it's not a
matter of putting his lips together and blowing.
   He inhales.
   ``I also sort of pop the notes off with my tongue a lot of the
time to get a more staccato effect than most whistlers use,''
Brandon said Wednesday. ``That's especially good for the Bach and
Handel pieces I like to do with symphony orchestras and in some
jazz improvisation.''
   Brandon, 40, won the 10th International Whistle-Off contest in
Carson City, Nev., earlier this year and won the championship of
the National Whistlers' Convention in Louisburg, N.C., for a second
year in a row.
   Brandon says he learned his unusual inhalation technique by
accident while walking on the street in Chicago when he was 7 or 8
years old.
   ``I was whistling, and I inhaled and made a sound I'd never made
before,'' he said.
   The technique has taken him to performances with several
symphony orchestras, night club engagements and an appearance on
Johnny Carson's television show.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry and Susan Beebe never pictured
themselves as detectives, but a mud-covered photo album helped them
solve a mystery.
   Beebe recently found the photo album and its pictures strewn
over a highway near the Platte River.
   He wanted to return the album to its owner, but there was no
name or address in the album and most of the photos had only first
names. The Beebes didn't recognize any of the locations.
   They spread the 200 or so photos on their living room floor to
dry, arranged them in chronological order and began looking for
clues.
   One photo, marked ``Grandma Van Wagenen,'' showed an elderly
woman standing in a backyard, overlooking a farm. A photo of a
college graduation was the only one marked with a place _ a photo
studio in Rome, N.Y.
   Beebe, 50, called directory assistance asked for a Van Wagenen
in Rome. The first Van Wagenen he called couldn't help, but gave
Beebe the numbers of some others.
   Harold Van Wagenen told Beebe he thought the album might belong
to a relative, Master Sgt. David Mathis, who is stationed at
Ellsworth Air Force Base in South Dakota.
   Beebe called Mathis' mother, Lois, in West Leyden, N.Y., who
provided the big break.
   ``Oh, that's Suzie's,'' said Mrs. Mathis.
   ``Suzie'' is Air Force Capt. Suzanne Sauer, who is stationed at
Offutt Air Force Base, just miles from where the photo album was
found.
   ``I was dumbfounded,'' Sauer said. ``I said, `I can't believe
you did this for me.'''
   Sauer said the album apparently fell out of her car while she
was moving.
   Beebe said he enjoyed the challenge and refused any reward,
including reimbursement for his long-distance phone calls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Horning's 40th birthday celebration
started in Moscow and ended in San Francisco, but you couldn't call
it a bash.
   Call it a wash perhaps _ he marked the event by swimming under
three bridges in different parts of the world.
   Twenty-nine hours after his personal challenge began in Moscow,
Horning walked out of San Francisco Bay Wednesday night to be
greeted by a crowd of mostly strangers.
   ``It was great,'' he said with a smile. ``It's great to be 40.''
   Horning began the day in Moscow with a 3.7-mile swim in the
Moscow River in the capital of the Soviet Union. Then he jumped on
a jet to New York and swam a mile in the East River and under the
Brooklyn Bridge. Then he flew back to San Francisco to splash
through the fog and the final two miles.
   Celebrating his birthday with exotic swims has become a
tradition for Horning, beginning in 1982 when he swam around
Manhattan.
   ``Moscow was great, New York was great and it's great to be
home,'' the Berkeley resident said when he got out of the water.
``I've never swum out here at night before, but it was great''
   The crowd chanted ``Swim, Dave, swim!'' and then sang ``Happy
Birthday'' when Horning came ashore.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NATCHEZ, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Disney Channel has chosen a Broadway
and movie veteran to portray the childhood companion of Mississippi
writer Willie Morris. And Morris says he's glad they got an
intelligent dog who can drive.
   ``Old Skip would be highly pleased that he's being played by a
Broadway and movie dog,'' Morris said about the selection of Moose
to play his pet in the production of Morris' 1971 book, ``Good Ole
Boy.''
   The full-length, made-for-cable movie was filmed in and around
Natchez.
   In June, Morris said he hoped a superstar dog would be chosen to
play Old Skip. Disney auditioned some local dogs, but finally
settled on Moose.
   Set in the 1940s, the story is about Morris' boyhood in Yazoo
City. The dog in the book goes shopping, plays football, becomes a
hero and teases the townspeople by pretending to drive a car.
   The role of Old Skip went to Moose, who played Sandy, the canine
pal of Orphan Annie, in a national Broadway tour of the musical
``Annie.'' The Airedale also performed in the off-Broadway
production of the ``Miracle Worker,'' and appeared with Robin
Williams in the PBS movie ``Seize the Day.''
   ``I'm very impressed. Moose did drive a car in a couple of
scenes, which is crucial,'' Morris said.
   ``I do like his looks,'' Morris said of Moose. ``Although he is
from Staten Island, he has all the appearances of a Mississippi
dog. He barks with a Southern accent. I think that comes from
acting experience.''
