<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fortas-Biography     07-28 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fortas-Biography,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biography Details Fortas' Resignation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abe Fortas was tricked into taking a
seat on the U.S. Supreme Court and later was bluffed into becoming
the first justice ever to resign in disgrace, the author of a new
book said Thursday.
   Using records President Lyndon Johnson once ordered destroyed,
author Bruce Allen Murphy also details Fortas' extensive role as an
adviser in the president's inner circle, unprecedented for a
sitting justice.
   ``The book is like a murder mystery: Who killed Abe Fortas'
career?'' said Murphy, whose research took him to libraries in
Boston, Philadelphia, New York, Washington and New Haven, Conn. His
book, ``Fortas: The Rise and Ruin of a Supreme Court Justice,''
will be released Friday.
   Johnson repeatedly asked Fortas to accept the nomination for a
seat on the Supreme Court, but the prominent Washington attorney
each time turned down the offer.
   LBJ got Fortas to accept the job in 1965 by saying the president
needed his friend's help drafting a statement to the press on a
troop increase in Vietnam.
   While they rode the White House elevator to the East Room to
meet the press, Johnson told Fortas that in a few minutes he would
be announced as the nominee to the Supreme Court.
   Four years after he joined the Supreme Court, Fortas resigned
for accepting a $20,000-a-year salary to work for a foundation set
up by millionaire industrialist Louis Wolfson while he was a member
of the court. Supreme Court justices made $39,500 at the time.
   Attorney General John Mitchell's Justice Department bluffed
Fortas into leaving the court by intimating it had more damaging
evidence than the money from Wolfson, which had been returned,
Murphy said.
   Murphy discovered photocopies of Justice Department documents in
the papers of the late Chief Justice Earl Warren.
   Fortas, who died in 1982, ``represents the turning point in the
United State Supreme Court history in the 20th century,'' said
Murphy.
   Without Fortas, liberal Arthur Goldberg would have remained on
the bench and might have succeeded Warren as chief justice during
the Johnson administration, said Murphy, 36, a professor of
political science at Penn State University.
   Instead, Johnson persuaded Goldberg to leave the court to become
ambassador to the United Nations to make room for Fortas.
   The Senate rejected Fortas' nomination as chief justice and his
1969 resignation allowed Richard Nixon to appoint two members of
the court and making the court more conservative, Murphy said.
   Johnson ordered all his files on Fortas destroyed during the
tough Senate confirmation hearings for Fortas as chief justice,
Murphy said.
   Aides disobeyed the order and sent the papers, locked in a safe,
to the Lyndon B. Johnson Library in Austin, Texas, where Murphy,
who spent six years researching his book, found them.
   Fortas destroyed all his own personal and professional records,
even typed copies of speeched he delivered.
   In the file at the Johnson Library, Murphy found records of
White House meetings Fortas attended on proposed legislation,
Johnson's speeches and the Vietnam War.
   Murphy, who had only one interview with Fortas before he died,
said Fortas' soft, melodious voice, sharp analytical mind and
ability to convert complex legal issues into understandable terms
caused his rise from poverty in Memphis, Tenn., to Washington's
inner circles.
   Murphy also explored extra-judicial activities in ``The
Brandeis-Frankfurter Connection: The Secret Political Activities of
Two Supreme Court Justices,'' which was published in 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
