<HEAD>Bush Telephoning Veep Prospects; List Now Over 12</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 6 grafs with Bush calls to Quayle and Domenici
and CORRECTS that Bush call to Quayle was Monday, not Thursday,
picking up in 3rd graf pvs, Bush who; subs 6th graf pvs, Campaign
sources, to remove Domenici first name</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush has called more than a
dozen prospective running mates, aides said Thursday, while Bush
himself said merely that his selection effort has been orderly and
that public speculation is inevitable.
   Widening the list of prospects, Bush and aides have been in
contact several times this week with Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., whose
name did not figure in earlier speculation.
   Quayle spokesman Jeff Nesbit said that the vice president had
called Quayle on Monday, and that the call was followed up by a
visit to Quayle's office on Tuesday by Robert M. Kimmitt, the
Washington lawyer who is overseeing the screening process of
potential candidates.
   Bush aides further contacted Quayle on Thursday, Nesbit said.
   ``He would accept it if asked,'' Nesbit said.
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., also confirmed on Thursday that
he had been approached by the vice president, saying he was proud
and honored to be on the list. ``I know it will be a difficult
decision for the vice president to make,'' he said in a statement.
   Bush, who says he will not make his final choice until the
Republican National Convention next month, has now all but
completed calls to prospective candidates on his so-called ``long
list,'' said an aide who spoke only on the condition of anonymity.
   ``He's only talking to people he's considering,'' said the aide.
   ``I would suspect that process is complete,'' the aide said.
``That doesn't preclude some new calls tomorrow or the next day.
The process is fluid and he's controlling it.''
   Campaign sources said the vice president had earlier placed
similar calls to _ or contacted personally _ his strongest
primary-campaign rival, Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kans.; Dole's wife, former
Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, and Sens. Domenici, Alan
Simpson, R-Wyo., William L. Armstrong, R-Colo, John Danforth,
R-Mo., and Nancy L. Kassebaum, R-Kans.
   Also already contacted, the sources said, were Rep. Jack Kemp,
R-N.Y., Governors Thomas H. Kean of New Jersey, John Sununu of New
Hampshire, Carroll A.Campbell of South Carolina, George Deukmejian
of California, and former Governors Lamar Alexander of Tennessee
and Richard Thornburg of Pennsylvania, who recently was nominated
by President Reagan to be attorney general.
   One on the list, Bob Dole, wasn't acknowledging his call, at
least publicly. He joked that he and his wife had been ``waiting
for the phone to ring at home. I can't get Elizabeth to leave the
house.''
   Speaking at a fund-raising breakfast, the Senate minority leader
joked that he hoped Bush's choice of a running mate would be
narrowed to just him and his wife, ``and I drop out.''
   However, Bush himself told reporters last week that Bob Dole
would be on ``any list'' of potential running mates.
   Calls from the vice president were an early stage of the
selection process. Bush had said he hoped to have a tentative list
completed by week's end.
   Washington attorney Robert M. Kimmitt is overseeing the
screening process, including the distribution of questionnaires
seeking financial and personal background information from
prospective candidates.
   The vice president told reporters outside his White House office
on Thursday that speculation over his running mate was inevitable.
``You can't avoid speculation,'' Bush said.
   ``The process is going along in an orderly fashion. Hopefully,
it won't be demeaning to anyone,'' he said.
   Bush, who had no public events scheduled on Thursday, was to
visit a child-care center Friday morning in a northern Virginia
suburb of Washington.
   ``He wanted to follow up on his child-care initiative,'' said
Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate.
   Bush on Sunday proposed a $1,000 tax credit for child care
primarily aimed at low-income working mothers.
   Meanwhile, Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said that recent
polls showing Bush trailing Michael Dukakis by as much as 18 points
coming out of the Democratic National Convention had been expected.
   ``I figured it could go up to 20 points,'' Atwater said in an
interview. ``Polls right after a convention don't mean anything.''
   ``As Walter Mondale said in l984, `Where's the beef?''' Atwater
said, referring to the 1984 Democratic presidential candidate's use
of a fast-food advertising slogan to refer to then-rival Gary
Hart's Democratic primary theme of ``new ideas.''
   ``There's no substance whatsoever in Dukakis' campaign,''
Atwater said. ``We're going to point out over and over again that
George Bush's campaign is one of issues and substance.''
