<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BankDeregulation-Glance     07-28 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Deregulation-Glance,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Bank Deregulation Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the key provisions of
far-reaching bank deregulation legislation approved, 30-20,
Thursday by the House Banking Committee:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SECURITIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The bill grants bank holding companies the power, through
separately capitalized subsidiaries, to underwrite corporate bonds,
mutual funds, commerical paper, corporate debt convertible to stock
and securities backed by mortgages and other consumer loans.
   A bank would not have to form a holding company to underwrite
municipal bonds or to sell shares in a mutual fund underwritten by
another company.
   Securities firms retain exclusive rights to the biggest area of
securities underwriting: corporate stock.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SAFEGUARDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Affiliated banks and securities firms are barred from sharing
the same name, logo, advertising or premises. The securities
subsidiary will be required to inform customers they are not
dealing with a federally insured bank.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INSURANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The legislation limits banks' ability to expand into insurance.
National banks and state-chartered banks owned by holding
companies, which are regulated on the federal level, will not be
allowed to underwrite insurance, unless they already do so.
Free-standing state banks remain governed by state laws.
   If state law permits, state banks will be allowed to sell
insurance, unless they are owned by an out-of-state holding
company. There is an exemption for national banks serving
communities of 5,000 population and less.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REAL ESTATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   National banks and state banks owned by a holding company will
be banned for two years from entering the real estate business.
Banks currently engaged in real estate activies may continue.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONSUMERS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Banks will be required to demonstrate a good record of lending
to poor neighborhoods before receiving Federal Reserve Board
permission to engage in new powers. Agricultural banks with assets
of less than $50 million and all commercial banks with assets less
than $25 million are exempted
   Banks will also be required to offer low-fee, low-service
``lifeline'' checking accounts to poor customers. They can be
opened for as little as $25 and can have a balance as high as
$1,000. However, customers will have to pay extra to write more
than 10 checks per month.
   Special checking accounts must be offered to poor people who
only want to cash government checks up to $1,500 such as Social
Security and welfare payments. No more than $2 may be charged per
check for the cashing service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ChemicalWeapons 1stLd-Writethru a0652 07-28 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Weapons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Discloses Production Sites of Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Pentagon comment, LEADS with 3 grafs, picking
up 3rd pvs `The United States' and INSERTS 7 grafs after 11th pvs
`The production', PICKING up 13th `Delegates have.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. official made the first disclosure of the
location of American production facilities for chemical weapons in
an attempt Thursday to speed talks aimed at banning the manufacture
and use of such weapons.
   In Washington, an Army spokesman said chemical weapons were
being produced or stored at only two of the five sites named by Max
Friedersdorf, chief U.S. delegate to the 40-nation Conference on
Disarmament.
   Friedersdorf told the conference his announcement was an
unprecedented step toward greater openness.
   The United States previously declared the location of its
stockpiles and the types of chemicals contained in them, but not
the amount or the location of the production facilities. The Soviet
Union has declared the amount of its stockpiles, but not their
location, nor the location of production sites.
   Friedersdorf said his delegation hoped the declaration would
``contribute both to greater confidence and to the negotiation of
related provisions'' of a convention banning the production,
stockpiling and use of chemical weapons.
   The Geneva conference has been negotiating such a convention for
20 years. This year's summer session began July 7.
   ``The declaration we are making today is unprecedented,''
Friedersdorf said, adding that no other conference member had
provided information on chemical weapons production facilities.
   ``We urge other countries that possess chemical weapons
production facilities to declare the locations of their facilities
and to outline how the facilities would be destroyed,'' he said.
   The United States and Soviet Union are the only two members of
the conference who have acknowledged possessing chemical weapons.
Many conference members have declared that they do not possess
chemical weapons, but Friedersdorf indicated in his speech that the
United States does not believe some of them. He declined to say
which countries.
   Washington has said previously it believes about 15 nations
possess such weapons, but it consistently declines to identify them.
   In December, the Soviet Union said its chemical weapon stocks
total 50,000 tons, but Western experts have estimated the total is
much higher. The Soviet Union also said it had no stocks outside
its borders, a contention that also has been challenged by the
United States.
   The production facilities declared by the United States are
Rocky Mountain Arsenal in Colorado; the Pine Bluff Arsenal in
Arkansas, which produces the new binary chemical weapons; Muscle
Shoals in Alabama; Newport Army Ammunition Depot in Indiana; and
Aberdeen Proving Ground in Maryland.
   At the Pentagon, Lt. Col. John Chapla said chemical weapons
currently are produced or stored only at Pine Bluff and Muscle
Shoals.
   ``These are locations which are at present or were at one time
involved in the production of chemical weapons,'' Chapla said of
Friedersdorf's list. ``At Rocky Mountain and Newport, there is no
chemical weapon production, testing or storage going on.''
   Chapla said Aberdeen is used to test some components of the
current generation of chemical weapons but is not used to produce,
store or test the binary, or dual chemical, weapons the military
now uses.
   ``Our focus now is the production of binary chemical,
principally at Pine Bluff,'' he said.
   Some work is also done at Muscle Shoals on one of the chemicals
used in binary weapons but the weapon is not deadly until the two
chemicals are combined, Chapla said.
   ``The binary program is such that you never have a complete
weapon stored in any one place,'' he said. ``The two chemicals are
never kept together and they will not be mated until just before
firing.''
   At the Geneva conference, the United States also submitted to
the conference ideas for methods to destroy chemical weapons under
an eventual ban.
   Delegates have drafted many parts of a chemical weapons ban. The
main unresolved issue is how to guard against cheating.
   Other problems include ensuring that the maximum number of
countries joins the ban, maintaining a military balance while
stocks are gradually destroyed, and precisely defining chemical
weapons.
   Friedersdorf said in his speech that ``an agreed definition (of
chemical weapons) is within reach'' and the conference has made
``significant progress'' toward resolving some issues in the past
months. He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
