<HEAD>Bentsen Cheered By Union Members in Attacks on Administration</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bentsen drug comments, subbing 2nd graf and
adding 3 grafs at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen told a union audience Thursday that the only time the
Reagan administration cares about American workers is ``when they
want to put 2 million of them on polygraph machines.''
   Later Thursday, in a speech in Reno, Nev., Bentsen criticized
Reagan administration drug-fighting efforts. He also planned to
visit Los Angeles and Amarillo, Texas, on his first solo campaign
trip since being nominated last week in Atlanta.
   The United Food and Commercial Workers convention gave a noisy
welcome to Bentsen in San Francisco. Many of the 3,500 members in
the audience were wearing ``I Like Mike'' T-shirts and waving
union-prepared signs for presidential nominee Michael Dukakis and
Bentsen.
   Earlier this year, the union was credited by lawmakers with
helping with compromise language in legislation that barred most
polygraph tests of job applicants by private businesses.
Administration officials had opposed the separate versions passed
by the House and Senate, but President Reagan signed the compromise
final version last spring.
   The congressional Office of Technology Assessment has estimated
that about 2 million polygraph tests are given each year, most of
them by private businesses.
   Four years ago, Reagan received nearly half the votes of the
traditionally Democratic members of the union, said spokesman Al
Zack. But he released a poll _ taken prior to last week's
Democratic National Convention _ showing the 1.1 million-member
union was 2-to-1 in favor of the Democrats this year.
   ``Those union members who were hoodwinked by Ronald Reagan are
coming home, in droves,'' said UFCW President William H. Wynn.
   The convention was to hear from Dukakis later by satellite
television hookup. After that, Wynn scheduled action on a
resolution putting his union on record in favor of the ticket and
requesting the parent AFL-CIO to make a formal endorsement.
   Bentsen made the most of his Senate record before the crowd,
citing this year's fights with the Reagan administration over the
trade bill and the sixty-days notice for plant closings.
   The Texas senator said administration officials have ``dragged
their feet for eight years'' when action was needed to help
American industry compete. ``Their indifference has cost America
more than a million manufacturing jobs and caused trade deficits
that will cripple growth,'' Bentsen said.
   ``Sure, the Reagan-Bush administration occasionally pays
attention to working men and women in America _ like when they want
to put 2 million of them on polygraph machines,'' he said.
   He said the Reagan-Bush record for women and minorities amounted
to a ``speed bump on the path to equality in America.''
   Later, in Reno, Bentsen blasted the Reagan administration for
``chaos that exists in drug control.''
   He told the National Conference of State Legislators that ``our
war against drugs lacks a commander.'' He said a Bentsen-Dukakis
administration would appoint a single drug czar to oversee the
battle.
   Bentsen said Dukakis' experience in state government gave him an
affinity with local officials, and he said the Democratic White
House would recognize the costs to state government when the
federal government cuts back on its programs.
</TEXT>
