<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ComputerDetective     07-28 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Detective,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Reported to Install Block Against Computer Sabotage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have equipped Britain's intelligence
listening post with a system that works like a computer detective
to ferret out software sabotage, the domestic news agency reported.
   Press Association said the new equipment will help avert
sabotage by computer amateurs known as hackers and by enemies who
use ``computer viruses,'' alien coding that insinuates itself into
a system.
   The detecting system was installed at the Government
Communications Headquarters in Cheltenham, about 110 miles
northwest of London, the agency reported. The listening facility
sifts through radio and other airborne messages, seeking military
and other secret communications.
   ``The nation's enemies have almost certainly tried to place
damaging software within our systems,'' Rupert Soames, managing
director of GPT Data Systems, was quoted as saying. His company
developed the system.
   A computer virus is a small piece of code inserted into a system
to corrupt data. It can infect other computers through networks or
exchanged software, or can lie dormant until a pre-determined
command activates it.
   ``One of the main concerns with the Strategic Defense Initiative
in the United States is its vulnerability to viruses and logic
bombs which would only trigger under war conditions,'' Soames was
quoted as saying.
   The SDI space-defense project, commonly called ``Star Wars,''
program, would use computer-guided lasers to shoot down enemy
missiles.
   Soames told the news agency several American companies have
expressed interest in the detecting system.
</TEXT>
