<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mandelas 1stLd-Writethru a0662 07-28 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandelas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Burning Is One of Many Mandela Hardships</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9 grafs pvs `She and Nelson ...' with 1 graf to CORRECT
that only Mrs. Mandela was new to home in 1958. PICKS up graf 10
`It has...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Mandela-Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fire that destroyed her
home Thursday was one of many hardships that have beset Winnie
Mandela since her husband Nelson, the African National Congress
leader, was sent to prison 26 years ago.
   She has spent 17 months in solitary confinement, lived in
isolation, been arrested several times and passed virtually her
entire adult life under stringent police restrictions and public
scrutiny.
   Mrs. Mandela is 54 and was trained as a social worker. She has
become a leading campaigner against apartheid and black activists
often call her ``Mother of the Nation.''
   Her commanding presence, controversial statements and
willingness to confront authorities has made her one of the most
visible symbols of opposition to white domination in South Africa.
   Another result of her prominence is that some of her personal
hardships become public events.
   When she visits her husband at Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town,
journalists are there.
   By the time she reached her burned-out home Thursday it was
surrounded by firefighters, police and journalists who already had
wandered through the smoldering remains. Mrs. Mandela saw the
crowd, stayed in her car and went directly to an office she
maintains nearby.
   Friends said the house held all her belongings, including
wedding photographs, family documents and the piano her husband
used to play.
   Mrs. Mandela moved into the modest four-room bungalow in Soweto,
Johannesburg's huge black township, after she married Mandela in
1958. Mandela had owned the house and lived in it since the 1940s.
   It has been shot at and stoned by attackers who have not been
identified. Police visit it regularly.
   After Mandela's arrest in 1962, Mrs. Mandela began receiving
banning orders that prohibited her from addressing public
gatherings, meeting with more than one person and entering places
ranging from schools to printing houses.
   They applied from 1963 to 1986 except for one 18-month period.
   From May 1969 to September 1970 she was held in solitary
confinement, tried twice under the Terrorism Act and acquitted both
times.
   Mrs. Mandela was imprisoned for six months in 1974 for violating
the banning order and detained for four months in 1976 after riots
in Soweto.
   A banning order issued in 1977 forced her to leave the Soweto
house and move to Brandfort in the rural Orange Free State. Her
home and office there were burned down in 1985 and she was allowed
to return to the home in Soweto a year later.
   Her defiance undimmed, Mrs. Mandela declared on her return: ``I
should never have been away from home in the first place. I am
grateful to no one. It was my right to be at home.''
   The Mandelas have two daughters. Zindzi, 27, lives with her
mother, and Zenani, 29, is studying at Boston University in the
United States with her husband, a member of Swaziland's royal
family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mandela-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0675 07-28 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0675,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandela Home Burned by Teen-Agers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th `State of emergency' to include
Chikane comment; picks up 8th `Mrs. Mandela'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos JOH1,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The home that has belonged to Nelson
Mandela and his family since the 1940s was gutted in an arson
attack Thursday that apparently involved a teen-gang dispute and
was not aimed at Mandela himself.
   Police said no one was hurt and no arrests were made.
   Capt. Ruben Bloomberg said in Pretoria that 30 to 50 black high
school students stoned the home of the imprisoned leader of the
African National Congress, doused it with gasoline and set it afire.
   Neighbors and black journalists said some attackers wore jackets
of Daliwonga high school in Soweto, and were involved in a dispute
Wednesday with the young black ``comrades'' who guard the home.
   Mandela's wife, Winnie, a prominent anti-apartheid activist, was
bound for a news conference concerning detainees when she learned
of the fire, which broke out about noon (6 a.m. EDT). Her daughter,
Zindzi, 27, and her two grandchildren, who also live at the
four-room home, were away at the time.
   But neighbors and journalists said some of the ``comrades'' who
often travel with Mrs. Mandela and guard her home were at the house
when the fire began.
   State of emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest,
security force action, treatment of detainees, some forms of
protest and a range of statements classified as subversive.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, general secretary of the South African
Council of Churches, said leaders in Soweto and other black
townships had been asked ``to call upon the community not to act
emotionally so they do not create a situation where there is a
spiral of violence.''
   He said an attempt would be made to talk to the principal and
the students of the school involved to ease the situation. He said
young men who congregate around the Mandela home were told ``not to
act without thinking or with revenge.''
   Although the dispute is local, he said, ``when it is Mandela's
house that is attacked, that makes it a national issue. Anybody who
attacks a well-known leader's house like that one would know they
would anger the people in the community and cause them to take
action.''
   Mrs. Mandela arrived by car about an hour later and viewed the
blackened windows and burned furniture in the yard from inside the
car. She then was driven to her nearby offices where she conducts
social welfare projects.
   The ``comrades,'' some wearing jackets of the Mandela United
soccer club, sponsored by the family, pushed journalists away from
the office. One threatened to burn a photographer's car.
   Later, attorney Amrichand Soma told reporters Mandela was
reached at Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town, where he is serving a
life term for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the
white-dominated government, and said no statement should be made.
   However, Aubrey Mokoena, a family friend and head of the Release
Mandela Campaign, said: ``The community must ... put an end to
this. Anyone who would think of attacking Mandela's house
represents the forces of darkness.''
   Journalists were allowed to enter the still-smoking home in the
Orlando section of Soweto, while black police with shotguns kept a
crowd of 300 neighbors away. A sodden carpet of hot, black ash
covered everything.
   Flames flickered in a side room. The house was filled with steam
from the heat and the water. Firemen pushed clothes out a bedroom
window, pulled a smoldering mattress outside, shoved smoking
cabinets and chairs onto the lawn.
   All the contents, including framed wedding pictures and the
family piano, were destroyed.
   Mrs. Mandela has lived in the house periodically since she
married Mandela in 1958. Last year she built a mansion on a hill
overlooking this huge black township outside of Johannesburg, a few
blocks from the burned home. But Mokoena said the new house is not
habitable and she would spend the night with friends.
   Mandela moved into the house with his first wife, Evelyn, in the
1940s and raised his two sons and his oldest daughter there. Evelyn
Mandela lives in the Xhosa tribal homeland of Transkei.
</TEXT>
