<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen-Finances     07-28 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Finances,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders FEC to Respond to Dukakis-Bentsen Campaign Fund Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court late Thursday ordered
the Federal Election Commission to respond to a request that the
presidential campaign of Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen be
barred from spending federal campaign funds until a dispute over
the financing is resolved.
   The court order said the FEC must respond by Monday to a motion
to block the spending of the money, and the court invited lawyers
for the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign to respond as well.
   The National Republican Senatorial Committee and Bentsen's GOP
opponent for the Texas Senate seat, Rep. Beau Boulter, are seeking
to block the federal campaign money. They charge that by running
simultaneously for the Senate and for vice president _ as Texas law
allows _ Bentsen gains an unfair financial advantage over
Republicans.
   The FEC rejected that argument on Tuesday when it released $46
million in federal campaign money for the Democratic ticket.
   Republicans appealed the FEC decision to the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia, and a three-judge panel
decided late Thursday to solicit arguments in the case. The appeal
contended that the FEC action was arbitrary and contrary to federal
campaign financing law and asked that the Democrats be barred from
spending any of the $46 million until the matter is resolved.
   ``The court has found this a serious enough issue to require its
review,'' said Ben Ginsberg, legal counsel for the GOP Senate
campaign committee. ``They are asking the FEC to say why it acted
properly.''
   The three-judge panel was made up of Chief Judge Spottswood W.
Robinson III, Judge Laurence Silberman, and Judge Douglas Ginsburg.
   Republicans say Bentsen has some $4 million in private funds set
aside for his Senate campaign which he can spend in Texas but which
will also benefit the party's presidential ticket, in effect
violating the $46 million spending ceiling for presidential
campaigns and the use of private money for the general election
race.
</TEXT>
