<HEAD>Precede SECAUCUS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Continues Attack on Reagan Administration Ethics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First five grafs new, UPDATING with public appearances; picks
up 5th graf pvs, ``He was...''; SUBS 8th and 9th graf pvs, adding
details about Cleveland appearance, meetings with Jackson
supporters, and comments on Bentsen; picks up 10th graf pvs,
``Newark mayor...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis
turned up the heat on the Reagan administration and Attorney
General Edwin Meese on Thursday, saying if the Democratic ticket is
elected ``the ethics office will be in the Oval Office, not some
place down the hall.''
   Dukakis also began wooing local supporters of former rival Jesse
Jackson as he campaigned across the industrial Northeast and
Midwest, holding meetings with former Jackson delegates and local
elected officials who backed Jackson in the Democratic primaries.
   The Massachusetts governor hammered at Meese and the Reagan
administration in a speech at an outdoor shopping mall in Secaucus,
N.J., in the Meadowlands area, and kept up the attack at a rally
before 2,000 people in downtown Cleveland.
   ``I want to tell you that in 1989, we're going to have a
president and vice president who won't sit by and do nothing when
they're told by high-ranking officials in the Justice Department
that the attorney general of the United States has been violating
the law,'' Dukakis said.
   His remarks included a dig at Vice President George Bush's
proposal this week to create a White House ethics office.
   He was referring to two former top Justice Department officials,
former assistant attorney general William Weld and former deputy
attorney general Arthur Burns, who told Congress earlier this week
that they had voiced concerns about Meese's actions before
resigning.
   ``I hope I never have to listen to that kind of briefing,''
Dukakis said. ``But if I do I can tell you I won't sit there and do
nothing. We'll take action.''
   Dukakis departed from the text of his prepared speech, devoted
to calling for investment in jobs and economic opportunity, to
comment on Meese and the broader subject of impropriety by some
serving in the Reagan administration. He repeated lines from his
nomination acceptance speech delivered at the Democratic National
Convention last week when he said in his administration those who
violate the public trust will be fired and ``if you violate the law
you'll be prosecuted.''
   In Cleveland, Dukakis praised, but was not accompanied by, the
state's two Democratic senators: John Glenn, whom he passed over in
selecting Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate, and Howard Metzenbaum,
who faces a tough re-election fight this year. In an interview with
a local television station, Dukakis said he picked Bentsen after
deciding the Texas senator ``had the right stuff'' _ a phrase that
recalled the title of the book and movie that depicted Glenn's life
as astronaut.
   Dukakis met privately with Jackson supporters in Newark, N.J.,
and in Cleveland, and spokesman Dayton Duncan said he would meet
with Jackson supporters Friday in Michigan _ the state where
Jackson stunned Dukakis with a two-one victory in the March
caucuses.
   Newark Mayor Sharpe James, who had been a Jackson delegate, said
some in the group had been disappointed by Dukakis' selection of
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as his running mate but that all seemed
pleased by their 20-minute discussion with the nominee.
   ``Now we're ready to support Michael Dukakis _ he won,'' James
said, pointing to the new Dukakis '88 button he had just put on his
lapel.
   ``I have now replaced my Jesse Jackson button,'' he said in an
interview. ``... The alternative is to support George Bush or to do
nothing and allow Bush to win.''
   Donald Payne, a member of the Newark city council and Democratic
nominee for Congress, said Dukakis showed ``a very good grasp of
urban issues'' but made no commitment for more federal spending.
   Fletcher Wiley, a Dukakis senior adviser who sat in on the
meeting, said one purpose of Dukakis' campaign trip was to meet
with Jackson supporters in cities where he is stopping.
   Dukakis also stopped at a day-care center where he was
photographed talking with small children.
   In his speech, Dukakis spoke about his call for a ``new era of
greatness'' made in his acceptance speech. ``It begins with the
recognition that a strong economic future needs three fundamental
things _ investment, innovation and teamwork,'' he said.
   He called for more investment in research, including by business
leaders, to keep up with research and training by Japan and other
countries.
   ``I want to restore some balance to our federal research and
development programs, and we'd better not forget that our military
strength cannot be sustained without economic strength _ a lesson
the Soviet Union has finally learned, and we must too,'' he said.
   As Dukakis spoke, about a dozen anti-abortion protesters stood a
short distance away and chanted ``Civil Rights for Unborn Babies.''
The nominee walked close by them as he left.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
