<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Aides Exchange Barbs Over Comment on Prison
Sentences</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aides to Republican George Bush and Democrat
Michael Dukakis traded barbs Thursday over an assertion by Bush
Campaign Manager Lee Atwater that Dukakis had ``commuted the
sentences of 58 violent criminals'' while governor of Massachusetts.
   Dukakis Campaign Manager Susan Estrich immediately denied the
claim, saying, ``Poor Lee. After his candidate failed in his
attempt to promote a positive message on either ethics or day care,
Lee is returning to the well-traveled low road preferred by
political muggers.''
   In a statement, Atwater said that among the 58 criminals whose
sentences he claimed Dukakis had commuted were ``28 first-degree
murderers and a convicted heroin dealer.''
   ``Dukakis ... also commuted the sentences of 25 convicted
second-degree murderers, some of whom had served sentences of as
little as two to five years,'' Atwater said.
   ``It appears that Mike Dukakis just can't stand the thought of
violent criminals spending time behind bars,'' Atwater said.
   Countered Ms. Estrich in a statement of her own: ``Lee should
stop distorting the facts. Under Michael Dukakis' leadership the
Massachusetts crime rate dropped l3 percent in five years while
crime nationally jumped 4 percent.''
   ``The homicide rate in Massachusetts is half the national
average and the lowest of any industrial state,'' she said.
   Leslie Dach, campaign communications director for the Democratic
nominee, said that ``for the record, Dukakis has commuted 10
sentences in six years.''
   ``Balderdash,'' said Bush spokesman Mark Goodin when told of the
response by the Dukakis aides. He said the figures the likely
Republican nominee used were taken from Massachusetts state records.
   ``The only reason crime has gone down in Massachusetts is that
Dukakis has let all the criminals out of jail and they've gone to
other states,'' Goodin said.
   Bush has repeatedly criticized a Massachusetts prison furlough
program that allowed passes for first-degree murderers. The program
was later amended, but not until after one of the prisoners escaped
from a furlough and raped a Maryland woman.
</TEXT>
