<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Emmys-Reax     07-28 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emmys-Reax,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Varied Reaction to Emmy Nomination: Who Else Got Them? What Do I
Wear?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Emmys, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corbin Bernsen learned of his Emmy nomination
in a long-distance wake-up call from his mother; Ann Jillian heard
when she punched the telephone message playback button; and Betty
White heard it on the radio.
   Nominations for the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences
coveted Emmy Awards were announced Thursday. NBC-TV's ``L.A. Law''
swept the bulk of nods with 19.
   ``L.A. Law'' producer-creator Steven Bochco furiously hunted for
the telephone numbers of his far-flung cast to congratulate them.
Because of the 21-week Writers Guild of America strike, the actors
were hard to find.
   ``Normally everybody is hard at work so you just walk on stage
and tell them. Now we're looking for telephone numbers,'' said
Bochco, adding, ``We're very excited.''
   The on-screen and real life husband-wife duo Michael Tucker and
Jill Eikenberry, called the ``Tucker-Berrys'' by the ``L.A. Law''
crew, were out of town. Tucker was doing a film in Montreal and his
wife was in North Carolina.
   ``We will find them somehow,'' said Bochco.
   ``Steve called me. I'm thrilled,'' said Alan Rachins, another of
the show's nominees, and ``L.A. Law'' star Susan Dey was especially
taken with surprise at her nomination, wondering aloud what she
would wear to the ceremony.
   Bernsen got a wakeup call in Milwaukee from his mother, actress
Jeanne Cooper, who told him of his nomination. She was nominated
last year for her ``L.A. Law'' guest role playing Bernsen's mother.
   ``She just said, `I'm sorry I woke you up, but congratulations.'
I said, `What for?' and she told me I got a nomination,'' he said.
   Bernsen, who has just begun filming the the movie ``Major
League'' with Charlie Sheen and Tom Berringer, was then read a list
of his competitors and exclaimed ``Great!'' when he learned co-star
Tucker was nominated.
   ``Pretty good guys to be with, I'd say. Now I'll see who my
friends are,'' he said.
   Bernsen and Bochco said the key to ``L.A. Law's'' success could
be a sophistication that appeals to audiences young and old.
   ``It has the serial thing people like to follow and it's got
sophistication. As I've always said, I think we acknowledge the
intelligence of the viewing audience,'' Bernsen said.
   ``We like to think we don't insult them,'' Bochco said. ``We
have good stories and that great ensemble group. We draw
inspiration from their ability.''
   Miss Jillian was overwhelmed by the two nominations for the NBC
movie ``The Ann Jillian Story'' _ leading actress in a miniseries
or special and best drama-comedy special. It dealt with her battle
with breast cancer.
   ``I woke up, stumbled into the living room and I pushed the
(telephone) message unit and a voice said, `Congratulations on your
Emmy nomination.' I just couldn't believe it,'' she said.
   ``I'm very honored and very thrilled, but the nomination isn't
for me. It goes for all those ladies who had to go through this. I
tried to do this with dignity and above all hope. I'm so grateful.''
   Actor Tim Busfield, nominated for supporting actor in the drama
series ``thirtysomething,'' was acknowledged for an episode dealing
with a marriage counseling session.
   ``I owe this to all the women I've ever had fights with,'' he
said.
   Miss White was putting on her makeup when she heard about her
third nomination for ``The Golden Girls.''
   ``Isn't this exciting? I can't believe it,'' she said. Asked if
an Emmy nomination meant much this third time, she said, ``Sure, I
don't take it lightly. It's your peer group saying they like you.''
   Miss White and ``Golden Girl'' Rue McClanahan have won past
acting Emmys, so both are now rooting for wins this time by
co-stars Beatrice Arthur and Estelle Getty. All four are nominated,
Miss Getty in the supporting actress category.
</TEXT>
