<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0697 07-28 0941</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Making VP Calls But No Word of Decision; Dukakis Talks Ethics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 8th graf pvs, ``The
Massachusetts...,'' to add poll material, picking up 9th pvs,
``Dukakis also...; adds four grafs to give Dukakis quote on Jackson
hostage efforts and court action on campaign funds; edits
throughout to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush said Thursday his search for a Republican running
mate is proceeding in an ``orderly fashion,'' but offered no clues
about the outcome. Democrat Michael Dukakis renewed his attack on
the vice president's handling of Attorney General Edwin Meese's
legal difficulties.
   ``The process is going along in an orderly fashion,'' Bush told
reporters. ``Hopefully, it won't be demeaning to anyone.''
   Sources said that Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole had been
notified by Bush that he was under consideration, among about a
dozen prospects. Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana also is under
consideration, at least in a preliminary way, said one source,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Three Republicans are known to have received Bush campaign
requests for background information, including Rep. Jack Kemp of
New York, who has figured prominently in speculation, and Sen. Pete
Domenici of New Mexico and New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, who have
not.
   Dukakis embarked on a hectic campaign swing through seven
Eastern and Midwestern states, combining fresh criticism for Bush
with a renewed effort to reach out to Jesse Jackson's
primary-campaign supporters.
   He said that if the Democrats win the White House this fall,
``the ethics office will be in the Oval Office, not some place down
the hall.'' That was a jab at Bush, who said in a speech earlier in
the week that he would appoint a special counselor on ethics to
work in the White House and other agencies of the federal
government.
   Dukakis also said that beginning next year, ``we're going to
have a president and vice president who won't sit by and do nothing
when they're told by high-ranking officials in the Justice
Department that the attorney general of the United States has been
violating the law.''
   The Massachusetts governor's comment was a reference to
congressional testimony earlier this week by two former top Justice
Department aides, who said they had told President Reagan and Bush
last spring that they had concerns about Meese's legal difficulties.
   Dukakis also met privately in New Jersey with about two dozen
local officials, most of them black, who backed Jackson's drive for
the Democratic presidential nomination. Newark Mayor Sharpe James
said the group was ``ready to support Michael Dukakis. ... The
alternative is to support George Bush or to do nothing and allow
Bush to win.''
   Dukakis' post-convention high in the polls continued Thursday,
as a Harris poll gave him an 18-point lead over Bush. But pollster
Louis Harris said such a wide margin was likely to be ``very
temporary.''
   Harris' survey of 1,268 likely voters found 57 percent support
for Dukakis to 39 percent for Bush. It was the fourth national poll
since the Democratic convention last week to find a Dukakis lead of
that magnitude.
   The new Harris poll was done July 22-25 and had a margin of
error of plus or minus three percentage points.
   Topic No. 1 in Republican circles was Bush's search for a
running mate _ and the campaign signals were anything but clear.
   One senior adviser, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
vice president had personally telephoned about a dozen prospective
running mates to notify them they are being considered.
   Aside from Dole and Kemp, the names that have surfaced most
consistently in speculation include California Gov. George
Deukmejian, Illinois Gov. Jim Thompson and Sens. Nancy Kassebaum of
Kansas and Alan Simpson of Wyoming. Dole's wife, former
Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, also has been mentioned as
a possible contender.
   Dole joked during the day that he and his wife have been
``waiting for the phone to ring at home. I can't get Elizabeth to
leave the house.''
   The Republican guessing game flourished while Democratic vice
presidential candidate Bentsen told the United Food and Commercial
Workers convention in San Francisco that the Reagan-Bush record for
women and minorities is a ``speed bump on the path to equality in
America.''
   Meanwhile, Jackson said he has asked the United Nations
secretary-general to ask Iranian officials for assistance in
freeing U.S. hostages held by Iranian sympathizers in Lebanon.
   But Jackson said ``no meeting has been set, and no meeting has
been sought'' for him to negotiate personally with Iranian
officials.
   ``We've simply talked through Secretary-General (Javier Perez)
de Cuellar, who did meet with the Iranian foreign minister,'' he
said in a telephone interview with The Associated Press.
   Bush, in an interview published in USA Today, called Jackson a
``loose cannon'' and said he should stay out of the hostage affair.
   Dukakis said he was unfamiliar with the facts about Jackson's
effort, ``but as a general matter private citizens should not try
to conduct foreign policy.''
   In Washington, the dispute over $46 million in federal campaign
money for Dukakis entered a new phase as a federal appeals court
ordered the Federal Elections Commission to respond to a request
that the funds be held up.
   The National Republican Senatorial Committee and Bentsen's GOP
opponent for his Texas Senate seat, Rep. Beau Boulter, are seeking
to block the money. They charge that by running simultaneously for
the Senate and for vice president _ as Texas law allows _ Bentsen
gains an unfair financial advantage over Republicans.
   The FEC rejected that argument on Tuesday when it released $46
million in federal campaign money for the Democratic ticket.
</TEXT>
