<HEAD>Four Injured in Gaza Strip Clash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Patrols, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Israeli border policemen were stoned and
two Gaza Strip residents were wounded as troops battled
demonstrators in the occupied territory on Thursday, the army said.
   Meanwhile, in the occupied West Bank, Israel seized an
Arab-owned house after the High Court of Justice ruled the army
could evict residents and set up a command post. The house sits on
the strategic Jerusalem-Hebron road.
   ``The military government said ... they must do something to
stop the throwing of stones,'' Ahmed Abuy Riad, who lived in the
house, told Israeli television. ``But the stones weren't thrown by
me .... I am innocent.''
   A military representative, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said violent protests broke out in Gaza City's Sheikh Radwan
neighborhood on Thursday. Two military border policemen were hit by
rocks, and two Gazans were shot in the legs and slightly wounded,
the official said.
   Also Thursday, a Gaza man, 37-year-old Hadel Hafez el Toruk,
died after he was shot four times last Friday in Gaza City.
   The shooting occurred at the same time that soldiers fired at a
group of Arabs after one threw a firebomb in central Gaza City, the
army said.
   The military spokesman said the army was checking to see if
Toruk was shot by the troops.
   If so, he would be the 235th Palestinian killed in the
eight-month revolt against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, the territories captured from Egypt and Jordan in the 1967
Middle East War. Four Israelis have also been killed.
   In politics, Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said Thursday
that he welcomed meetings between U.S. Assistant Secretary of State
Richard Murphy and Palestinians, as long as they do not belong to
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Murphy has said he wants to meet again with Palestinians in the
Middle East, something he had done in the past.
   The U.S. official is scheduled to travel to the Middle East from
Geneva during the first week in August for a peace mission that
will take him to Israel, Jordan, Syria, and Egypt.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Anita Stockman said
Thursday she was unaware of any concrete plans for Murphy to talk
to Palestinian leaders. She also said U.S. policy of refusing to
meet PLO leaders remained in place.
   Peres said he did not care if the Palestinians that might meet
with Murphy supported the PLO ideologically, as long as they were
not members. Israel refuses to talk to the PLO, calling it a
terrorist group.
   ``We do not censor ideas....'' Peres said. ``They should come
without rocks, without knives, without fire bombs.''
