<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-28 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers In East, Hot In Northern Tier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms remained over Oklahoma and stretched
along the Eastern Seaboard and Gulf Coast states Thursday, while
the north-central states endured a day hot even for late July.
   Midday thunderstorms brought 1.37 inches of rain during a half
hour at Victoria, Mass., and winds gusted to nearly 60 mph at
Bedford, Mass. Winds reached 46 mph as 2\ inches of rain fell at
Wilmington, N.C.
   Early morning thunderstorms produced hail as large as golf balls
in central Oklahoma.
   Heavier rainfall during a six-hour period ended at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1.37 inches at Victoria, Texas; almost an inch at Tulsa,
Okla., and three-quarters of an inch at Pensacola, Fla.
   The temperature at the Duluth, Minn., airport reached 95
degrees, breaking the record for the date of 92. The New Orleans
airport had a record low temperature for the date of 69 degrees
Thursday morning, one degree lower than the 70-degree mark set in
1984.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures around the nation ranged from 56
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 103 degrees at Needles, Calif.
The nation's low Thursday morning was 41 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Friday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
Florida across southeast Louisiana and in central Colorado. Sunny
skies were forecast for the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were predicted to be in the 70s and 80s in New
England, the lower Great Lakes and the Appalachians, as well as the
upper Mississippi Valley, northern Plains, much of Washington state
and along the California coast. Highs should be in the 80s in much
of Colorado, northwest New Mexico and northern Arizona, and 100
degrees or more in north central Texas and southwest Oregon, with
about 110 degrees through the desert Southwest. High temperatures
over the rest of the nation should generally reach the 90s or near
90 degrees.
</TEXT>
