<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Ambassador Says No Discussions With Jackson on Hostages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Perez de Cuellar to meet
hostage's wife, MINOR EDITING, no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian foreign minister will not meet
the Rev. Jesse Jackson to discuss the possible release of Americans
held hostage in Lebanon by pro-Iranian factions, Iran's U.N.
ambassador said Thursday.
   Meanwhile, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
announced he would meet Friday with the wife of a kidnapped
American, Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins.
   Higgins was abducted by pro-Iranian extremists in Lebanon in
February, and U.N. diplomats have reported hearing rumors recently
that he might be released.
   This week's peace talks between the secretary-general and envoys
from Iran and Iraq have brightened hopes for movement in gaining
the release of Western hostages in Lebanon. Perez de Cuellar said
he raised the issue Wednesday with Iranian Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati.
   However, Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati said
Thursday that his country's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati,
was focusing on ending the Iran-Iraq war, not on releasing
hostages, while in New York.
   ``He doesn't have a mandate to embark on anything other than
implementation of the Security Council Resolution 598'' on a
cease-fire and peace plan to end the war, Mahallati said in answer
to questions.
   ``Indeed, not,'' Mahallati said when asked if Velayati would
meet Jackson.
   Earlier Thursday, Jackson telephoned Perez de Cuellar about the
hostages and asked him to convey a message to Velayati, U.N.
officials said. They said the secretary-general did so.
   But Mahallati said his mission had not yet received a
communication from Perez de Cuellar.
   ``I don't think the minister (Velayati) had intended in this
visit to make any effort in this line, and we don't have any
mandate to embark on any such discussion,'' Mahallati said.
   Perez de Cuellar told reporters Wednesday night that he had
raised the problem of American hostages ``very, very specifically''
with Velayati during a meeting that day.
   ``I can confirm that the Rev. Jesse Jackson telephoned the
secretary-general early today about the fate of the American
hostages and asked that this message be conveyed to the foreign
minister of Iran,'' the secretary-general's spokesman, Francois
Giuliani, said in answer to reporters' questions.
   ``This was conveyed by the secretary-general to the foreign
minister.''
   Giuliani did not elaborate.
   Earlier Thursday, the Iranian Mission's counselor, Mohammad
Javad Zarif, said there had been no approach from the Jackson camp
and said, ``I do not think that there are any specific issues that
we'll have to talk about.''
   Jackson said Wednesday in Chicago that he had sought a meeting
with Velayati through the secretary-general to discuss obtaining
release of the American hostages.
   Iran has said it could intercede to obtain their freedom if the
United States agreed to release Iranian assets frozen in the United
States.
   The United States has said it is willing to discuss the issue
but has rejected any deal or payment of ransom.
   Nine Americans are among 18 foreigners being held hostage by
pro-Iranian extremists in Lebanon. Longest held is Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
Anderson, 40, was abducted in Moslem west Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   The U.N Security Council was expected to adopt a resolution
Friday appealing for the release of Higgins, 43, kidnapped Feb. 17
on a highway in Lebanon, U.N. officials said. Higgins was chief of
the U.N. Troop Supervision Organization, a military observer group
in the Middle East.
   Perez de Cuellar told reporters Thursday that he would meet
Robin Higgins, Higgins' wife, at U.N. headquarters at her request.
</TEXT>
