<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CovertAction 1stLd-Writethru a0665 07-28 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Covert Action, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Says Panama Leak Came From Administration, Not
Congress</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with comment from official in Panama, INSERTS three
grafs after 8th graf bgng, ``Boren said ... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A news leak on a covert plan to undermine
Panamanian military ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega came from the
Reagan administration and was a ``set-up deal'' to make it look
like the disclosure came from Congress, leaders of the Senate
Intelligence Committee said Thursday.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of the panel, and the
committee's ranking Republican, Sen. William Cohen of Maine, said
they believed the leak was a ``heavy-handed'' attempt to derail a
bill that would tighten congressional oversight of covert
operations, and also to enhance Vice President George Bush's
political prospects.
   ``I think the matter was handled in such a way as to set up
members of Congress to make them appear the source of the leak,''
said Cohen. ``I am offended by it.''
   ``I think the Intelligence Committee was used, in this case,''
added Boren.
   Boren said the whole matter had been handled in highly unusual
fashion, including a much wider dissemination than is normal for
information about presidential covert action authorizations, which
are known as ``findings.''
   ``I have a feeling it's much broader. More people than normal
knew,'' Boren said, possibly including members of Congress outside
the 15 senators and 17 House members who are on the intelligence
panels.
   ``If they've briefed other people, we can't be responsible for
that,'' said Cohen.
   Boren said reporters already were calling the Senate
Intelligence Committee and waiting outside its secure hearing room
on Tuesday even before the CIA briefing began. Cohen said he
expressed suspicions about the possibility of a leak before any
information was given in the briefing.
   In Panama, Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter on Thursday called
reports of the covert action plan ``intolerable'' and ``terrorist''
and said the Panamanian government would take a complaint to the
United Nations Security Council.
   ``It is intolerable and irritating that in the highest spheres
of power in the United States they talk of possible terrorist
actions in Panamanian territory,'' the government news agency
Panapres quoted Ritter as saying.
   He added that ``the Panamanian authorities are maintaining a
state of alert to reject any type of terrorist action.''
   On Wednesday, the Washington Post and the Los Angeles Times
reported that Reagan had signed a finding authorizing unspecified
covert activities aimed at undermining Noriega's rule. The military
ruler has clung to power for months despite previous U.S. efforts
to weaken the Panamanian economy, and U.S. inability to budge him
has become a political liability for the administration.
   Later reports said the covert action authorization included
support for the country's internal political opposition, but
stopped short of direct military or paramilitary action.
   Legislation is due to come to the House floor within the next
two weeks which would require notification of the House and Senate
intelligence committees within 48 hours of any covert action plan
signed by the president.
   The measure, prompted by last year's Iran-Contra investigation,
is designed to tighten current law, which requires only that
unspecified ``timely notice'' be given to Congressional overseers.
   The administration strongly opposes the bill, calling it a
strait jacket on the president's ability to conduct intelligence
operations and arguing that in cases of extremely sensitive covert
acts the White House must be free to withhold notification from
Congress.
   Boren said he did not believe the administration action would
have any significant impact on future U.S. policy decisions, and
added that Noriega would be unaffected by any threat from the
United States.
   ``Noriega doesn't put much stock in words,'' said Boren. ``I
think it's time we went back to Teddy Roosevelt's admonition. We've
talked loudly and carried a small stick ... I don't think hurling
more words at him is going to work.''
</TEXT>
