<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GreenvilleBoycott     07-28 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greenville Boycott,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks Want School Superintendent Fired; Begin Boycott</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black parents and students are
boycotting white businesses in a campaign to oust the white
superintendent of the mostly black school district.
   The controversy began in the spring when 87 of the system's
9,200 students failed a new standardized test needed to pass to the
next grade.
   Willie Long, who heads the protest for the group, called Save
Our Children, said the test issue is now a ``dead horse.'' He said,
however, that the test encouraged parents to join the protest as
their anger grew.
   Protesters said Wednesday they would expand their action to
pressure the Greenville Public Schools Board of Trustees to fire
Superintendent Nolan Vickers and his assistant, Janet Sweatt, who
also is white.
   Protesters accuse Vickers and Sweatt of being insensitive to the
needs of blacks, who comprise more than 90 percent of the school
system's students.
   Vickers and Sweatt were in meetings Thursday and unavailable for
comment, said Assistant Superintendent Arthur Peyton, who is black.
   When asked if he has any problems with the current school
administration, Peyton replied, ``No I don't because I'm
instrumental in running it. In the things that are coming out, I'm
as much responsible for it as anyone else.''
   School Board President Mary Haynes, who is black, declined to
comment on the boycott, but said board members probably would
discuss it at their Aug. 11 meeting.
   Parents and students marched Wednesday in groups as small as
four and as large as eight in front of department stores, a
shopping mall, two fast-food restaurants and a car dealership.
   ``We're definitely making an impact,'' said Long, who teaches
biology in the school district. ``Our being out here is against the
will of the white business community.''
</TEXT>
