<HEAD>Writers' Strike Talks Set To Resume Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for scriptwriters and television
and film producers agreed to resume contract talks Friday to try to
end the 21-week walkout that has idled Hollywood production, a
federal mediator said Thursday.
   Floyd Wood, district director for the Federal Mediation and
Conciliation Service, asked negotiators to return to the bargaining
table Friday afternoon. Both sides stated that they would comply,
Wood said.
   Negotiations between the Writers Guild of America and the
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers broke off
Tuesday morning after a marathon 20-hour baragaining session failed
to produce a settlement.
   In a strike-related development, NBC announced Thursday that it
will bring back ``The Magical World of Disney,'' which the network
recently removed from the fall schedule because of the strike.
   NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff had previously
announced that the writers' strike would keep the Disney program
off the Sunday schedule this fall. The network had planned to
replace ``The Magical World of Disney'' with a recast version of
``The Hardy Boys,'' using old scripts.
   ``The Hardy Boys'' will now move to another weeknight.
   The Disney series, set to debut Oct. 9, will be filled with
feature films, old Disney specials and compilation programs until
an end to the writer's strike provides original programming.
   The union has been on strike since March 7. Issues in the
impasse are payments for reruns of one-hour television shows
rebroadcast domestically and all shows rebroadcast overseas.
