<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Out,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City of Atlanta Loses Water Pressure Due To Pump Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly all of Atlanta was without water for
several hours Thursday night after a boiler that generates steam to
run municipal pumps failed.
   The boiler shut down at 5:15 p.m. and was repaired about 6:45
p.m., said Rob Rivers, head of the water department.
   ``We have to raise the pressure very, very slowly, or we'll
cause tremendous problems, water mains bursting everywhere,''
Rivers said.
   He said the major boiler, which produces steam to power the
water pumps, ``suffered either an electrical or mechanical failure
and shut down,'' Rivers said. ``Pressure went from 120 pounds (per
square inch) to 40 pounds.''
   The problem, which he blamed on outdated equipment, extended to
``most everyone inside the city,'' Rivers said, especially those at
higher elevations.
</TEXT>
