<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder-Suicide,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Actress And Parents Dead In Apparent Murder-Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bodies found in a charred home have been
identified as those of child actress Judith Barsi, who died at the
hands of her actor father in the movie ``Fatal Vision,'' and her
mother, the coroner's office said Thursday.
   A man's body found in the house after the fire Wednesday
previously was identified as the child's father, Jozsef, 55, who
apparently shot his wife and child to death, set the family home
afire and then killed himself.
   The bodies of Judith, 11, and her mother, Maria, 48, were
positively identified at the scene by physical characteristics,
said coroner's investigator Michael Riddle.
   The family's nearest relatives were in Arizona and no funeral
arrangements had been made, he said.
   Miss Barsi made her film debut in 1987 in ``Jaws IV: The
Revenge,'' in which she played the role of Thea.
   Her television appearances included roles in ``St. Elsewhere,''
``Cagney and Lacey'' and ``Growing Pains,'' said Bonnie Gold, a
spokeswoman for an acting agency that managed her career.
   She also played convicted killer Jeffrey MacDonald's daughter in
the movie ``Fatal Vision.'' She, her sister and pregnant mother
were killed in the movie, which was based on a true story.
   Neighbors said Barsi was an overprotective father and abusive
husband who had threatened to kill his 48-year-old wife and burn
their home.
   Next door neighbor Eunice Daly said Mrs. Barsi told her last
week that her husband became abusive and threatening when he drank.
She said Mrs. Barsi told her she was considering divorce but was
afraid to move out.
   ``She said, `I can't because he'll come after us and kill us and
he's threatened to burn the house down,''' Ms. Daly said.
   Mrs. Barsi said she planned to cash her daughter's $12,000
federal tax refund check that day, before her husband could get it,
the neighbor said.
   The child's body was found in her bed and the woman's in a
hallway, police Lt. Warren Knowles said. He said both had been shot
once in the head.
   ``The child was not allowed to go anywhere, very few places
alone,'' neighbor Linda Williams said. ``Even when she came to our
home, it always had to be OK'd by Dad.''
</TEXT>
