<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-PeaceConvoy     07-28 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Peace Convoy,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Welcome American Peace Convoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista newspaper Barricada
saluted a convoy of U.S. veterans that is bringing food, medicine
and clothes to the capital with a banner headline Thursday reading,
``Veterans Break Boycott.''
   The Veterans' Peace Convoy was expected in Managua Friday and
would turn over the supplies to the government at a ceremony at the
Revolution Plaza downtown.
   Barricada said thousands of people greeted the convoy of 20
vehicles and 44 activists when it crossed the Honduran-Nicaraguan
border Wednesday after months of opposition from the U.S.
government.
   The U.S. Customs Service initially refused to let the convoy
cross the U.S.-Mexico border, saying taking the vehicles to
Nicaragua would violate a 1985 trade embargo.
   Humanitarian aid is permitted under the embargo, but the Customs
Service says the vehicles must return to the United States.
   The convoy people oppose U.S. backing of the rebels, known as
Contras, in their almost 7-year-old war against Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government.
   Barricada said U.S. police ``brutally repressed'' the group in
its attempt to bring ``medicine, food and clothes for Nicaraguan
children butchered by the war action of the Reagan administration.''
   Eight members of the group were arrested July 9 when they
refused to leave the road leading to a toll booth at a Rio Grande
bridge crossing in Laredo, Texas. The convoy finally crossed the
Mexican border at Nuevo Laredo on July 14.
   The Customs Service said the trucks must return to the United
States within 30 days or convoy members will face fines of up to
$50,000 and 10 years in prison. Convoy members refused to sign
forms promising they would return the trucks.
   In June, U.S. Customs officials stopped the original convoy of
38 vehicles from crossing into Mexico. About 100 convoy
participants drove to Washington to rally against Customs'
decision, circling around the White House and in front of the State
Department in three days of protest.
</TEXT>
