<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 2232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Investigation 1stLd-Writethru a0751 07-28 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0751,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Team Ends Investigation of Jetliner Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs on separate investigation by International Civil
Aviation Organization.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military experts left the Persian
Gulf on Thursday after a 3{-week investigation of the destruction
of an Iranian airliner by an American warship, Navy officials said.
   The team led by Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty arrived July 5, two
days after missiles fired by the cruiser USS Vincennes hit an Iran
Air Airbus flying over the Strait of Hormuz, killing all 290 people
aboard.
   Pentagon officials said officers of the Vincennes mistook the
Airbus A300 for an Iranian F-14 jet fighter on an attack course.
   Fogarty's team worked in secret and made no statements before
leaving.
   The U.S. Navy officials said the report would ``work its way up
the chain of command'' to Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci. Because
Carlucci is in the Soviet Union until about Aug. 8, they said, the
report could not be released until mid-August.
   Investigators compiled data from computer tapes on the Vincennes
and two other U.S. warships that were in the area, the frigate USS
Elmer Montgomery and missile frigate John H. Sides.
   They also took sworn testimony from the commander of the
Vincennes, Capt. Will C. Rogers III, and other officers of the
three warships.
   An initial 15-day deadline for the investigation was extended at
Fogarty's request.
   The Navy officials would not give details of the investigations
and said contact with Iran for information would have to be through
diplomatic channels. The Vincennes has been assigned to the Arabian
Sea, just outside the Persian Gulf, and is expected to complete its
tour at the end of summer.
   In Ottawa, Iranian diplomat Gholamreza Behtashi said a
five-member team from the International Civil Aviation Organization
is expected to arrive Friday in Tehran, Iran's capital, to pursue
its own investigation into the disaster.
   Behtashi, third secretary at the Iranian Embassy, said the team
is made up of technical personnel from the Montreal-based United
Nations agency.
   ``They will go from Tehran to the Persian Gulf and investigate
the various aspects of the incident,'' Behtashi said.
   Iran asked the governing council of the agency to meet in
special session to condemn the attack, but members refused to
censure the United States.
   The 33-nation governing council ordered the inquiry on July 14.
   U.S. delegate Edmund Stohr said the United States will offer the
investigating team whatever help it can. He said the team had not
asked to board the Vincennes, and he didn't know if such a visit
would be possible considering the military situation in the gulf.
   ICAO is a technical body composed of 159 nations. It sets
standards for civil aviation and airline safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 2331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     07-28 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Road,' A Play By Jim Cartwright, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Road,'' a gritty, grimy and thoroughly
fascinating journey through industrial England, puts most of the
audience where the action is _ right in the middle of an unnamed
Lancashire town dying during Margaret Thatcher's boom times.
   This provocative play, which opened Thursday at off-Broadway's
La Mama Annex, lets theatergoers wander a dismal thoroughfare and
mingle with the town's citizens. The less adventurous can perch
along a three-sided balcony and observe the action, but the
distance would seem to dilute the drama.
   To get the full effect of Simon Curtis' masterful direction,
it's better to be right down on the road, a depressingly realistic
environment designed by Paul Brown. Curtis does a remarkable job,
not only with the actors but with the audience which follows the
flow of the play across the playing area with minimal instruction
from the performers.
   The setting reflects the dead-end dreams of its inhabitants. The
hulk of an abandoned car sits on one corner of the playing area.
Squat, dilapidated homes line one side of the street. Other open
spaces become the oppressive parlors and bedrooms of these people
who have lost all hope.
   Playwright Jim Cartwright has written some bitter yet often very
funny vignettes about their threadbare existence and stitched them
together by creating a scruffy master of ceremonies named Scullery.
The character is played with a roguish charm by Jack Wallace.
   Scullery introduces the residents of the road, all of them in
the process of going out for the evening. ``Going out'' for most of
them means getting drunk.
   Several of the scenes are etched in despair. Audiences meet the
middle-aged Jerry who, in a poignant soliloquy, laments the days
long ago when people had jobs, good times and felt ``safe.''
   ``I can't get away from the past,'' he says. ``But no matter
what they say, I can't see how that time could turn into this
time.''
   The hopelessness of today is reiterated throughout the play and
Cartwright offers several variations on that desolation. In another
sketch, a young man named Joey is on a hunger strike. ``They rush
you from the cradle to the grave. But now we've come to a
standstill, no job, no hope,'' he murmurs to his good-natured
girlfriend who joins him in the starvation pact.
   There's also a defiance in the desperation, particularly in the
play's powerful last scene when two young men pick up two girls and
bring them home for booze and sex. The quartet is moved by Otis
Redding's recording of ``Try a Little Tenderness,'' and as they
become progressively drunker, they chant fiercely, ``Somehow _
might escape.'' You get the impression that if they don't,
something terrible is going to happen.
   Cartwright's play is overtly political and his message
occasionally becomes heavy-handed. There are references to Thatcher
and what kind of country England has become under Conservative
Party rule. But his characters are immensely human _ often
humorous, often repugnant and completely believable.
   The play's seven actors portray a variety of characters and
their versatility is a marvel. Kevin Bacon gets the most difficult
workout. He must switch from the impassioned hunger striker to a
drunkenly catatonic soldier. As the striker's simple-minded
girlfriend, Joan Cusack projects a delicacy that shines through all
the despair. She radiates a sweetness that is captivating.
   Equally fine work comes from Gerry Bamman as the nostaglic
Jerry; Betsy Aidem as an old hag trying to get dressed to go out
for an evening of fun; Michael Wincott, an unnerving and menacing
Skinhead, and Jayne Haynes as a sassy tart.
   ``Road'' is a joint production of Lincoln Center Theater and La
Mama. For Lincoln Center, it is another feather in an already
crowded cap of shows that includes ``Anything Goes,'' ``Sarafina!''
and ``Speed-the-Plow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
