<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq 3rdLd-Writethru a0776 07-28 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0776,0859</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran And Iraq Trade Charges, Impasse Builds Over Issue of Direct
Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Javier Perez de Cuellar
saying talks have not collapsed and he's working on breaking
deadlock; announces he will meet Friday with wife of hostage; edits
to conform. PICKS up 10th pvs, The Iranian Mission insisted. </NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   War enemies Iran and Iraq traded
recriminations during a one-day suspension of U.N. peace talks
Thursday. The talks at an impasse over Iraq's insistence on direct
talks and Iran's reluctance to agree.
   However, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said the
impasse did not mean peace talks were collapsing. He said he was
working on a formula for breaking the disagreement.
   Iraq demands a face-to-face meeting before a truce and Iran
insists on a truce before it will consider a direct meeting at a
later stage.
   Iran accused Iraq Thursday of stalling, sabotaging U.N. peace
talks and blocking a truce in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   Pressure was increasing on Iraq in the 15-member Security
Council to drop its direct talks demand and other proposals that
could prolong the fighting, according to U.N. diplomats, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Foreign ministers Tariq Aziz of Iraq and Ali Akbar Velayati of
Iran did not visit U.N. headquarters Thursday after Perez de
Cuellar called a one-day suspension in his revolving-door diplomacy
aimed at ending the war.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati told reporters who
asked about direct talks, ``We will maintain our position. We will
not accept any preconditions (for direct talks). No step can be
taken before a cease-fire ...
   ``Accepting (U.N. cease-fire) Resolution 598 has been the last
flexibility by the Islamic Republic of Iran.''
   Perez de Cuellar said he hoped Iranian officials ``are
reflecting on the possibility of having direct talks at some
stage,'' but said he cannot compel the two sides to do so if Iran
is unwilling.
   Later Thursday, he assumed a more positive tone, assuring
reporters that talks were still under way.
   ``I reject the idea of any collapse absolutely. I reject it
emphatically. I have to keep waiting,'' Perez de Cuellar said,
adding he believed ``at some stage, direct talks are
indispensable.''
   He acknowleded there was an impasse and, when asked if he had a
formula for breaking it, said: ``I'm working on that.''
   Also Thursday, Perez de Cuellar announced he would meet Friday
with the wife of an American U.N. official kidnapped in Lebanon
last Feb. 17, Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins. He said he would
meet Robin Higgins, Higgins' wife, at U.N. headquarters at her
request.
   The Iraqi Mission insisted that ``given the Iranian duplicity
and bad faith, peace can only be achieved through direct
face-to-face negotiations'' under U.N. auspices. It said that
Iraq's goal was lasting peace and not just a cease-fire.
   The deadlock over direct negotiations has complicated U.N.
efforts to end the Persian Gulf conflict.
   Fighting continued Thursday, with Iran saying it crushed an
Iraqi force in two days of fighting around the western Iranian city
of Eslamabad, 60 miles from the Iraqi border.
   Perez de Cuellar suspended talks for a day to study his
exchanges with the Iraqi and Iranian envoys since Tuesday. Meetings
were to resume Friday.
   Mohammad Javad Zarif, counselor at Iran's U.N. Mission, told
reporters direct talks would not promote peace at this time.
   He commented one day after Velayati accepted all of Perez de
Cuellar's proposals on implementing the resolution's peace plan.
   Iraq has not yet responded.
   Details of the proposals have not been disclosed.
   On Wednesday, Aziz said Baghdad insists on direct talks with
Iran before a cease-fire and will not be ``stampeded'' into a truce
without guarantees from Iran.
   The Iraqi Mission accused Iran on Thursday of ``a malicious
campaign to sow confusion in diplomatic efforts to achieve peace by
flooding the U.N. and media with statements alleging that Iraq is
fighting inside Iran.''
   The mission said Iraq's recent military operations were carried
out ``to liberate remnants of occupied Iraqi territories.'' It said
troops only entered Iranian territory to liberate Iraqi land, and
added: ``Iraqi forces have long since withdrawn. Iraq has no
territorial ambitions inside Iran.''
   Iraq accused Iran of ``simply seeking a hasty truce without
giving any commitments that it will comply honestly and sincerely
to the full implementation of the resolution as a plan for
comprehensive and durable peace.''
   ``The policy of Iraq is to put obstacles in the way of the
secretary-general's peace efforts,'' Iran's Zarif said. ``This
whole Iraqi exercise is planned to sabotage the efforts upon which
the international community is looking with hope.''
   The U.N. chief summoned both foreign ministers to New York this
week for intensive consultations on setting a timetable for a
U.N.-supervised cease-fire, a troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange,
formal peace negotiations and creating a panel to determine which
side started the war, all points contained in the Security Council
resolution.
</TEXT>
