<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ArtelEmergency 1stLd-Writethru a0773 07-28 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Artel Emergency, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0773,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Meets With Residents On Chemical Plant Dangers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with details and comments from evening
meeting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NITRO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials who have taken over an
abandoned chemical plant in which a roof collapsed on already
leaking drums warned worried residents Thursday night that they may
face an emergency.
   U.S. Environmental Protection Agency spokesmen told about 300
residents who crowded into a school auditorium for a town meeting
that the agency does not know what is in more than 1,000 decaying
drums at Artel Chemical Co.
   ``So the bottom line is, we're in danger?'' asked one woman in
the audience after the two-hour question-and-answer session.
   ``We wouldn't be there if you weren't,'' answered Dr. Joseph
Lafornara, with the EPA's Environmental Response Team from Edison,
N.J.
   ``But the hazard has been there for years. You've been living
with it. What we're saying is, in three or four months, it won't be
there anymore.''
   Lafornara characterized the site as one of the three most
critical among hundreds he has worked with under the federal
Superfund program, which draws money from the chemical industry to
help clean up hazardous dump sites.
   EPA spokesman Harold Yates said the plant had a long history of
``legal maneuvering'' and safety violations. He said the plant
manufactured ``small batches of exotic chemicals'' that cleanup
workers now are having trouble identifying.
   Former Artel employees attacked the EPA for not hiring them to
identify substances in the unmarked chemical drums, while some
residents harshly criticized the EPA for not stepping in years ago.
   Yates said the most pressing problems at the closed plant
include at least 60 drums of highly volatile metallic sodium and a
large tank containing 9,000 gallons of methyl mercaptan, a chemical
that is mixed in with natural gas to give it an odor.
   Yates said the threat of a ``severe explosion'' had been created
over the weekend when rain triggered a roof collapse at the plant's
main warehouse.
   ``There are drums that are rupturing as we speak,'' he had said
Wednesday. ``We're talking about a major accident that could happen
there.''
   But Yates said Thursday an engineer determined that the building
was structurally safe, and Kanawha County Emergency Services
Coordinator Bill White played down the danger.
   ``I do not think the potential is any greater than it has been
in the last five years,'' White said. ``The roof's been leaking for
years. The barrels have been leaking for years.''
   White said the EPA told him that Saturday's roof fall had
punctured several barrels of acid and that water or moisture had
reacted with the chemicals ``and they started fuming.''
   But he said there was little environmental danger.
   The Artel plant is one of several chemical plants along a strech
of Kanawha Valley in western West Virginia. Nitro, with about 8,000
residents, is about 12 miles west of Charleston.
   The plant has been closed since 24 employees walked off the job
June 6 in a pay dispute. They contended that they were being paid
below minimum wage. Operations then were shut down after the U.S.
Department of Labor obtained a federal court injunction against
Artel.
   The EPA has stepped in to clean up the unidentified chemicals at
Artel, and an Ohio company is finishing the first step of taking
test samples from the containers.
   White said the chemicals will be moved for disposal, increasing
the risk of spills and leaks at that time.
   The plant was owned and operated as Fike Chemical Co. for about
25 years by Elmer Fike, who was retained as a minority owner and
consultant by Artel when he sold the plant in 1986.
   Fike could not be reached at home Thursday and former plant
manager Tom Beal, Fike's son-in-law, was out of town, a family
member said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
