<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Deficit 1stLd-Writethru a0684 07-28 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deficit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Says Drought Relief Could Trigger Broad Spending Cuts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with congressional drought relief action, SUBS 5th
graf bgng ``He said OMB ... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration on Thursday projected the
federal deficit for the upcoming budget year at $140.1 billion _
short of the trigger for across-the-board spending cuts _ but
warned that a hefty drought-relief bill could cause the automatic
reductions to kick in.
   The new deficit estimate, covering the fiscal year that begins
Oct. 1, is $5.9 billion below the $146 billion level that would
force politically painful cuts under the Gramm-Rudman budget law.
   However, James Miller, head of the Office of Management and
Budget, said that the drought relief bill and several other
spending proposals could quickly wipe out the cushion and trigger
the spending cuts, which would take effect right before the
November elections.
   Miller said that President Reagan supports drought relief, a
popular initiative in an election year, but he said the president
doesn't want to ``use the plight of the farmers as an opportunity
to make a Christmas tree out of that bill'' by loading it up with
provisions that have little to do with drought relief.
   Later Thursday, the House approved a drought bill providing up
to $5.8 billion in assistance for farmers, while the Senate passed
a drought relief measure estimated to cost between $5.85 billion
and $6.55 billion.
   The administration is also fighting to hold down spending on
other measures pending before Congress, including anti-drug
legislation, trade legislation and aid for the hungry and homeless.
   Miller said if all of those measures were adopted, the 1989
deficit would increase by between $6.4 billion and $8.7 billion,
enough even at the low end of the estimate to trigger the spending
cuts.
   ``We can't do all the things that Congress has on its list right
now,'' he told reporters during a White House briefing. ``Congress
has got to pare down and make sure it doesn't go over these
limits.''
   House Budget Committee Chairman Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., agreed
that the administration's mid-session budget review showed ``we may
be moving uncomfortably close'' to automatic spending cuts.
   ``It is clear from this report that Congress and the
administration will have to make difficult choices in the months
ahead. All of the urgent needs of the nation cannot be funded at
the levels most of us would support in less difficult times,'' Gray
said.
   Under the Gramm-Rudman act, the administration is required to
estimate the coming year's fiscal budget deficit by mid-August. The
White House budget office must then adjust that estimate in October
to take into account any new legislation.
   If such legislation pushes the deficit past the trigger amount
of $146 billion, automatic spending cuts of more than $10 billion
automatically take effect in October, right before the fall
elections, with half of the cuts taken out of domestic spending and
half out of military spending.
   The administration's new budget estimates, which are based on
updated economic and spending projections, predicted that the
deficit in the current fiscal year would be $152.3 billion.
   This is slightly higher than the $146.7 billion deficit estimate
the administration made in February, but it is still well below the
deficit estimates of $160 billion or more that were being made by
many private economists at the time.
   Better-than-expected economic growth, which has pushed the
unemployment rate down to a 14-year-low and boosted government tax
revenues, was credited for lowering the shortfall.
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., a private
consulting firm, said his current estimates were close to the
administration's forecasts for this year and next year.
   The 1987 budget deficit was $150.4 billion as a one-time
windfall from tax overhaul resulted in a big improvement from the
$221.1 billion record deficit suffered in 1986.
   Miller, noting that the administration's original forecast was
scorned as a ``rosy scenario,'' blamed higher spending in such
areas as deposit insurance for missing the administration's
February target.
   The budget review said that the bank and savings and loan
insurance funds would pay out $4.6 billion more this year than had
been originally budgeted because of high failure rates at financial
institutions in the depressed Southwest.
   The deficit target under the Gramm-Rudman legislation for the
upcoming fiscal year is $136 billion, but the legislation says
automatic spending cuts can be avoided if the government's deficit
projection is within $10 billion of that figure. Thus, for 1989,
any estimate below $146 billion would avoid the need for spending
cuts.
</TEXT>
