<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0722 07-28 0985</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0722,1007</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advancing Forest Fire Forces More Evacuations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with fires in Utah and
Washington, resident's reaction to arson cause, increase Rapid City
fire acreage to 2,800 and increase damage to homes, etc. Picks up
17th graf pvs, `Although cooler...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos RAP2, YNP3, LaserColor YNP5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arson forest fire that has burned
into the western edges of this city expanded and switched direction
Thursday and more subdivisions were ordered evacuated, officials
said.
   ``It's out of control. It has expanded drastically since I was
there last evening,'' Gov. George Mickelson said.
   In Wyoming, efforts to block a fire burning toward Old Faithful
geyser in Yellowstone National Park were hampered by what normally
would be good firefighting weather _ cool, damp conditions slowed a
backfire intended to head off one of seven major fires.
   Fires also burned in Alaska, Montana, Idaho, California, Utah
and Washington state.
   Three subdivisions in western Rapid City were ordered evacuated
Thursday as a precaution as wind whipped a fire in the heavily
forested Black Hills. Later Thursday, officials suggested that
residents leave another rural housing area.
   Reports that the fire was arson brought strong reaction from
residents.
   ``I can't believe there's people that sick,'' said Susan Van
Norton, who couldn't return home after a dental appointment because
of the evacuation order. ``It floors me to think that someone could
cause that much destruction and devastaton to so many people.
   Fire officials did not know how many homes were involved but
said the number was in the hundreds.
   ``It's almost being defended totally by air at the present time
because it is in those canyons and the ground crews simply cannot
fight the fire,'' Mickelson said in an interview from his office in
Pierre.
   The wind switched from the southeast to the north during the
morning and gained speed, he said. That combined with a forecast
high of 100 degrees ``does not bode well for fighting the fire,''
the governor said.
   The fire had been declared 70 percent contained by late Thursday
after burning an estimated 2,800 acres. Fifteen homes, 32
outbuildings, 14 vehicles and a bridge had been destroyed.
   Earlier Thursday, about half of the 1,000 people who were told
to leave their homes Wednesday were allowed to return.
   Mickelson was at the scene Wednesday and saw a barn and a house
catch fire no more than 200 yards away. The buildings were engulfed
in seconds.
   Don Kopp, the fire incident commander, said Wednesday that the
fire was the work of an arsonist. And he said authorities have been
investigating a series of about 50 fires dating back to May that
are believed to have been started by the same person.
   A 14-year-old boy was arrested in Rapid City after a small fire
was reported on a ridge overlooking the town. But police said they
did not think he was responsible for setting the main fire on
Tuesday.
   Fires inside Yellowstone had charred 95,135 acres by Thursday
evening, about 4 percent of the park's 2.2 million acres.
   Although cooler temperatures, higher humidity and scattered
showers aided fire control efforts, the conditions created problems
for firefighters attempting to start a 6-mile backfire along the
eastern edge of the 8,500-acre North Fork fire that was within six
miles of Old Faithful.
   But the same conditions helped firefighters outside the park and
officials in the Bridger-Teton National Forest prepared to release
some of the 690 firefighters battling the 24,400-acre Mink Creek
fire in the forest's Teton Wilderness, said Ed Waldapfel, fire
information officer.
   The seven major fires in the park have not discouraged tourists
from visiting the famous Old Faithful geyser, as hundreds have been
gathering to watch its regular eruptions.
   Officials continued to stress Thursday that the Old Faithful
complex around the geyser was in no danger from the fire. The
complex consists of three lodges providing 521 rooms, including the
Old Faithful Inn, which is on the U.S. Department of Interior's
list of national historic landmarks. Other services at Old Faithful
include a general store and two service stations.
   Controversy continued over the National Park Service's so-called
``let it burn'' philosophy. The Park Service prefers its action to
be called fire management, saying fires are a natural part of a
healthy forest.
   Park naturalist ranger Don Buss said the last time the park
burned ``very badly was back in the 1600s.''
   Tons of fallen timber, fast-growing brush, trees killed by pine
beetle and nearly 100 years of fire suppression have kept an
elderly forest intact as a likely fire victim, park officials said.
   ``A forest that is 200-to-300-years old is more or less
preparing its own funeral pyre,'' said John Varley, a park
scientist.
   Five more families left their homes early Thursday in western
Montana when the Madison Gulch fire grew to about 900 acres in the
Lolo National Forest. About 50 people left their homes in the area
Wednesday as a precaution from areas near Alberton, a town of 300
on the Clark Fork River about 35 miles west of Missoula.
   There were 51 wind-whipped fires burning across Alaska;
firefighters were battling only 16 of them. Bureau of Land
Management spokesman Bill Rockwell said fires this summer have
blackened 1.4 million acres in Alaska.
   Ten families remained out of their homes in the area of the
3,000-acre Willis Gulch fire northeast of Boise, Idaho, and the
state imposed strict fire restrictions, due to go into effect at
midnight, on government land throughout the dry southern part of
the state.
   In California, firefighters were working on scores of small
fires throughout the Sierra Nevada, most of them caused by
lightning. But a fire that burned about 30 acres Wednesday near
Coulterville, destroying four structures and forcing the evacuation
of up to 70 homes, was blamed on a careless 13-year-old smoker.
</TEXT>
