<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Biaggi-Wedtech     07-28 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Prosecutor: Defense Attacks on Meese are a Smokescreen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor ridiculed defense tactics
at the Wedtech corruption trial Thursday, saying they were a bid to
cloud the case with allegations against Attorney General Edwin
Meese III.
   Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and six others on trial since
mid-March are charged with a racketeering conspiracy that allegedly
turned Wedtech Corp. into a vehicle for bribery and kickbacks.
   Prosecutors claim Wedtech, a now-defunct military contractor,
grew into a multimillion-dollar concern by committing fraud against
a government program that set aside contracts for minority-owned
businesses.
   A key element of the defense case, however, was the claim that
corrupt Wedtech executives had connections to Reagan White House
insiders like Meese and did not need to buy Biaggi's influence to
obtain the no-bid defense contracts.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Howard Wilson, in a day-long rebuttal of
the defense's closing arguments, compared the so-called ``Meese
defense'' to a squid that ``squirts black ink into the sea,
eveything gets cloudy, everything gets muddy.
   ``It's impossible to see the creature and he escapes,'' said
Wilson, adding that his admittedly ``silly parable'' showed ``what
so much of the defense in this case has been.''
   He compared it to ``a squid under attack. Talk about something
else. Don't talk about the facts. Create a diversion and a
smokescreen so there's a lot of ink and muddy waters.''
   In his closing argument Thursday, Biaggi attorney James LaRossa
said Meese was ``at the core of the conspiracy'' and accused the
attorney general of orchestrating corruption by investigating
Wedtech's competitors while allowing the company to pay his legal
fees during his confirmation hearings in Washington.
   Another prosecutor, Edward J. Little, shocked the courtroom last
week when he conceded in his summation that Meese ``was a sleaze''
but said his activities had no bearing on the guilt or innocence of
Biaggi and his co-defendants.
   In his rebuttal argument, Wilson hammered at that point.
   ``The biggest smokescreen or diversion in this case _ to protect
them (the defendants) from the truth _ is Ed Meese,'' said Wilson.
   Meese was under scrutiny for some time because of his Wedtech
connections, but a special prosecutor in Washington, James C.
McKay, determined there was insufficient evidence to charge Meese
with wrongdoing. However, McKay questioned the attorney general's
ethics on several issues.
   Meese has said he will leave office later this summer.
   U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley was to instruct the
jury on the law governing its deliberations Friday, before it began
weighing evidence in the four-month-old trial. Motley's charge to
the jury was expected to last all day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
