<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Massacres     07-28 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Massacres,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Asks Sudan to Check Massacre Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International appealed to Sudan on
Thursday to investigate reported massacres of hundreds of civilians
by government forces fighting rebels.
   The London-based human rights group also called on Prime
Minister Sadek Mahdi's government to repeal amputation and flogging
as legal penalties.
   In a 10-page report, Amnesty urged Sudan to ``take firm measures
to assert the rule of law'' and establish independent inquries into
reported massacres in the southern part of the East African nation.
   The report followed a letter the group sent to Sudan in May
outlining its concerns over reported human rights abuses. Amnesty
said it received no reply.
   The Sudanese People's Liberation Army, based in the Christian
and animist south, has waged a guerrilla war against
Moslem-dominated governments in the northern capital of Khartoum
since 1983.
   The rebels oppose Islamic law, introduced by ousted President
Gafaar Nimeiri, which imposes amputation and flogging for certain
offenses, Amnesty International said.
   No amputations have been carried out since the military toppled
Nimeiri while he was visiting Egypt in 1985, but floggings continue
and courts still pass amputation sentences, the report said.
   Massacres of unarmed civilians have taken place ``apparently
because they belonged to an ethnic group regarded as sympathetic to
or supportive of the (rebels),'' it said.
   Soldiers and militiamen reportedly massacred 1,000 to 2,000
Dinka tribesmen in the town of Wau in August and September 1987, it
said.
   Hundreds of other Dinka civilians were burned to death by mobs
in the town of Ad-Daien when police failed to intervene, the report
said.
   Relief agencies have estimated that fighting has displaced up to
half the 6 million residents of the south, the report said.
Hundreds of thousands of them fled to neighboring Ethiopia, where
the government is fighting its own civil war against rebels in the
north.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
