<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DigestBriefs     07-28 1092</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Digest Briefs,1138</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: This package does not contain the following items from the
News Digest: WASHINGTON _ Deficit; WASHINGTON _ Bank Deregulation;
BOGOR, Indonesia _ Cambodia; RAPID CITY, S.D. _ Forest Fires Rdp;
LOS ANGELES _ Cher's Boyfriend; BAR HARBOR, Maine _ Nerve Disorder;
UNDATED _ Political Rdp; WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. _ Landing
Shuttles; WASHINGTON _ Texas Tsunami; OXFORD, Miss. _ Blues
Archives.
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed a $5.8 billion relief package
for drought-stricken farmers Thursday after scaling back a heavily
debated price-support increase for the dairy industry.
   ``Hold on,'' House Agriculture Committee Chairman E. ``Kika'' de
la Garza, D-Texas, declared as the House approved the measure.
``Help is coming in a sensible, rational, compassionate way.''
   Approval came after dairy-state lawmakers responded to a
drumroll of criticism by compromising on a plan to increase the
price-support level for milk. The House adopted a scaled-back
version that still would leave the cost of the benefit above the
$100 million level.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer spending increased in June at the
fastest pace in 10 months, the government said Thursday, fueling
concern over inflation and whether the economy will have room for
production of exports.
   The Commerce Department said personal consumption spending,
which includes virtually everything except interest on debt, shot
up a seasonally adjusted 1.0 percent in June, the steepest climb
since a 1.3 percent gain in August, two months before the October
stock market crash.
   The report was a disappointment to many economists who are
looking for growth in consumer demand to slow in order to narrow
the nation's trade deficit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq demanded a formal peace treaty wih
Iran, not just a cease-fire, and asked the U.N. Security Council on
Thursday to guarantee its enforcement.
   In New York, the Iranian U.N. Mission said: ``The policy of Iraq
is to put obstacles in the way of the secretary-general's peace
efforts. This whole Iraqi exercise is planned to sabotage the
efforts upon which the international community is looking with
hope.''
   Both sides reported fighting at Eslamabad, 60 miles inside Iran.
Iraq, which says it has withdrawn from Iranian territory, describes
the invaders as Iranian rebels but Iran claims they are Iraqi
troops.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``L.A. Law,'' the gripping show
whose behind-the-scenes power struggles were as intriguing as its
onscreen courtroom dramas, swept the nominations Thursday for the
40th annual Emmy Awards.
   Cable programs, eligible for Emmy competition for the first
time, drew 15 nominations, accounting for less than 5 percent of
the available categories.
   The nominations were noteworthy, too, for who was overlooked.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service began a 16-month,
$700,000 quest Thursday to lick the problem of stamps that don't
stay stuck, urging industry to produce an adhesive to serve as a
``seat belt for a stamp.''
   Gordon C. Morison, a senior assistant postmaster general, made
it clear during a daylong conference at Battelle Memorial Institute
that the post office was serious about development of a superior,
water-activated adhesive.
   ``Unfortunately, the news that we have made in the last few days
is that we're spending a lot of money on something the press
perceives as insignificant,'' Morison told about 100 adhesive
industry executives and technical experts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A news leak on a covert plan to undermine
Panamanian military ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega came from the
Reagan administration and was a ``set-up deal'' to make it look
like the disclosure came from Congress, leaders of the Senate
Intelligence Committee said Thursday.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of the panel, and the
committee's ranking Republican, Sen. William Cohen of Maine, said
they believed the leak was a ``heavy-handed'' attempt to derail a
bill that would tighten congressional oversight of covert
operations, and also to enhance Vice President George Bush's
political prospects.
   ``I think the matter was handled in such a way as to set up
members of Congress to make them appear the source of the leak,''
said Cohen. ``I am offended by it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is pressing the Soviet Union
for maps showing the locations of millions of mines scattered in
Afghanistan during the Red Army's eight-year occupation so that
millions of Afghan refugees can go home, a top State Department
official says.
   At the same time, Pakistan's foreign minister, in a meeting
Thursday with Secretary of State George Shultz, allayed concerns
that the Soviet Union was reneging on its timetable for withdrawing
troops from Afghanistan. ``This impression has just been
dispelled,'' Sahabzada Yaqub Khan said.
   Shultz, Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and Yaqub Khan are
comparing notes on how to monitor the Soviet withdrawal _ and on
Afghanistan's future after the troops are gone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The home that has belonged to Nelson
Mandela and his family since the 1940s was gutted in an arson
attack Thursday that apparently involved a teen-gang dispute and
was not aimed at Mandela himself.
   Police said no one was hurt and no arrests were made.
   Police Capt. Ruben Bloomberg said in Pretoria that 30 to 50
black high school students stoned the home of the imprisoned leader
of the African National Congress, doused it with gasoline and set
it afire.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed supporters of American-born Rabbi Meir
Kahane are patrolling Arab sectors of Jerusalem in vans and on foot
in defiance of police, who have arrested 20 of the vigilantes in
six days.
   On one patrol Thursday, four men whose ages ranged from 16 to 24
drove through Arab east Jerusalem to the Jewish community of Neve
Yaacov and escorted bus No. 25, often a target of Arab stoning
attacks, to the center of the city.
   Officials fear such patrols by members of Kahane's Kach
movement, which advocates expelling all Arabs from
Israeli-controlled territory, will provoke violence between the
Holy City's 135,000 Palestinians and 340,000 Jews.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. drug agent who was kidnapped and
killed while investigating a narcotics empire in Mexico was beaten
so severely that his skull looked like a cracked eggshell, a
prosecutor said Thursday.
   In his opening statement to jurors, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Jimmy Gurule said Enrique Camarena, a Drug Enforcement
Administration agent, died what he called a barbaric death in a
torture chamber.
   The prosecutor outlined the evidence he plans to present to the
U.S. District Court jury hearing the trial of three Mexican
nationals charged in the case. The trial is expected to take about
10 weeks.
</TEXT>
