<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-APonTV-`TheReporters     07-28 0957</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-`The Reporters,' Adv 29,0983</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday PMs, July 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Fox Newsmagazine Perfects `Tabloid TV'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You know how you'll be standing in the
grocery checkout line and you'll pick up one of those tabloids with
the screaming headlines? And the story inside never lives up to the
promise on the cover?
   Fox has turned that kind of an idea into a television show,
``The Reporters,'' making its debut Saturday.
   True, there are no stories, at least in the premiere, about
aliens from outer space or two-headed babies.
   But the first installment does tease with the promise to
``answer the nagging question _ is Mike Tyson a homosexual?''
   Never mind that no one who screened the show at the TV critics'
convention here could recall ever hearing the ``nagging question,''
what seemed immediately more interesting than the answer was what
happened to the person who asked.
   Reporter Steve Dunleavy did put the question to Tyson, after a
fashion, but the program never gives the promised answer, other
than Tyson's mumble about such rumors being typical when you have
all the money and women.
   Otherwise, Dunleavy's piece is a rambling profile that reveals
little that is new about the heavyweight champ.
   ``The Reporters'' begins with a dramatic, fast-paced opening
similar to CBS' ``West 57th.'' What follows isn't really a news
show, though the reporters from ``The Reporters`` defended it as
such during a heated presentation to television critics.
   Earlier in the week, the same critics got a peek at GTG's
syndicated magazine show, ``USA Today: The Television Show.''
Questions about its ``Entertainment Tonight''-style of happy talk
paled next to ``The Reporters,'' which makes ``USA Today: The
Television Show'' look like ``CBS Reports'' by comparison.
   On ``The Reporters,'' the reporters make less-than-subtle
statements of their own conclusions about their stories. Getting
the other side _ or at least presenting it to viewers _ seems an
alien concept.
   Dunleavy even suggested there was no difference between his
editorializing in the Tyson piece and the commentary written by the
TV critics who were questioning his tactics. He didn't seem to
grasp the difference between clearly labeled opinion and something
presented as objective reportage.
   For instance, after Tyson tells Dunleavy he'd do something
``irrational'' to anyone who threatened his wife, Dunleavy gushes
in voiceover, ``And believe me, he means it!''
   Dunleavy is a veteran of Rupert Murdoch's tabloids in Australia
and more recently worked at the Star and the New York Post. Murdoch
owns Fox Broadcasting Co. Dunleavy is also seen on Fox's syndicated
news show, ``A Current Affair.''
   ``The Reporters'' is from the same people who do ``A Current
Affair,'' but that show somehow has an edge of wink-wink,
nudge-nudge, thanks in part to host Maury Povich, that is lacking
in the deadly serious and self-important ``The Reporters.''
   Rafael Abramovitz, another of ``The Reporters'' who is also a
veteran of ``A Current Affair'' became angry at the TV critics, at
one point explaining his cracking voice _ ``I'm trembling, because
I'm offended!''
   Besides the Tyson piece, critics took exception to a story in
which reporter Krista Bradford helped a Taiwanese student legalize
her alien status and avoid deportation.
   In the final scene, Bradford shows the girl a tape of an
interview with a government official agreeing to let her stay in
the United States. The girl, overwhelmed by the news, hugs
Bradford. Then the crew takes her to the Statue of Liberty.
   CBS' Dan Rather had some emotional encounters with traumatized
Vietnam veterans for a recent network documentary and the network
took the veterans to the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. But somehow it
all served to illustrate the issue without becoming embarrassingly
self-conscious.
   Abramovitz disagreed. ``If you think they (the networks) work a
story any differently than we do, they're a lot better at pulling
the wool over your eyes than we are,`` he said.
   ``I think we can display emotion without commenting on the
issues,'' said Bradford. ``I agree it's a fine line, and I'm happy
with where I have placed it.''
   Abramovitz called the show ``first-rate journalism.''
   ``We used to have a trick. We used to hide all these things and
make it look like `objective journalism,''' he said. ``I think it's
time to come out in the open and tell it like it is.
   `We're going to be doing stories about real people in a real way
and we're not going to confuse people about what's on the screen or
what's in our minds.''
   The critics didn't get to screen Abramovitz's piece for the
premiere show; the story, called ``The Actress and the Dwarf,'' was
still being edited.
   The reporters on ``The Reporters'' might have a point about
elitism. Low-brow entertainment has its place, and who doesn't have
a guilty pleasure?
   Viewed as unintentional spoof of the ``60 Minutes'' genre, ``The
Reporters'' is not bad entertainment. But calling it an objective
news show is a little scary.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   MORE ``REALITY'' FROM FOX _ Fox has more ``reality-based''
series in production for the fall to fill in for entertainment
shows delayed by the Writers Guild strike: ``Beyond Tomorrow'' is a
science magazine show, the concept imported from Australia where it
is a top-rated TV series; and ``Cops,'' in which cameras follow
five Broward County, Fla., police officers for a week, then edit
their stories together ``Hill Street Blues'' style. Fox says even
if the strike ended tomorrow, it wouldn't be able to get ``Angels
'88,'' its new remake of ``Charlie's Angels,'' on the air until
January and would barely get its comedy ``Married ... With
Children'' on in time for the November sweeps rating period.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, July 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv29   07-28 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 29,0642</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday July 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bills Coming Due</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation. Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The story appeared in the sports section. But
like many a modern sports story, it was about finance and
economics, too.
   After a prolonged negotiation, Dave Cadigan, the first round
draft choice of the New York Jets football team, had signed a $2
million contract.
   The sticking point, according to news accounts, had been that
Cadigan and his lawyer wanted most of the $850,000 signing bonus
paid in 1988, while the maximum income tax rate is 28 percent.
   ``Cadigan wanted to receive a larger portion of his overall
bonus this year, as the maximum rate could go up in succeeding
years,'' the New York Times reported.
   There is a lot of that going around these days _ a sense that
some long-outstanding bills will soon come due for many Americans
as individuals and the country as a whole.
   When analysts listen to campaign promises from either party this
year, they react with more than the customary skepticism. How, they
ask, is anybody going to pay for these goodies when the government
is already shoulder-deep in debt?
   ``Stop kidding us,'' says the current issue of Fortune magazine,
chastising the presidential candidates for playing down the
question of a tax increase. ``Everybody knows that for the deficit
to come down, taxes must go up.''
   William Brennan, who publishes the newsletter Brennan Reports on
tax and investment planning, is giving advice very similar to what
Cadigan got from his attorney.
   Normally, Brennan says, savvy taxpayers begin around this time
of year figuring out how to defer as much income as possible past
New Year's Day, in order to reduce the tax bills they will face.
   ``In the past, planning was usually concentrated on deferring
income _ that's no longer true!'' he observes.
   ``There may be cases where income should be accelerated into
1988, while tax rates are low. In the future, a 28 percent or 33
percent rate may be pretty appetizing when we look back to 1988.''
   It is less than two years since Congress overhauled the income
tax system, curbing or eliminating many tax deductions. The
legislators were able to sell the bill to the public by lowering
tax rates.
   So you might expect cries of outrage at talk of raising those
rates again. But there are other forces at work as well.
   One is the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings bill, also enacted in 1986,
that mandates across-the-board cuts in spending for government
programs unless specific goals are met toward balancing the federal
budget.
   In this election year, says Pamela Pecarich, director of tax
policy at the accounting firm of Coopers & Lybrand, policymakers
probably can dodge the Gramm-Rudman ax with some imaginative
maneuvering and optimistic assumptions. ``Next year will be a
different story,'' she says.
   Then there are the stirrings of inflation that lately have
troubled Wall Street _ and that Alan Greenspan, chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board, has spoken of with unusually candid concern.
   These inflation worries arise out of a vibrant economy in which
industry is enjoying a renascence and unemployment has fallen to a
14-year low.
   But that near-boom has been financed to a great extent with
other people's money _ in many cases, money borrowed from foreign
investors to pay for goods made by foreign manufacturers.
   ``There is very good momentum in the economy right now,'' says
Paul Boltz, financial economist at the investment management firm
of T. Rowe Price Associates.
   However, he adds, ``We haven't started to pay for this party.
And we won't until we have a trade surplus.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri July 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0722EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:WeirdAl Adv04   07-28 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Weird Al, Adv 04,0776</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs, Aug 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Parody Star Begins Filming On First Feature Film Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They stood on their heads and yodeled. They
smushed marshmallows in their mouths and chanted, ``Chubby bunny,
chubby bunny, chubby bunny.'' They dressed as Uncle Sam and tapped
danced on stilts.
   They were weird. But they had a purpose.
   More than 100 people staged their weirdest acts last week for a
chance to be seen on the big screen with a guy who proudly bills
himself as ``Weird Al.''
   His real name is Al Yankovic, a 27-year-old Southern California
native who hit the big time in 1983 with a song called ``Another
One Rides the Bus.''
   It was his way of laughing at pop culture _ the song is a parody
of the rock group Queen's hit song, ``Another One Bites the Dust.''
He's been laughing his way to the bank ever since.
   Five albumns later, Weird Al is on the radio and video music
stations again laughing at pop culture, this time with ``I'm Fat''
from his ``Even Worse'' albumn. The song and LP is a takeoff on
Michael Jackson's ``I'm Bad'' from the ``Bad'' album.
   ``Most of the songs I do are about food or TV _ two of the
things that have shaped my life most,'' Yankovic said.
   Five years later, Weird Al is still, well, weird. And he's
making a full-length feature film to prove it called ``U H F,'' due
for release next summer. Shooting was to begin in early August in
Tulsa.
   ``It feels kind of cold and clammy,'' said the former college
disc jockey. ``It's a lot harder to be funny for an hour and a half
than it is for three or four minutes,'' he said, referring to his
work with music videos.
   Ten years ago, Yankovic was an architecture student at Cal-Poly
San Louis Obispo College. He left with a degree and moved on to
develop Weird Al. Now he has a movie deal to film the screenplay he
and longtime friend and manager Jay Levey finished in 1983.
   ``The character that I play is going to be somewhat like Weird
Al,'' Yankovic said. ``But this isn't going to be `Weird Al's Big
Adventure.'''
   ``The movie is a cross between `It's a Wonderful Life,' `The
Texas Chainsaw Massacre' and `Purple Rain,''' said Levey, who is
directing the film. ``It's a love story.''
   OK, not really. Yankovic's character, George Newman, owns a UHF
TV station and turns it into the hottest thing around by putting on
nice, wholesome, weird programming.
   Levey began managing Yankovic's career ``from his inception .. .
when he was an embryo.'' He also has directed the Weird Al videos,
a change of pace from directing ``U H F,'' his first feature film.
   ``I just kind of fell into directing. Shooting music videos is
kamikaze work. You have two days to do four days of work,'' Levey
said. ``The pacing is not quite so deadly in film.''
   The Tulsa auditions were an open call for acts that may be used
later during the eight-week filming schedule when staging a
telethon to save Newman's station, Levey said.
   ``They came at us for five hours. They were all so strange,'' he
said. ``It's hard to describe them without sounding ridiculous. But
they were all great.''
   The movie is being filmed in Tulsa because it's ``the perfect
Anytown,'' Levey said. ``And that's meant as a very affectionate
compliment to Tulsa.''
   Executive producer Gray Frederickson suggested Tulsa as a film
location after his experience here in 1982 while shooting ``The
Outsiders.'' And having a chance to come back home makes working in
the state more desirable, he said.
   ``This is repeat business, so that's great,'' said Mary Nell
Clark, director of the Oklahoma Film Office.
   ``U H F'' is the fourth motion picture filmed in the state this
year. ``The Killing Device'' was filmed in Tulsa in April, ``The
Bounty Hunter'' in Sand Springs in May and portions of ``Rainman''
in Guthrie, Hinton and El Reno in June.
   Clark said she is able to sell the state to film companies
because of the varied location work that is available. ``I always
tell them about the varied terrain. I've hyped that so much now
that I think they believe me.''
   Television, video and full-length feature filming in Oklahoma
brought in about $50 million last year, Clark said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Thurs Aug. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv31   07-28 0990</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 31,1018</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drought Bites Into Cherry Pies and Bean Soup, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought has taken its toll on beans, peas and
other food crops as well as chewing away at big-ticket items like
corn, soybeans and spring wheat, says the Agriculture Department.
   ``The drought's greatest impacts on fruit and vegetable crops
are likely to be on dry edible beans, tart cherries, green peas,
sweet corn, and snap beans for canning,'' says economist Glenn Zepp.
   ``Wisconsin and Minnesota produce about 50 percent of U.S. sweet
corn and green peas, much of which is on non-irrigated acreage,''
he says. ``Wisconsin produces about 40 percent of the U.S. snap
bean output, about half of which is grown on non-irrigated
acreage.''
   The production of vegetables grown for the fresh market tends to
be concentrated on irrigated land, so the drought impact has not
been so great.
   Zepp, writing in the August issue of Agricultural Outlook
magazine, provided an appraisal of how the hot weather and drought
has affected several high-value crops.
   Here's a summary of his analysis:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CANNED VEGETABLES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Midwestern output of green peas is about 50 percent below
normal. Sweet corn and green beans are harvested later in the
summer, and production depends on rainfall in the remainder of the
season. Canners expect Midwestern sweet corn and green bean
production to be only 70 percent to 75 percent of what had been
planned, and carrot and beet production is expected to be 60
percent to 65 percent.
   Canners boosted prices of peas, sweet corn and snap beans by 10
percent to 20 percent in June because of anticipated production
shortfalls.
   Most of the corn, peas and beans grown in Wisconsin and
Minnesota are for canning. Vegetables for freezing are concentrated
in the Pacific Northwest, where water for irrigation generally has
been adequate for vegetable production this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>POTATOES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Hot, dry weather in June hurt development of potatoes across the
Northcentral states, reducing stands and stressing plants. The USDA
estimates 1988 total potato acreage at 1.27 million acres, down 2
percent from last year. The area for fall harvest is estimated at
1.06 million acres, down 3 percent from last year. The large 1987
fall crop resulted in generally lower prices, causing farmers to
reduce acreage this season.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWEET POTATOES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Growers planted 93,900 acres of sweet potatoes for 1988, down 3
percent from last year. The biggest change was in Louisiana, where
acreage dropped nearly 11 percent from 1987. Dry soils delayed
planting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DRY EDIBLE BEANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Drought appears to have contributed to a 36 percent cut in
Michigan's dry bean acreage this year, since most of the crop is on
non-irrigated land. Dry weather delayed plantings in Michigan,
which increased the chance of frost damage this fall before the
crop is mature. Also, some growers shifted dry bean acreage to
soybeans, hoping for higher returns.
   Michigan grows mainly navy beans, accounting for about 60
percent of last year's navy bean harvest nationwide. Navy bean
prices rose nearly 40 percent during the third week of June because
of anticipated drought losses and smaller supplies.
   The July estimate of area for harvest for all types of dry beans
was 1.51 million acres, down 13 percent from last year. In addition
to the decline in Michigan, large acreage reductions were reported
for California, Colorado, Idaho and Nebraska. North Dakota, on the
other hand, reported 21,000 acres more for harvest than in 1987.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>APPLES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Production is forecast at 8.07 billion pounds this year, down 23
percent from the 1987 apple harvest. All regions expect smaller
production. In Washington state, the stress on trees from last
year's record crop and this year's varied bloom and set contributed
to reduced prospects. Trees in New York's Lake Ontario region
suffered from some winter damage, and Michigan's crop is expected
to be smaller because of spring freezes and drought.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GRAPES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The California total grape harvest is forecast at 4.7 million
tons, up 1 percent from last season. Raisin-type grape output is
forecast at 2.15 million tons, down 2 percent from last year. Some
irrigators have had water allocations scaled back, and many have
switched to costly pumping of well water.
   Production of table-type grapes in California is forecast at
600,000 tons, up 18 percent from last year. Tight water supplies
have not affected table grape production, and growers are reporting
heavy yields.
   California wine grape production is forecast at 1.95 million
tons, the same as last year. Drought has had little effect so far,
but some acreage may undergo stress as irrigation water runs out.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TART CHERRIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Production is forecast at 207 million pounds, down 42 percent
from 1987. Production in Michigan, the largest cherry producer, was
off 43 percent. New York's output is down 34 percent from last year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TOBACCO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The total U.S. tobacco area for harvest in 1988 is estimated at
624,000 acres, up 6 percent from last year. Both flue-cured and
burley showed increases, reflecting higher effective quotas for
1988. Moisture has been adequate for plant growth in much of the
flue-cured belt, and yield prospects look good. But dryer
conditions prevailed in the burley area, so yields likely will be
reduced.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SUGAR BEETS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Estimated plantings of sugar beets were put at 1.32 million
acres, up 4 percent from last season. The acreage was up in all
major growing areas except California. However, dry conditions
resulted in poor germination, requiring growers to replant some
fields several times. According to industry sources, more than
250,000 acres, mostly in the Red River Valley, had to be replanted.
In some cases, farmers may have switched to other crops having a
shorter growing season or requiring less soil moisture for seed
germination.
   According to USDA analysts, sugar beet production will be
substantially below last year's near-record harvest, while cane
output may equal or exceed last year's level.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-28 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0564</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy expanded at a healthy 3.1 percent
annual pace from April through June, but rising food, energy and
clothing costs pushed the inflation rate to 4.7 percent, its
highest level in almost six years, the government reports.
   Some private economists worried that the big jump in inflation
reported Wednesday signaled the concluding stages of the current
long economic recovery and could well result in a recession some
time next year.
   But the White House dismissed the inflation figure as a
temporary deviation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henley Group Inc., after failing to gain
control of Santa Fe Southern Pacific Inc., has agreed to sell its
Santa Fe shares to Itel Inc. in a deal that would give Henley a 40
percent stake in the Chicago-based holding company.
   The companies valued the deal announced Wednesday at $1.2
billion in cash and stock.
   The complex transaction also calls for sale to Itel of Henley's
stock holdings in American President Cos. Ltd., a shipping
container company, and of Henley's Signal Capital subsidiary, a
financing company and lessor of railroad cars.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rainfall and cooler temperatures have eased the drought in some
of the worst-hit parts of the country, but extreme conditions still
prevail in the West, the northern Plains and the Rockies, the
National Weather Service said.
   Jitters about next week's weather held crop futures prices in
check Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade where corn prices
fell, soybeans were mixed and wheat was higher.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors who jumped into the agricultural
commodity markets when the Midwestern drought became apparent last
spring have been scrambling for the exit doors since the weather
changed for the wetter, experts say.
   With crop conditions either static or improving, prices for
future delivery of grains and soybeans have fallen precipitously.
   The drop in crop futures prices has spilled over into the
livestock and sugar futures markets, and has prompted some
economists to lower their month-old projections for 1989 food
inflation from about 7 percent to 6 percent or less.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of bank deregulation have suffered
several key defeats as the House Banking Committee works on
long-awaited legislation hailed as the most important change in
banking law since the Depression.
   By a 35-14 vote Wednesday, the committee approved an amendment
to permit mutual fund underwriting, and by a 27-23 vote it endorsed
an amendment to allow underwriting of bonds which are later
convertible to stock.
   As originally written, the far-reaching bill granted bank
holding companies some new securities powers, but would have
prohibited them from underwriting corporate stocks and mutual funds.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. says its second-quarter
earnings climbed 11 percent from a year earlier to $1.66 billion,
setting an auto industry record for the second consecutive quarter.
   The profit reported Wednesday was 2.5 percent above the previous
industry record the No. 2 automaker set in the first three months
of this year.
   Ford said its earnings, which amount to $3.43 a share, came on
second-quarter sales of $22.39 billion. During the same period last
year, Ford earned $1.50 billion, or $2.90 a share, on sales of
$19.50 billion.
</TEXT>
