<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0534</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prudential Insurance Co. of America has
launched what health industry officials deem a revolutionary
program requiring policyholders to undergo heart, kidney or liver
transplants at hospitals it considers to have the best
survivability rates.
   The nation's largest health insurer said Wednesday it will
negotiate contracts with hospitals to perform the surgery in a plan
that health and insurance industry officials hope will stem
spiraling medical costs.
   It may mark the first time a major health insurer has broken
with the tradition that the patient and physician choose the
hospital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aggressive investment firm Wasserstein,
Perella & Co. says it will receive a $100 million infusion of
capital from Nomura Securities Co., Japan's largest securities firm.
   In return, Nomura will control a 20 percent stake in Wasserstein
Perella, frmed six months ago by two leaders of First Boston
Corp.'s highly successful mergers and acquisitions operation.
   The two firms have agreed to work together on mergers and
acquisitions involving Japanese, U.S. and European companies. The
transactions announced Wednesday are expected to be handled through
a joint venture company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Direct holdings in the United States by
foreign investors have more than tripled since 1980, with increases
likely to continue through the end of the century, according to a
private study.
   ``An unprecedented transfer of American assets to foreign
control is under way,'' said the study released Wednesday by the
Congressional Economic Leadership Institute.
   The study said that since 1980, foreign direct investment in the
United States has expanded by more than 215 percent, while U.S.
investment abroad jumped by only one-fifth that rate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is
``scrambling vainly to catch up'' with a rapidly changing airline
industry whose decisions at times are driven by dollars and not
safety, a congressional study contends.
   The report released Wednesday by the Office of Technology
Assessment suggests that Congress provide the FAA with additional
funds and press for more inspectors and air traffic controllers as
well as organizational streamlining that places more emphasis on
safety.
   The FAA does not have enough inspectors, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC has hired newspaper editor Michael G.
Gartner as president of NBC News, replacing Lawrence K. Grossman
who has resigned.
   Gartner, named to the post Wednesday, most recently was a
part-time general news executive with Gannett Co. and editor of the
Ames, Iowa, Daily Tribune.
   Grossman said he is quitting because of differences with the
network's new corporate owners. General Electric Co. bought the
network as part of its acquisition of RCA Corp. in 1986.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined broadly Wednesday. The Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials dropped 20.27 points to 2,053.70.
   The dollar fell against most major currencies. Gold prices
mostly were higher.
   Bond prices fell in response to the report on economic growth,
which rekindled worries about rising inflation.
   Corn futures prices fell, soybeans were mixed and wheat was
higher. Oil futures advanced.
</TEXT>
