<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     07-28 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home heating oil has led a mild rally in energy
futures, reflecting technical factors and speculation that OPEC may
act soon to stabilize sagging prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate crude, the benchmark U.S.
grade, settled up 20 cents at $16.16 per barrel. The near-term
crude contract had lost 42 cents on Monday and Tuesday.
   Among refined petroleum products, the near-term contract for
home heating oil shot up 1.22 cents per gallon to 45.03 cents,
after losing 0.36 cent in the previous session.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline, which fell 1.06 cents per gallon on
Tuesday, rose 0.64 cent to settle at 50.80 cents.
   James R. Steele, an energy analyst with Refco Inc., said traders
were optimistic the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
would work toward cutting production at a price-monitoring
committee meeting set for Aug. 3.
   He said technical factors also partly were responsible for
boosting prices on Wednesday, with much of the attention focused on
heating oil.
   ``There seems to be a feeling that this area is now
underbought,'' he said.
</TEXT>
