<HEAD>Yields on Two-Year Notes Highest Since September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on two-year Treasury notes rose in the
government's latest auction to the highest level since last
September.
   The average yield was 8.41 percent on Wednesday, up from 8.05
percent at the last auction on June 22.
   It was the highest rate since two-year notes averaged 8.57
percent on Sept. 29. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of
8] percent, with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,993.70.
   A total of $8.78 billion in notes were sold out of bids
totalling $23.52 billion.
