<DOCNO> AP880728-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Nomura-Takeovers Bjt   07-28 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nomura-Takeovers, Bjt,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Japanese Securities Firm To Buy Stake in Investment Boutique</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wasserstein, Perella & Co.'s agreement to sell a
20 percent stake to giant Nomura Securities Co. for $100 million
represents a coup that could win the aggressive, young firm an ever
bigger share of the lucrative international merger and acquisitions
business.
   Other cash-rich Japanese companies have bought into large,
established, capital-hungry Wall Street firms. But the investment
by Nomura _ Japan's biggest securities house _ represents a
relatively more potent capital boost to the small, six-month-old
investment boutique.
   Wasserstein Perella was formed in February by two leaders of
First Boston Corp.'s highly successful mergers and acquisitions
operation, who quit to start their own firm.
   Under an agreement announced Wednesday, the two firms plan to
work together on mergers and acquisitions involving Japanese,
American and European companies. The transactions are expected to
be handled through a joint venture company.
   ``This will be a very good source of business for our firm, and
(Nomura's) knowledge of the Japanese market is a real advantage to
our clients who are looking to sell assets to Japanese buyers,''
said Michael Biondi, a vice president at Wasserstein Perella.
   Tokyo-based Nomura Securities had 1987 profits totaling $2.13
billion and a market capitalization in excess of $56 billion.
   Yoshihisa Tabuchi, Nomura's president and chief executive, said
the affiliation ``will provide our clients with unique benefits in
execution skills and strategic insight in the global mergers and
acquisitions marketplace.''
   Japanese companies long have had a keen interest in the
fast-paced M&A business that has evolved in the United States. At
the same time, Wall Street firms hungry for new sources of capital
increasingly have turned to foreign partners.
   In late 1986 Sumitomo Bank Ltd. paid $500 million for a
non-voting stake in Goldman, Sachs & Co. Last year Nippon Life
Insurance Co. acquired a 13 percent stake in Shearson Lehman
Brothers Holdings Inc. for $538 million.
   And also in 1987, Yasuda Mutual Life Insurance Co. agreed to pay
$300 million for an 18 percent stake in PaineWebber Group Inc.
   On Tuesday, Japan's fourth-largest securities house, Yamaichi
Securities Co., agreed to acquire a 25 percent equity interest in
Lodestar Group, a small U.S. merger and acquisitions firm headed by
Kenneth Miller, former M&A head for Merrill Lynch & Co. Yamaichi
also invested $100 million in Lodestar's corporate buyout fund.
   Biondi said Nomura made the investment for strategic reasons.
   ``They want to be an important factor in the global M&A market _
they want to learn and be in partnership with someone who is
perceived as a very high-quality provider of M&A advice,'' he said.
   One source on Wall Street said the deal ensures Wasserstein
Perella ``gets all the advantages of having the pockets of a major
player in the financial markets, while Nomura gets access to an
enviable flow of deals.''
   Indeed, Wasserstein Perella has represented such major players
as Campeau Corp., Georgia Pacific Corp., Beatrice U.S. Food Corp.
and Macmillan Inc. The firm, with offices in four U.S. cities and
in London, has advised clients on transactions valued at more than
$19 billion since its inception.
   Biondi said Nomura's contribution was the first ``outside
money'' the young investment firm had raised. ``Until now we were
100 percent owned by employee shareholders,'' he said.
   Wasserstein Perella has $500 million earmarked for leveraged
buyouts and expects to raise further capital for the buyout fund.
Nomura's contribution will be a substantial boost to the firm's
operating capital, Biondi said.
   In a statement announcing the Nomura deal, the firm stressed
that while its goal was to be a major player in mergers and
acquisitions, it did not want to amass a huge staff. That would
prevent potential problems inherent with a big workroll, such as
conflicts of interest, while sharply boosting the potential profits
for the firm's partners.
   Bruce Wasserstein, president and chief executive, and his
partner, Joseph Perella, the firm's chairman, were in Japan and
could not be reached for comment.
   The pair stunned the investment community in February when they
left First Boston, the investment house they helped propel to the
top ranks in the mergers and acquisition business. A string of
other First Boston professionals resigned to follow them, taking a
toll on the venerable investment house.
   The takeover team they headed was believed to have brought in
more than $350 million in mergers and acquisition revenue in 1987
alone, and some analysts estimated the duo was responsible for half
of First Boston's 1987 profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PrudentialTransplants Bjt   07-28 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prudential Transplants, Bjt,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Largest Health Insurer To Direct Transplants To Specific
Hospitals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Transplants-List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest hospital industry group
is calling for caution in Prudential Insurance Co. of America's
revolutionary plan to direct policyholders to have major organ
transplants at hospitals it believes have the best survivability
rates.
   The giant insurance company's plan, announced Wednesday, could
mark a break with tradition that leaves the choice of hospital up
to patient and physician, but is seen as helping to hold down
rising health care costs.
   But Bruce McPherson, vice president for group health care at the
American Hospital Association in Washington, said hospital ratings
based on statistics should not be the sole criteria for judging
quality care.
   ``It is important for them to disclose their quality criteria,
how that quality criteria was designated, what the connections are
in terms of the criteria they chose and which hospitals appear on
the lists,'' McPherson said in a statement.
   Prudential is the nation's largest health insurer, covering 20
million people. It has negotiated contracts with hospitals to
perform the special surgeries, including heart, kidney or liver
transplants.
   Dr. Dan Dragalin, vice president of the Prudential Group's
medical services division, said the company would use financial
incentives, such as coverage of travel costs, to have policyholders
travel to a handful of hospitals nationwide.
   ``We decided if we were going to direct patients (to specific
hospitals) we would choose institutions that meet very tough
criteria,'' said Dragalin. He also said Prudential chose hospitals
that offered the highest quality package for various operations.
   Prudential said hospitals found foremost in the industry were
promised ``volume in exchange for cost discounts.'' The company
negotiated discounts of 25 percent to 30 percent on the complex
operations, which can cost up to $250,000.
   Diedre Perkins, manager of group medical services, said the
company also tried to find institutions that could serve as
regional facilities for Prudential beneficiaries requiring a
particular operation.
   Joel Miller, deputy director of the Health Insurance Association
of America, said his group long has advocated the use of designated
hospitals for complex operations.
   ``We believe there are two distinct advantages,'' he said.
``When only a few hospitals perform a high volume of transplant
operations, we believe the outcome of the operations are likely to
improve. We also see designated hospitals preventing unnecessary
duplication of investment in transplant capacity, which will hold
down costs.''
   James Mortimer, president of the Midwest Business Group on
Health, a Chicago-based coalition of employers, also said the plan
could prompt lower health-care costs.
   ``Getting the insurance industry to actively purchase care for
its corporate clients is a major step,'' Mortimer said in
Wednesday's edition of the Chicago Tribune.
   Of the 50 to 60 hospitals that do transplants, Prudential found
three qualified for heart transplants, two for liver transplants
and seven for kidney transplants.
   Dragalin said Prudential intends to expand the system to include
other complex and costly procedures, including bone marrow
transplants, coronary artery bypass surgery, burn treatment and a
host of neurosurgical operations.
   Dragalin said the company is negotiating with eight hospitals to
provide neurosurgical services.
   The 1.5 million Prudential beneficiaries who are members of
health maintenance organizations or managed care plans will be
required to use the designated institutions, the company said,
while Prudential plans to continue paying for the operations of
other policyholders who use non-designated hospitals.
   Prudential said its primary goal is to prevent patients from
being drawn to inexperienced hospitals by lower prices for complex
operations.
   ``Hospitals are increasingly diversifying and performing
procedures they haven't done in the past,'' Dragalin said, adding
that many are trying to compensate for the loss of some traditional
business to health maintenance organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
