<DOCNO> AP880728-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USX     07-28 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USX,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USX Head Says Steel Unit Could Be For Sale, But No Buyers Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the steel industry enjoying a healthy
revival after seven years of depression, USX Corp. is willing to
sell a chunk of its steel-making USS division, according to
Chairman David Roderick.
   But so far, proposals to spin off up to 20 percent of the unit
have come only from investment bankers, not actual principals,
Roderick said Wednesday at his quarterly news conference.
   Roderick said he welcomed proposals, ``providing we were offered
full, f-u-l-l, value...and we certainly have no incentive to sell
it for less than full value.''
   The chairman of the energy and steel company declined to suggest
a figure.
   ``We wouldn't want to restrict the imagination of potential
buyers,'' he said.
   USX President Charles Corry said any deal probably would involve
USX making a public offering of stock in part of the steelmaking
division.
   USX would retain tax benefits accumulated during steel's years
of unprofitable operations, said Corry, who is considered a leading
candidate to succeed Roderick when the chairman reaches the
company's mandatory retirement age of 65 next May.
   Meanwhile, Roderick projected 1988 steel industry shipments of
81 million tons or more, a high figure that would mean two more
quarters of robust business.
   With demand for steel showing no signs of faltering and mills
running at or near capacity, prices are rising and profits are
flowing in, he said.
   Roderick said the USS division, the domestic industry's largest
producer, is reconsidering an Oct. 1 price increased it announced
to customers of flat-rolled steel.
   The timing of the price move was undermined by Bethlehem, the
third-largest producer, which scheduled increases of up to 5.5
percent for Jan. 1. No. 2-ranked LTV Steel Co. followed Bethlehem's
lead.
   Roderick said price increases are justified even though his
company is churning out profits of $70 per ton.
   ``Back in the first first quarter of this year, our prices were
about 19 percent below 1981. We've picked some of that back up in
the second quarter, but my guess is that we're still 12 to 13
percent below the 1981 steel prices,'' he said.
   ``And when we get out of this decade...the steel prices are
going to be lower than when we came into the decade,'' Roderick
said. ``I ask you, how many manufacturing industries in the United
States are going to get through the decade of the '80s with
absolutely zero inflation in price?''
   Stronger earnings in steel compensated for the diminished
performance in energy for a fourth consecutive quarter as USX on
Tuesday reported second-quarter profits of $213 million, or 74
cents per share, on sales of $4.3 billion.
   ``Oil carried us from 1982 through 1987,'' Roderick said. ``This
is the first period when earnings from energy were lower than
earnings from steel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-28 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up in Technical Reaction to Earlier Falls; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly stronger today against
most European currencies in what dealers said was a technical
reaction to earlier declines. Gold was weaker.
   Traders said the dollar was recovering through heavy central
bank intervention after it was driven down Wednesday by
disappointing U.S. gross national product figures.
   ``It went down unbelievably fast Wednesday, and so I believe
there is some room to make (the dollar) a little firmer today,''
said a Frankfurt trader. ``The central banks really pushed hard on
the dollar, and now it's a bit undervalued.''
   The U.S. economy grew 3.1 percent in the second quarter of 1988,
less than the 4 percent rate widely anticipated.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7360, compared
with $1.7265 Wednesday. Dealers said the Bank of England intervened
after the pound, surging on expectations of higher British interest
rates, hit 3.22 Deutschmarks, its highest rate against the West
German currency in two years.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates included: 1.8552 West German marks, up from 1.8495; 1.5340
Swiss francs, down from 1.5375; 6.2555 French francs, up from
6.2375; 2.0892 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0820; 1,370.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,365.50; and 1.2085 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2070.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 132.10. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 132.17 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $432.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $433. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$428.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $431.25, down from $432.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid price of $433.78, up
from Wednesday's closing bid price of $432.34.
   Later, silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.74 a
troy ounce, down from Wednesday's $7.
