<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-28 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell slightly today, but stock prices
were firmer in slow trading after the release of U.S. gross
national product figures for the second quarter of the year.
   On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the dollar opened at 131.67 yen,
the day's low, and was stable around the 131.70-131.80 yen range
during the morning session. It edged up to close at the day's high
of 132.10 yen, down 0.40 yen from Wednesday's close.
   Volume totaled $4.8 billion, slightly up from Wednesday's $4.3
billion.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected
issues, which posted its second biggest gain this year Wednesday by
surging 434.81 points, rose another 57.52 points, or 0.2 percent,
to close at 27.796.09.
   In the first section, 850 million shares changed hands, compared
to Wednesday's 1.3 billion shares.
   Exchange dealers said growing concern about inflation in the
United States put downward pressure on the dollar.
   The U.S. gross national product, the broadest measures of an
economy's health, grew 3.1 percent in the second quarter, down
slightly from the revised 3.4 percent rate the previous quarter,
according to figures released Wednesday. But inflation registered
the biggest advance since the third quarter of 1982.
   Securities analysts discounted any major effect of the dollar's
fall on the stock market.
   ``You can't apply the same old principle of `When the dollar
falls, stock market also falls' any longer,'' said Keiichi Nishida
of Kidder Peabody.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
