<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0804EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Henley-Itel Bjt   07-28 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Henley-Itel, Bjt,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Fe Shares of Henley Will Go to Itel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henley Group Inc., after failing to gain
control of Santa Fe Southern Pacific Inc., says it will sell its
Santa Fe shares to Itel Inc. in a deal that would give Henley a 40
percent stake in the Chicago-based holding company.
   The companies valued the deal at $1.2 billion in cash and stock.
   The complex transaction agreed to Wednesday also calls for sale
to Itel of Henley's stock holdings in American President Cos. Ltd.,
a shipping container company, and of Henley's Signal Capital
subsidiary, a financing company and lessor of railroad cars.
   Santa Fe Southern Pacific, which fended off Henley's advances
over a six-month period, responded favorably. Its president and
chief executive officer, Robert Krebs, said in a news release: ``We
... are sure that Itel wil be a constructive shareholder of Santa
Fe Southern Pacific.''
   Henley's stock price rose $1.50 a share to $24.75 in
over-the-counter trading Wednesday, while Itel advanced 25 cents to
$19.87.
   Henley, a holding company run by investor Michael Dingman out of
dual headquarters in La Jolla, Calif., and Hampton, N.H., said it
would receive $827 million cash and 18.7 million shares of newly
issued Itel stock.
   That would give Henley 40 percent share of Itel, which leases
railroad cars and owns dredging and wire companies in the Chicago
area.
   Itel would get Henley's 16.9 percent share of Chicago-based
Santa Fe; its 9.6 percent holding in American President of Oakland,
Calif., and its 13.2 percent stake in Oak Industries, a Rancho
Bernardo, Calif., company that makes and distributes electronic
equipment for the cable television and other industries.
   Henley subsidiaries Signal Capital and the smaller Equilease
Corp. also would change hands, bringing Itel's total assets to $3.6
billion.
   Henley, which under Dingman has bought and reshuffled a number
of companies in recent years, would be subject to a 10-year
standstill agreement requiring it to vote its Itel shares with
management and barring further purchases, said James Knox, Itel's
senior vice president and general counsel.
   Itel principals Samuel Zell and Robert Lurie, who through a
partnership own 20 percent of Itel's 27 million shares, would be
issued warrants to purchase new stock to maintain their 20 percent
equity position, Knox said.
   The railroad portion of the deal is subject to federal antitrust
review, which the companies said is expected to take 30 days.
   Itel would emerge as the largest railroad car lessor in country,
with 30,000 railroad freight cars owned by Signal Capital's Pullman
Leasing in addition to its own 43,000 cars, the company said.
   On March 18, an adverse court ruling prompted Henley to abandon
a proxy fight for seats on Santa Fe's board, ending a six-month
battle that included attempts to buy the company. A rival suitor,
Olympia & York Developments Ltd. of Toronto, ended up with 19.6
percent of Santa Fe and two board seats.
   Itel approached Henley a few months ago specifically about
acquiring Pullman and discussions blossomed into a far-reaching
transaction among like-minded investors Dingman, Zell and Lurie,
Knox said.
   ``Part of the attraction of this deal was the possibility of
working together,'' Knox said.
   Zell, Itel's chairman and chief executive officer, and longtime
business partner Lurie, now a director, bought into Itel in 1984 as
it was emerging from bankruptcy and moved it from San Francisco to
Chicago in late 1985 and early 1986.
   Itel, which earned $8.3 million on sales of $1.3 billion last
year, leases rail cars under that name and owns Great Lakes
International, a dredging company in Oak Brook, Ill., and Anixter
Bros., a wire manufacturer in Skokie, Ill.
   Dingman, 56, built what is now Henley out of businesses spun off
in the 1985 merger that formed Allied Signal Corp. Last year, the
company lost $278 million on revenue of $3.52 billion.
   Its interests include Signal Landmark Properties, a Southern
California real estate company, Henley Manufacturing Corp., which
makes chemicals and auto parts, Fisher Scientific Group, which
produces medical supplies, and 80 percent of Wheelabrator Inc.,
which builds waste-to-energy plants.
</TEXT>
