<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     07-28 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Higher At Midday On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose Thursday, boosted mainly by
speculative buying of selected issues.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index rose 5.2
points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,846.0 by mid-afternoon. Volume was
275.2 million shares, compared with 188.9 million shares at the
same time Wednesday.
   The market largely ignored the pound's surge and Wednesday's
news of a wider-than-expected British trade deficit in June,
dealers said.
   Instead, attention turned to speculative situations, giving
selected stocks a sharp boost.
   Among major gainers, shares in Pearson PLC shot up 42 pence, or
73 cents, to 784 pence after trading as high as 796 pence amid a
variety of rumors about the company.
   One rumor held that Pearson might sell off its oil exploration
and production operations in the North Sea. A Pearson spokesman
said the company was reviewing its options in regard to the North
Sea holding.
   Pearson shares also got a boost as attention focused on the
publishing sector, following speculation that Reed International
PLC could become the target of a takeover bid. Reed shares
continued their recent run, jumping another 20 pence to 463 pence.
   There also were rumors that News Corp., controlled by publisher
Rupert Murdoch, could sell off its more than 20 percent stake in
Pearson and then make a bid for Reed, dealers said.
</TEXT>
