<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-28 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0323</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market firmed slightly in the early
going today, but many investors remained on the sidelines awaiting
a clearer indication on the direction of interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 3.73 at 2,057.43
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 9 to 7 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 489 issues up, 377
down and 476 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 16.86 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts noted that the market's key focus is interest rates.
Concern that rates might be moving upward heightened on Wednesday
when the goverment reported that inflation rose more than 4 percent
in the last quarter.
   ``The market can't mount any kind of sustainable move if you
have rates going against you,'' noted Larry Wachtel, first vice
president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   He said the bond market, which opened lower today, has to
stabilize on a longer term basis before money comes off the
sidelines.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Chrysler was unchanged
at 22]. The automaker's report of lower quarterly earnings had been
expected. National Semiconductor was up [ at 10|; Digital Equipment
was unchanged at 102\, and Exxon was up \ at 45~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.27 to 149.01. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 0.09 at 302.76.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 20.27 to
2,053.70, its lowest close since it stood at 2,052.45 on June 2.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 2 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 475 up, 943 down and 503 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 135.89 million shares, against 121.96 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
