<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC     07-28 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.A.E. Leader Affirms Support for Opec Unity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto one name is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruler of the United
Arab Emirates affirmed Thursday his nation's support for unity
within the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, the
official emirates news agency WAM reported.
   The agency, reporting the meeting between Sheik Zayed Bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan and cartel Secretary-General Subroto, quoted the U.A.E.
president as saying his country ``has always been at the forefront
for boosting OPEC decisions and supporting the stability of the oil
market.''
   The report did not specifically address the controversial issue
of U.A.E. oil production, but it indicated the emirates would not
undermine the 13-nation cartel by adopting unilateral decisions.
   Sheik Zayed's statements were made after Subroto gave him a
message from OEPC President Rilwanu Lukman of Nigeria, according to
the WAM report. Details of the message were not disclosed.
   The meeting was also attended by Mana Saeed Otaiba, the federal
U.A.E. oil minister. Subroto and Otaiba met earlier as oil sources
said the OPEC secretary-general sought a compromise regarding the
U.A.E. claim for a higher oil production quota.
   WAM said only that Subroto discussed with Otaiba the ``latest
developments in the world oil market.''
   The sources, who spoke on condition they not be named, said
Subroto's visit came in response to reports quoting U.A.E. oil
officials as saying the country would abandon its OPEC production
quota of 948,000 barrels of oil a day and produce about 1.5 million
barrels a day.
   They noted OPEC's price monitoring committee will meet Aug. 3 in
Lausanne, Switzerland, to discuss the oil market situation in light
of Iran's decision to accept a U.N. Security Council resolution
calling for a cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war.
   The war has been casting shadows on the cartel's efforts to curb
production levels and maintain an $18 per barrel benchmark price.
Both Iraq and Iran are prominent OPEC members and have been
flouting production and pricing policies, respectively, because of
the conflict.
   The U.A.E. demand for a higher quota is also a prominent issue
for the Lausanne meeting of the five-member pricing committee which
comprises the oil ministers of Saudi Arabia, Venezuela, Algeria,
Nigeria and Indonesia.
   Otaiba has said the U.A.E.'s current quota was not fair and did
not synchronize with its production potential, claimed to be 4
million barrels per day.
</TEXT>
