<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Sematech     07-28 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sematech,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Research Consortium Names New Chief Executive and Operating
Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sematech, a research consortium of 14
semiconductor manufacturers in partnership with the federal
government, appointed longtime industry leader Robert N. Noyce as
its chief executive officer.
   Noyce, once called ``the Mayor of Silicon Valley,'' is a
co-inventor of the integrated circuit, a critical element in
computers and other electronics. He is also the co-founder of Intel
Corp. and is its vice chairman.
   Charles E. Sporck, chairman of the Sematech board of directors,
also announced Wednesday the appointment of Paul P. Castrucci, a
top technical executive at International Business Machines Corp.
with 32 years' experience, as Sematech's chief operating officer.
   Noyce said he at first took himself out of consideration because
of other commitments, but ``it finally dawned on me it was far too
important for someone else to do. I had to do it myself.''
   With the chief executive and operating officers now in place,
Noyce said he was ``confident we're going to be able to make a
quick transition into full blown operations.''
   Sematech, based in Austin, Texas, is the nation's first
semiconductor research consortium supported by both private
industry and the federal government. Sematech will sponsor and
conduct research into advanced semiconductor manufacturing
processes, materials and equipment.
   Results of the research will be available to the 14 member
companies and the Department of Defense license-royalty free, and
one to two years later will be available to non-members.
   Congress appropriated $100 million to Sematech in this year's
budget and the consortium said it is confident next fiscal year's
budget will also contain $100 million. The total budget is $250
million annually.
   Semiconductors are vital parts in almost every modern
electronics system _ from microwave ovens to communications
satellites. The electronics industry in the United States accounts
for $230 billion in annual sales and 2.5 million jobs, Sematech
said.
   Sematech's goal is world leadership in semiconductor technology
by 1993. Part of its strategy is also to work with universities
around the country, and five were named last month to receive
grants of up to $1.5 million a year for manufacturing research.
   Such consortiums have been successful in Japan but ``have been
attempted in Europe without a great deal of success,'' Noyce said.
   Sematech's staff in Austin is now at 135 and when it is in full
gear will employ 600 to 800. A large percentage of employees will
be assigned from the member companies.
   The consortium's member companies are Advanced Micro Devices,
American Telephone and Telegraph, Digital Equipment Corp., Harris
Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co., Intel Corp., IBM, LSI Logic Corp.,
Micron Technology Inc., Motorola, National Semiconductor Corp., NCR
Corp., Rockwell International Corp., and Texas Instruments Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
