<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned mostly mixed today as
investors remained apathetic while awaiting a clearer indication on
the direction of interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 0.89 at
2,052.81 in the first hour and a half of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 6 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 504 issues up, 597
down and 519 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 43.72 million shares as of 11
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts noted that investors' key focus is interest rates.
``The market seems to be suffering from interest-rate paranoia,''
one trader said.
   Concern that rates might be moving upward heightened on
Wednesday when the goverment reported that inflation rose more than
4 percent in the last quarter.
   ``The market can't mount any kind of sustainable move if you
have rates going against you,'' noted Larry Wachtel, first vice
president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   He said the bond market, which headed lower again today, has to
stabilize on a longer term basis before money comes off the
sidelines. As bond prices move lower, rising yields have been
attracting funds that normally would have been earmarked for
equities.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Interco soared 8] at
67}. The company received a $64-a-share buyout offer from City
Capital Associates.
   York International fell 1[ to 57[. SnyderGeneral withdrew its
$61-a-share bid for the company because of antitrust concerns.
   Elsewhere, National Semiconductor was unchanged at 10{; Digital
Equipment was up \ at 102{, and Exxon was up [ at 45}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up 0.06 to 148.80. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 0.02 at 302.83.
