<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Germany-InterestRates     07-28 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Interest Rates,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Bank Raises Key Lending Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank on
Thursday raised its Lombard lending rate to 5 percent in a bid to
bolster the mark, which has lost ground to other major currencies
in recent weeks.
   The Lombard rate had stood at 4.5 percent since Nov. 6, 1987.
   The mark has been falling against the U.S. dollar and the
British pound on foreign exchange markets. Analysts said the
Bundesbank's decision, which is effective Friday, was aimed at
supporting the mark and slowing the flow of capital out of West
Germany.
   ``With this measure, the Bundesbank is taking account of the
development of market interest rates and tensions in the currency
market,'' a Bundesbank spokesman said.
   The Lombard rate is the interest rate charged on banks'
short-term borrowings from the central bank against securities as
collateral.
   The Bundesbank left its discount rate unchanged at 3 percent,
which was set June 30 after a hike of 0.5 percent.
   The higher Lombard rate effectively lifts the ceiling on money
market rates, giving the Bundesbank room to directly tighten money
market rates further if the mark shows major signs of weakening,
analysts said.
   Bundesbank president Karl Otto Poehl has said the dollar's
advance against the mark endangers international efforts to adjust
trade imbalances in the United States, Japan and West Germany.
   Thursday's announcement follows Bundesbank decisions to raise
the rate on securities repurchase deals for commercial banks.
   That rate has been raised three times in the last six weeks by
.25 percent increments to its current 4 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
