<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade with soybeans slightly higher, corn
mostly lower and wheat narrowly mixed.
   The rebound in the soybean market indicated traders were picking
up contracts at what were seen as bargain prices after more than a
week of sharp declines, analysts said.
   ``People are bottom-picking, buying it on expectations that
because it's been down so far, it's bound to go up one of these
sessions,'' said Walter Spilka, grains analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   The early gains in the soybean pit occurred despite tne National
Weather Service's latest 6-to-10-day forecast, which predicted
normal rainfall next week in most of the drought-stricken Midwest.
   The corn market appeared nervous about the possibility of a
further decline, and wheat traders were awaiting word of new export
business, Spilka said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to 6 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.61 a bushel; corn was
2\ cents lower to 4{ cents higher with September at $2.77{ a
bushel; oats were unchanged to 1{ cents higher with September at
$2.49 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 4{ cents higher with August
at $7.58 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were sharply lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .47 cent lower with August at
66.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .35 cent
higher with August at 78.70 cents a pound; hogs were .52 cent to
1.05 cents lower with August at 44.35 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .27 cent to the limit 2 cents lower with August at
30.95 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher while pork futures finished mixed
on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
