<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Bank Earns,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barclays Moves Back into Black After Year-ago Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barclays PLC said Thursday it returned to
profitability in the first half of 1988 from a loss in the same
period a year ago when its results were hurt by additions to its
reserves against Third World loans.
   The bank said it had earnings in the six months ended June 30 of
393 million pounds, the equivalent of $684 million, or 43.3 pence a
share, compared with a loss of 72 million pounds in the same period
a year ago.
   Barclays made no additions to its reserves for Third World loans
in the latest period. It added 570 million pounds in the first half
of 1987.
   Revenue, including interest income, foreign exchange earnings
and commissions, increased 9 percent to 2.24 billion pounds from
2.06 billion pounds.
   Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd., the company's investment bank,
increased its profit marginally to 27 million pounds from 25
million pounds a year earlier. The division lost 11 million pounds
in all of 1987 because of the stock market crash and start-up costs.
   The bank did not break out quarterly results. It is not required
to under British law.
</TEXT>
