<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Coastal,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coastal's Profit Up 37 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. said its after-tax profit rose 37
percent in the second quarter from a year earlier, boosted by gains
in all its areas of operation and reduction of its debt.
   The diversified energy company reported Thursday that its
second-quarter profit increased to $30.6 million, or 50 cents a
share, from $22.3 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 11.8 percent, to $1.9 billion from
$1.7 billion.
   The largest second-quarter increase was in the oil and gas
exploration and production segment, where earnings more than
doubled to $14.6 million from $7.1 million a year earlier. Coastal
said the increase was due largely to a favorable settlement of a
contested natural gas supply contract.
   The company's other operations include gas pipelines, oil
refining and marketing, coal and trucking.
   ``Coastal has reduced outstanding debt and preferred stock by
about $470 million to date this year and by a total of more than
$1.1 billion since the end of 1985, the year of the merger with
American Natural Resources,'' said James R. Paul, Coastal's
president and chief operating officer.
   In the first half of the year, Coastal's earnings rose to $77.1
million, or $1.35 a share, from $66.4 million, or $1.25 a share, a
year earlier. First-half revenue jumped to $4.2 billion from $3.6
billion.
</TEXT>
