<1ST_LINE>u f PM-MGM-UASplit     07-28 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MGM-UA Split,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerkorian-Sugarman Deal to Divvy Up MGM-UA is Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deal to recreate MGM and United
Artists as separate movie companies collapsed today, just two weeks
after it was struck, because financiers Kirk Kerkorian and Burt
Sugarman couldn't agree on terms.
   MGM-UA Communications Co., controlled by Kerkorian, was to have
been split into its original parts in a $400 million deal that
would have given Sugarman and two independent movie producers a
substantial share of a ``new'' Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.
   Two weeks of extensive negotiations have failed to produce a
definitive agreement, said Stephen Silbert, MGM-UA chairman and
chief executive officer. Details of the talks between the two
financiers who share a fascination with Hollywood weren't released.
   The restructuring, which would have left Kerkorian in control of
a ``new'' United Artists and with a substantial share of the
resurrected MGM, was the latest in a series of shuffles the Las
Vegas, Nev., financier has made at the company.
   Analysts saw it as a means of raising funds to pay down the
debts of the company which produced the Oscar-winning movie
``Moonstruck'' and TV's ``thirtysomething,'' though much of the new
money would have come from Kerkorian himself.
   The complex shuffle, announced July 11, was to have been
accomplished through an offering of rights to MGM-UA shareholders
entitling them to buy shares in the new MGM.
   Sugarman, through his Barris Industries Inc., which makes ``The
Dating Game'' TV show, was to have bought 25 percent of the new
stock. Barris producers Jon Peters and Peter Guber would have run
the new company.
   Kerkorian and public shareholders of MGM-UA would have had the
right to buy the rest of the new issue of 50 million shares at $8 a
share.
   Of the $400 million raised, $300 million was to have gone back
into United Artists and $100 million to MGM.
   The new MGM, whose roaring lion trademark associated with such
classic movies as ``Gone With the Wind,'' would have had rights to
a batch of relatively new movies. But the company's original
3,000-title library was sold to broadcast entrepreneur Ted Turner
and the famed MGM movie lot was sold to Lorimar-Telepictures Corp.
in Kerkorian's last shuffle of the companies in 1986.
   United Artists' 1,000-title library includes the ``Rocky'' and
``Pink Panther'' movies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
