p.m. on Wall Street.
   The Dow firmed on the opening but flirted with negative
territory before heading higher. Market watchers cautioned,
however, that any spike upward is likely to be temporary.
   Traders said the market drew some support from comments by
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who said the Fed has not
changed its view on the course of monetary policy. He also
suggested the dollar is at appropriate levels against key foreign
currencies.
   Gains in the marketplace were scattered, however. There was an
improvement in several blue-chip issues, and high-tech stocks rose
but failed to generate much momentum outside the sector.
   Analysts noted that investors' key focus is interest rates.
``The market seems to be suffering from interest-rate paranoia,''
one trader said.
   Concern that rates might be moving upward heightened on
Wednesday when the goverment reported that inflation rose more than
4 percent in the last quarter.
   ``The market can't mount any kind of sustainable move if you
have rates going against you,'' noted Larry Wachtel, first vice
president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   He said the bond market has to stabilize on a longer term basis
before money pours back into stocks. But the credit market headed
lower again today after the Commerce Department reported that
Americans' personal incomes rose 0.7 percent while consumer
spending jumped 1.0 percent during June.
   Analysts are likely view the big rise in spending as
inflationary because it places a strain on U.S. manufacturers who
are fighting to lower the trade deficit.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Interco soared 8\ to
67|. The company received a $64-a-share buyout offer from City
Capital Associates.
   McGraw-Hill was up 3\ at 65 amid rumors that the British firm
Pearson PLC might make a bid for the publisher.
   Elsewhere, Digital Equipment rose 1| to 103~; Polaroid was up 1\
at 43{, and Hewlett Packard was up { at 48~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up 0.79 to 149.53. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.17 at 303.02.
</TEXT>
