<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Greyhound     07-28 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Greyhound,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greyhound's Profit Up 51.5 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greyhound Corp. said its after-tax profit
jumped 51.5 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier,
boosted by improvement in all its operations except financial
services.
   The diversified company reported Thursday that its
second-quarter profit rose to $29.7 million, or 78 cents a share,
from $19.6 million, or 49 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Greyhound said its net income for the second quarter was
affected by a $768,000 charge representing its loss on early
retirement of debt by GLI Holding Co. Earnings in the year-earlier
quarter had been affected by a loss of $9 million from discontinued
insurance operations and by a special charge of $2.7 million
reflecting premiums paid on early retirement of debt.
   Second-quarter revenue was up 39.3 percent, to $854 million from
$613 million. The company said the increase resulted mainly from
its acquisition of Dobbs airline and airport service business in
November 1987 and its purchase of General Motors Corp.'s transit
bus and repair parts operations in mid-1987.
   In the first half of the year, Greyhound's profit declined to
$47.3 million, or $1.23 a share, from $53.3 million, or $1.35 a
share, a year earlier. First-half revenue rose to $1.6 billion from
$1.2 billion.
   John W. Teets, Greyhound's chairman and chief executive officer,
said all segments of the company have shown improvement in 1988,
except for the financial group _ where gains from sales of assets
this year have not matched the higher-than-normal 1987 levels.
   Second-quarter earnings of the financial group declined to $6.5
million from $7 million during the same period last year.
   The company's consumer products operations, primarily Dial
Corp., reported net income of $14.7 million for the second quarter,
up from $13.3 million a year earlier.
   The service group had earnings of $22.8 million, up from $15.3
million in the second quarter of 1987.
   The transportation-manufacturing group's profit rose to $7.8
million from $6 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
