<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Disney     07-28 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Disney,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Up 29 Percent in Latest Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Walt Disney Co. said Thursday that a
string of popular movies and free spending by theme park patrons
helped boost its profit for the latest quarter by 29 percent from a
year ago.
   Disney said it earned $165 million, or $1.20 a share, in its
third fiscal quarter ended June 30 from $128.4 million, or 93 cents
a share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter sales rose 22 percent to $915.7 million from
$751.2 million in the third quarter of 1987.
   Disney continued to score box office successes, with ``Three Men
and a Baby'' and ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' adding to a 46 percent
increase in sales in the company's movie division.
   Sales at Disneyland and Disney World theme parks, which
contribute the bulk of the company's revenue, were up 12 percent in
the quarter, though attendance was lower than last year, Disney
said. Higher per-capita guest spending accounted for the increase,
said the company, which doesn't reveal specific visitor headcounts.
   Sales continued to increase in the new consumer products
division as the company continued to open stores selling Disney
paraphenalia.
   For the first nine months of 1988, profit rose 25 percent, to
$385.6 million, or $2.81 a share, from $309.4 million, or $2.25 a
share, a year ago.
   Nine-month sales rose 14.3 percent to $2.4 billion from $2.1
billion in the first nine months of 1987.
</TEXT>
