<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Meredith     07-28 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Meredith,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4th Qtr Profit Down, Accounting Changes Boost Annual Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meredith Corp. said Thursday its
earnings fell 19.4 percent in its fourth quarter from a year ago,
reflecting weaker magazine profits, but that profit increased 39.6
percent for the full fiscal year, in large part because of
accounting changes.
   The diversified media company reported profit in the fourth
quarter ended June 30 fell to $6.7 million, or 35 cents a share,
from $8.4 million, or 43 cents a share, in the same period a year
earlier.
   Its revenue rose 23.2 percent to $194.1 million in the quarter
from $157.5 million a year earlier.
   Meredith Chairman Robert Burnett attributed the reduced earnings
to declines in the company's magazine and broadcasting operations,
despite gains from real estate ventures and a lower effective
income tax rate.
   ``Weaker magazine profits in the fourth quarter reflect
substantial increases in paper and postage costs and our March
acquisition of Craftways Corp.,'' Burnett said in a statement
releasing Meredith's financial results.
   For the entire fiscal year, profit rose to $47.4 million, or
$2.48 a share, from $33.9 million, or $1.77 a share, in the
previous year.
   Without accounting changes, net profit would have been up 7.7
percent at $36.6 million, or $1.91 a share. However, profits from
business operations fell 6.4 percent in the latest fiscal year to
$36.6 million from $39 million.
   Burnett attributed the drop in operating earnings in part to
declines in Meredith's television broadcasting, because of higher
programming costs, and from residential real estate operations,
because of low market values on houses acquired under a government
relocation contract that no longer is in effect.
   Earnings benefited from a lower effective income tax rate and
lower interest expenses.
   Meredith publishes books and magazines, including Better Homes
and Gardens, and has interests in commercial printing, television
and residential real estate marketing and franchising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
