<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-McDonnellDouglas     07-28 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-McDonnell Douglas,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Off 27.5 Percent in Latest Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. reported Thursday that
its second-quarter earnings fell 27.5 percent from a year ago,
citing higher aircraft development and production costs and wider
losses in its information systems segment.
   The defense contractor said it earned $70.4 million, or $1.83 a
share, in the second quarter compared with $97.1 million, or $2.39
a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue slipped 1.4 percent to $3.48 billion from
$3.53 billion for the second quarter last year.
   For the first half of the year, net earnings fell 12.9 percent
to $121.6 million, or $3.16 a share, compared with net earnings of
$140.1 million, or $3.45 a share,
   Six-month revenue rose 2.3 percent to $6.72 billion from $6.57
billion for the first half of last year.
   The company said the earnings decline in both periods resulted
from higher development costs for the U.S. Air Force's Advanced
Tactical fighter competition and the new MD-11 tri-jet, higher
production costs in major aircraft programs and increased losses in
the information systems segment.
   It said higher interest expenses were offset in part by lower
income taxes, which declined because of lower tax rates.
   The 1987 earnings had been affected by several unusual items,
including a non-recurring pre-tax charge of $66 million to cover
the cost of an early retirement program. In addition, results for
McDonnell Douglas Information Systems Co. in 1987 included a gain
of $15 million before taxes from the sale of about half of the
corporation's interest in a computer services company.
   The company also said 1987 earnings were positively affected by
a pre-tax gain of $38 million from the conversion to long-term
leases of MD-80 jetliners previously leased on a short-term basis.
A similar conversion in the first quarter of 1988 produced a
pre-tax gain of $21 million.
</TEXT>
