<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0517</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market narrowly gained ground today as
investors snapped up blue chip and high tech issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 21.34 at 2,075.04
an hour before the closing bell.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 13 to 9 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 814 issues up, 572
down and 499 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 129.03 million shares as of 3
p.m. on Wall Street.
   The market's opening was tentative as the Dow flirted with
negative territory before heading higher as bargain-hunters moved
in to buy selected stocks. A firming bond market also helped
support stock prices.
   The market's scattered gains centered on blue chip, high tech
and takeover stocks. A better-than-expected quarterly earnings
report from Digital Equipment served to support technology issues,
while the publishing sector got a boost from takeover rumors
surrounding McGraw-Hill, analysts said.
   Market watchers cautioned, however, that investors are largely
uncommitted to equities.
   ``There's an enormous amount of cash on the sidelines,'' said
Michael Metz, a vice president and technical analyst at Oppenheimer
& Co.
   ``Investors are waiting for some signal that interest rates have
peaked or that the market is going up anyway before they really get
aggressive,'' he said.
   Traders said the market drew some support from comments by
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who said the Fed has not
changed its view on the course of monetary policy. He also
suggested the dollar is at appropriate levels against key foreign
currencies.
   Analysts noted that investors' key focus is interest rates.
``The market seems to be suffering from interest-rate paranoia,''
one trader said.
   Concern that rates might be moving upward heightened on
Wednesday when the goverment reported that inflation rose more than
4 percent in the last quarter.
   ``The market can't mount any kind of sustainable move if you
have rates going against you,'' noted Larry Wachtel, first vice
president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Separately, the Commerce Department reported that Americans'
personal incomes rose 0.7 percent while consumer spending jumped
1.0 percent during June. Analysts are likely view the big rise in
spending as inflationary because it places a strain on U.S.
manufacturers who are fighting to lower the trade deficit.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Interco soared 8[ to
67{. The company received a $64-a-share buyout offer from City
Capital Associates.
   McGraw-Hill was up 4 at 65} amid rumors that the British firm
Pearson PLC might make a bid for the publisher.
   Elsewhere, Digital Equipment rose 2{ to 104}; the company
reported better-than-expected quarterly earnings. IBM, which
announced price increases on most of its products and services,
rose 1~ to 123; Polaroid was up 1\ at 43{, and Hewlett Packard was
up } at 49[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.34 to 150.08. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.38 at 303.23.
