<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Price Increases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to fix typo in ``related.'' Picks up 2nd graf pvs,
IBM said ... SUBS final graf bgng, IBM did not ... to clarify that
only some subsidiaries in Asia-Pacific Group announced price hike.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Co. announced
Thursday that it is raising prices for many of its older products
and related services, excluding its newest computer models from the
change.
   IBM said prices will increase 5 percent on most products and
services, while maintenance agreement charges will go up 3 percent.
   Excluded from the price increases are the new IBM 3090-S models,
introduced earlier this week, as well as the new Application
System-400 and the Personal System-2 and RT system computers.
   ``The most important products are excluded,'' said Jay P.
Stevens, an analysts at the investment firm Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   Most analysts said the changes reflect the higher costs of
developing new computers and an effort by IBM to steer customers
toward its newer products.
   ``IBM does this occasionally, raising prices in certain areas,''
said Wendy Abramowitz, an analyst with Argus Research.
   Analysts said IBM's newest products already have the costs built
into their prices.
   However, some said the move could signal industrywide increases.
   ``It sets the tone for the computer industry that margins are
under pressure in some sectors of some industries,'' Stevens said.
   IBM did not announce any increases for its European subsidiaries
but said IBM Canada and 15 of its subsidiaries in the Asia-Pacific
Group, excluding Japan, Korea and Taiwan, announced similar
increases Thursday.
</TEXT>
