<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1605EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-York-Buyout     07-28 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-York-Buyout,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SnyderGeneral Withdraws York Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   York International Inc. reaffirmed on Thursday
its support for an investor group's $750 million buyout offer after
a competing bidder withdrew its $795 million buyout proposal amid
government antitrust concerns.
   York, a heating and air-conditioning equipment manufacturer,
said SnyderGeneral Corp., a privately-held concern based in Dallas,
notified York by letter that it was withdrawing its bid.
   York said its board had decided it was not in the interest of
York stockholders to pursue further discussions or negotiations
with SnyderGeneral.
   Instead, it reaffirmed its support for a tender offer by a
subsidairy of the investor group York Holdings Corp. for up to 9.19
million shares, or 87.8 percent of York's shares, at $57.50 per
share expires at midnight Friday unless extended.
   York Holdings' bid is backed by the venture-capital unit of
Citicorp, the huge banking concern.
   SnyderGeneral spokeswoman Michelle Pavlik said her company had
no comment, and said company president Richard Snyder was not
immediately available.
   According to York International, SnyderGeneral's letter
withdrawing the buyout offer said the antitrust division of the
U.S. Department of Justice ``raised new concerns late yesterday as
to product overlap between York and SnyderGeneral other than
centrifugal and reciprocating chillers.''
   ``If the Antitrust Division were to require a divestiture with
respect to this particular product line, we would not be willing to
consummate the acquisition of York,'' the letter said, according to
York.
   The letter added that SnyderGeneral planned to keep talking with
the Justice Department and said ``if we obtain a satisfactory
resolution as to these new concerns, we intend to reinstate our
offer.''
   But York subsequently released a statement that said:
``Particularly in light of recent developments, most notably
SnyderGeneral's last-minute withdrawal of its latest proposal, the
York board reaffirms it support of the York Holdings transaction
scheduled to close tomorrow.''
   York's statement indicates the company considers SnyderGeneral
out of the picture, York spokesman Patrick Early said.
   On Wednesday, York International said its board failed to meet a
noon deadline that day to respond to a revised buyout proposal from
SnyderGeneral.
   SnyderGeneral had requested consent Tuesday to modify its $795
million proposal under which York shareholders would receive $61
per share.
   The action came after York International announced the Justice
Department investigation of whether the proposed merger violated
antitrust rules.
   York International was a unit of Borg-Warner Corp. until it was
spun off and went public two years ago.
   SnyderGeneral is a privately held company that employs about
4,800 people at nine facilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
