<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Drought-StrandedWorkers     07-28 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Stranded Workers,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Seeks Relief for Migrant Workers Unable To Travel Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of migrant workers are stranded in
the Midwest and don't have enough money to return home because the
drought has robbed them of a living, a Texas lawmaker said Thursday
in seeking federal assistance.
   Democratic Rep. Albert Bustamante, in a letter asking Labor
Secretary Ann McLaughlin for emergency aid, said many migrants are
in a desperate situation ``we can no longer continue to ignore.''
   Labor Department spokesman Bob Zachariasiewicz said the agency
``has a plan of action'' but it won't be unveiled until Mrs.
McLaughlin, who is overseas, gives it her final approval. An
announcement will be made next week.
   An administration source said the package would total $4 million
to $5 million, but ``the final distribution is just not set on
paper yet.'' The source spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In his letter to Mrs. McLaughlin, Bustamante said: ``Migrant
workers pinned their hopes on a successful harvest and invested
their personal savings to search for field work. Drought conditions
have dashed their hopes for employment and for recouping their
financial losses.
   ``Because the president's emergency relief program is directed
solely at the farmer level, migrant workers and their families have
no safety net to relieve their conditions. Measures taken to date
have allowed migrant laborers to fall through cracks.''
   Bustamante, a migrant worker for 23 years and the son and
grandson of Mexican-Americans who followed the crops, said he still
has relatives who travel from Texas to Minnesota to harvest sugar
beets.
   He estimates the stranded migrant and seasonal worker population
at about 10,000, but said it is difficult to get a true figure.
   Bustamante said most of the migrants are U.S. citizens, and most
are from along the Texas border.
   ``Exhaused of their personal financial resources, they have no
money for temporary shelter and food,'' he wrote. ``Many would like
to return home, but they cannot. They are broke, indebeted,
stranded and dependent on the kindness and charity of local
efforts.''
   He said he is seeking funds to provide shelter, food and
job-search assistance to migrants who want to stay in the Midwest
to help farmers salvage crops, and to give others who want to
return home money for travel.
</TEXT>
