<HEAD>Dollar Higher; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major currencies
Thursday, led by strong demand in Europe and boosted by word from
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan that a stronger dollar
would not help the U.S. trade deficit.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted gold at a bid of $432.75 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down
from $433.45 late Wednesday. Analysts said the dollar started
sluggish, but gained strength in Europe and continued strong
throughout the day.
   The dollar got a spark from Greenspan's testimony before a
congressional subcommittee that the central bank was likely to
tighten rather than loosen credit, which would tend to support the
dollar.
   Analysts said Greenspan's reiteration of the Fed's stance helped
strengthen the dollar, due to speculation that interest rates could
move higher, increasing the value of dollar-denominated investments.
   ``Interest rates domestically are going up. That is reflected in
the bond market,'' said Jack Barbanel, first vice president at
Gruntal & Co. ``And the dollar is starting to get its strength back
again.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 132.10. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 132.35 yen. In New York, the dollar
rose to 132.55 yen from 131.63 late Wednesday.
   The British pound fell against the dollar. In London, sterling
was quoted at $1.7225, compared with $1.7265 Wednesday, while in
New York, the pound fell to $1.7215 from late Wednesday's $1.7288.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.88615 German marks, up from 1.84705; 1.5505
Swiss francs, up from 1.53845; 6.2875 French francs, up from
6.2255; 1,377.75 Italian lire, up from 1,364.00; and 1.20785
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2056.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with rates late
Wednesday, included: 1.8645 West German marks, up from 1.8495;
1.5505 Swiss francs, up from 1.5375; 6.2885 French francs, up from
6.2375; 2.0920 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0820; 1,370.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,365.50; 1.2086 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2070.
   Gold spot prices steadied after swinging in a relatively wide $6
range in Europe, dealers in Zurich said.
   But on the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for August
delivery closed at $432.50 a troy ounce, down from $433.50 late
Wednesday.
   In Zurich, spot gold finished at $432.50 an ounce, unchanged
from Wednesday's close. In London, the metal closed at a bid price
of $433 a troy ounce, also unchanged from late Wednesday's bid.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $433.78 an ounce,
up from Wednesday's closing bid price of $432.34.
   Silver for August delivery finished at $6.707 a troy ounce on
New York's Comex, down from $6.965 late Wednesday. Earlier, silver
was quoted in London at a bid of $6.79 a troy ounce, down from
Wednesday's $7.
</TEXT>
