<1ST_LINE>r f AM-M&AActivity     07-28 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-M&A Activity,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>M&A Activity Robust in 1st Half, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merger and acquisition activity increased
steadily during the first six months of 1988 while the dollar value
of completed deals jumped 45 percent from a year ago, a financial
information firm reported Thursday.
   IDD Information Services said that 1,705 transactions were
completed in the first two quarters, up from 1,622 in the first
half of 1987.
   More impressive, perhaps, was that the deals this year carried a
pricetag of $131 billion, up from $89.5 billion in the year-ago
period, the firm said.
   Foreign investors snapped up U.S. companies at a rapid pace,
spending $25 billion on acquisitions in the first half of this
year, up 67 percent from $15 billion in 1987.
   IDD attributed the interest _ led by Canada, Japan and Great
Britain _ to a weaker dollar.
   Despite predictions of a decrease in activity following the
October market crash, leveraged buyouts moved along at a brisk
clip. In the first half of the year, IDD said there were 77
leveraged buyouts with a total value of $30 billion, compared with
58 buyouts valued at $20 billion a year ago.
   In a leveraged buyout, investors borrow against a target
company's assets and repay borrowed funds from the company's cash
flow.
   The use of tender offers as a way to acquire companies also
increased dramatically. IDD said such transactions were valued at
$75.9 billion, compared with $35.3 billion in tender offers a year
ago.
   In terms of number of transactions completed, Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. led the pack of major investment houses by acting as
financial advisor in 92 deals; followed by Goldman Sachs & Co. with
77 and First Boston Corp. with 70.
   Based on dollar value, however, Goldman Sachs was No. 1,
representing $41.72 billion in completed transactions, followed by
Shearson Lehman, $40.4 billion, and First Boston, $34.1 billion.
   IDD Information Services, headquartered in New York, supplies
the merger and acquisition information to financial and legal
clients.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
