<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Earnings Plunge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 13th graf pvs, The first ... to
include first-half sales figures. Picks up 14th graf pvs, During
the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL ANN RIHA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. reported Thursday that its
second-quarter earnings slid 24.5 percent compared with a year ago,
and analysts said buyer incentive programs may have compressed
results more than the company expected.
   The nation's No. 3 automaker said it earned $320.4 million, or
$1.45 per share, in the three months ended June 30 compared with
$424.1 million, or $1.98 per share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   The depressed profits due to rebate and incentives programs were
a short-term sacrifice to boost market share and improve the
company's long-term competitiveness, Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca
said.
   That game plan led to brisk sales, which should strengthen
Chrysler's standing in the marketplace, Iacocca said.
   ``You get a conquest (first time) buyer into your stable and
hopefully you keep him,'' explained Joseph Phillippi, auto analyst
with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The results came on sales of nearly $8.5 billion in the second
quarter, up 32.8 percent from $6.4 billion in the same period a
year ago.
   ``The profit margins were very poor considering the level of
business they did in the quarter,'' said analyst Dave Healy of
Drexel Burnham Lambert of New York. ``They have been pushing
heavily with incentives and the market share's gone up, but the
results show the effect of it.''
   ``They were a little bit under where they were going to come in
(under the forecast),'' Phillippi said. ``The principal reason,
essentially as I read the number, was average yields per unit were
down a little bit, and that reflects fleet sales, the cost of
rebates and incentives... It was essentially the incentives.''
   Chrysler's 20.7 percent share of the U.S. truck market was up
nearly two percentage points from the second quarter of 1987, the
company said.
   Through June, Chrysler's combined U.S. car and truck retail
sales were up 16 percent from the same period of 1987.
   ``We're going after a bigger base of loyal customers, because
that's what it takes to succeed over the long haul,'' Iacocca said.
   For the first half of the year, Chrysler's net earnings totaled
$504.1 million, or $2.27 per share, down from $693.5 million, or
$3.22 per share.
   The first half results include a $93.1 million charge for
previously announced plant closings in the Acustar Inc. subsidiary.
   First-half sales rose 30.6 percent to $16.16 billion from $12.44
billion a year earlier.
   During the second quarter, the nation's No. 3 automaker
continued to hold the line on 1988 model prices, with 42 percent of
the passenger cars it sells tagged below 1987 prices.
   ``That's paid off for us in higher market share, but we're
caught in a classic case of `margin squeeze,' and we can't rely on
that strategy forever,'' Iacocca said.
   ``We have seen that the incentives, in terms of rebates, have
been coming steadily down for about six months,'' Phillippi said.
``The basic game plan, I think, in a sense among the executives at
the three large companies, is to launch the new models without any
meaningful incentives.''
   On Wednesday, Chrysler announced a small price increase on the
Colt GT for 1989, but said it would lower prices on two other Colt
models.
   Chrysler Financial Corp., Chrysler's credit arm, made record
earnings on the increased sales volume, reporting profits of $61
million for the second quarter of 1988 and $126 million for the
first six months of the year, the subsidiary announced today.
   The results eclipse the previous quarterly high of $56 million,
set in the second quarter of 1987, and a six-month earnings record
of $117 million, also set a year ago, a company statement said.
   On Wednesday, No. 2 Ford Motor Co. reported an auto industry
record second quarter, earning $1.66 billion, up from $1.50 billion
in the second quarter of 1987. General Motors Corp., the world's
largest manufacturer, last week reported its second-quarter
earnings _ $1.5 billion, compared with $1.17 billion in the
comparable period of 1987.
</TEXT>
