<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 1832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru   07-28 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0899</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Slip, Sugar Sinks; Technicals Cited</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 17th graf pvs, Sugar futures ...
with coffee prices. Picks up 18th graf pvs, The continuing ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and sugar futures prices fell sharply Thursday in trading
that analysts said was inspired by technical conditions and had
little to do with fundamental supply-and-demand factors.
   Most wheat and soybean futures also slipped lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade, and coffee futures joined sugar in falling for a
third straight day on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange.
   On other markets, precious metals were lower; cattle were up
while pork futures plunged; and energy futures were mixed.
   Thursday marked the fifth consecutive day of falling corn
futures prices and the ninth straight daily drop in the price for
August delivery of soybeans.
   But in a departure from the past three months, the weather had
little impact on the markets, analysts said.
   Instead, they said corn traders were watching their market's
open interest, a rough measure of the number of speculators who
have _ in effect _ placed their bets but not collected their
winnings.
   Open interest has been running at an unusually high level in the
corn market and stood at more than 244,000 contracts when the
market opened Thursday.
   The majority of the open interest was believed to represent
``long'' positions, or wagers that prices would rise. Since prices
have been falling, some players feared that many holders of those
long positions were preparing to sell and either cut their losses
or settle for only a slight profit.
   A sudden, massive sell-off would cause prices to plummet and
some traders tried to beat the rush by selling ahead of it, which
caused corn prices to fall sharply anyway.
   The selling sentiment spread to the neighboring wheat and
soybean pits, causing prices to fall in those markets, too, said
Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris
Upham & Co.
   The National Weather Service's latest 6-to-10-day forecast,
calling for normal rainfall next week in the drought-stricken
Midwest, was bearish but it was not a major factor in Thursday's
action, Spilka said.
   ``I think weather forecasts are maybe contributing about half
the influence right now (and) I think near-term forecasts are more
important than the 6-to-10-days,'' he said.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 5{ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.57 a bushel; corn was 14} cents lower
to 2 cents higher with September at $2.65 a bushel; oats were 3
cents lower to 7{ cents higher with September at $2.56{ a bushel;
and soybeans were 12 cents lower to 15 cents higher with August at
$7.41{ a bushel.
   The situation was similar in the sugar market, which ignored the
bullish news of new sugar purchases by China and plummeted to its
lowest level in about a month.
   ``This was a technically driven sell-off,'' said Judith Ganes,
sugar analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Sugar futures have been extremely strong and stood at 6{-year
highs on Monday. Ms. Ganes said the market fundamentals remained
bullish and that the nearly 3{-cent plunge over three days ``just
gives you better bargains.''
   Sugar for October delivery settled .53 cent lower at 10.82 cents
a pound.
   Coffee futures continued their technically-driven decline with
the September contract settling .26 cent lower at $1.2379 a pound.
   The continuing decline in the grain markets forced some
speculators with additional holdings in silver and platinum futures
to take profits in the metals markets so they could meet their
financial obligations in the grain markets, said Bette Raptopoulos,
an analyst in New York with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Gold was more stable in its traditional role as a ``safe haven''
for investment dollars, she said.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled 70 cents to $1
lower with August at $432.50 a troy ounce; silver was 25.8 cents to
29.6 cents lower with August at $6.707 a troy ounce.
   Hog and pork-belly futures fell their respective daily limits of
1.50 cents and 2 cents a pound on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
because ``there's too much supply and not enough demand, period,''
said Chuck Levitt, an analyst in Chicago with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   Cattle futures followed the grains to a mixed close, Levitt said.
   Live cattle were .87 cent lower to .33 cent higher with August
at 66.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .93
cent higher with August at 79.75 cents a pound; hogs were 1.12
cents to 1.50 cents lower with August at 43.87 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were 1.32 cents to 2 cents lower with August at
30.95 cents a pound.
   Crude oil prices were little changed in quiet trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange as traders waited for an upcoming OPEC
committee meeting.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 1 cent to 2 cents lower
with September at $16.15 a barrel; heating oil was .23 cent to .69
cent lower with August at 44.34 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .11 cent lower to 1.15 cents higher with August at 51.95 cents
a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
