<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-CruiseShips     07-28 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Cruise Ships,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>P&O Agrees to Buy Sitmar Cruises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peninsular and Oriental Steamship Navigation Co.
said Thursday it will acquire U.S.-based Sitmar Cruises
International Inc. for $210 million in a bid to boost the British
company's luxury cruise operations.
   The purchase gives P and O control of Sitmar's Los Angeles-based
fleet of four cruise ships and three large cruise ships currently
under construction. Sitmar is privately owned by U.S. and European
investors.
   P and O subsidiary Princess Cruises has a five-ship fleet, also
based in Los Angeles.
   P and O Chairman Sir Jeffrey Sterling said the combined fleets
should make a strong contribution to the group's earnings once the
new Sitmar ships are added in the early 1990s.
   The cruise ship operations are part of P and O's passenger
service division, which Sterling said contributed 47 million
pounds, or $82 million, to total 1987 operating profit of 328
million pounds, or $571 million.
   Sterling said Sitmar is profitable, but P and O did not provide
any figures.
</TEXT>
