<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Airlines 1stLd-Writethru   07-28 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Airlines, 1st Ld-Writethru,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAL, Delta Post Higher Profit</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: NEW grafs 2-3 to CLARIFY that comparison included nonairline
subsidiaries; picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, The number ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines and the parent of United Airlines on Thursday
said their after-tax profit rose strongly in the latest quarter
from a year earlier, boosted by revenue gains generated by growth
in passenger traffic.
   UAL Corp., the parent of United, the nation's largest airline,
reported a 134 percent jump in second-quarter profit. Its earnings
advanced to $124.2 million, or $5.77 a share.
   The profits surged past last year's second-quarter airline
earnings of $53 million. The company actually earned a total of
$73.4 million, or $1.29 a share, during 1987's second quarter, but
that figure included profits from nonairline subsidiaries it has
since sold.
   The number of UAL shares outstanding was sharply reduced during
the period, to around 21.5 million in the second quarter of 1988
from 56.9 million in the year-earlier quarter.
   Second-quarter revenue rose to $2.34 billion from $2.07 billion
a year earlier.
   Early this year, Chicago-based UAL completed the sale of its
non-airline assets _ the Hertz car rental agency and the Westin and
Hilton International hotel chains. It changed its name from Allegis
Corp., which had been intended to signify its former status as a
travel conglomerate.
   ``These results make it clear that United has returned to its
core business of running an airline and doing so with the talent of
63,000 committed employees,'' said Chairman Stephen M. Wolf, who
took over the company last December following the ouster of former
chief Richard Ferris.
   In the first half of the year, UAL's profit surged to $701
million, or $19.12 a share, from $42.8 million, or 79 cents a
share, a year earlier. Earnings in the 1988 first half include a
$548 million gain from the sale of Westin Hotels.
   The number of shares outstanding dropped to around 36.6 million
in the first six months of 1988 from 54.0 million in the same
period of 1987.
   First-half revenue rose 13 percent, to $4.44 billion from $3.93
billion.
   Atlanta-based Delta, the third-largest U.S. airline, reported a
76 percent boost in profit in the fourth quarter of its fiscal year
ended June 30.
   Delta's fourth-quarter earnings jumped to $103.28 million, or
$2.11 a share, from $58.8 million, or $1.21 a share, a year earlier.
   The results for the latest quarter include a loss of $1.08
million, or 2 cents a share, from the disposition of aircraft and
an $89,000 loss from foreign currency translation.
   Fourth-quarter revenue rose 19.1 percent, to $1.87 billion from
$1.57 billion.
   Analysts said the airline probably benefited from troubles at
Eastern Airlines, Delta's main competitor.
   Miami-based Eastern has been beset by labor and financial
problems, including a federal safety inspection of its fleet, and
last week announced the layoffs of about 4,000 employees plus the
elimination of 140 flights.
   Prior to those cutbacks, Delta competed head-to-head with
Eastern on about 70 percent of its routes.
   For its fiscal year ended June 30, Delta's profit rose to
$306.83 million, or $6.30 a share, from $263.73 million, or $5.90 a
share, in fiscal 1987.
   It was Delta's first full fiscal year since its takeover of
Western Airlines.
   Revenue for the fiscal year increased to $6.92 billion from
$5.32 billion.
</TEXT>
