<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 2150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Tenneco     07-28 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Tenneco,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports 2nd-Qtr Profit More than Tripled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc. reported Thursday that its
second-quarter profit more than tripled with an assist from a
one-time gain from sale of two subsidiaries.
   The company also announced it has opened its books to about 10
different bidders seeking to buy Tenneco Oil Co., the unit involved
in exploration and production and refining and marketing that was
put up for sale in May.
   For the three-month period ending June 30, the diversified
energy company posted net earnings of $154 million, or $1 per
share, compared with $46 million, or 24 cents per share, during the
same period a year ago.
   The latest results include a one-time gain of $23 million
related to the sale of Tenneco Oil Co. of Gebr. Broere, a European
shipping and storage company, and Mitchell Supreme, a New Jersey
heating oil retailing company.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 5.4 percent to $3.9 billion from
$3.7 billion a year earlier.
   For the first six months of 1988, Tenneco Inc. said its net
income nearly tripled to $217 million, or $1.38 per share, from $75
million, or 32 cents per share, for the first half of 1987.
   Six-month revenue rose 6.8 percent to $7.9 billion from $7.4
billion.
   ``The core of businesses which will comprise Tenneco following
the sale of the oil company reported strong profits with pipelines,
automotive, packaging, chemicals and agricultural and construction
equipment recording increases over last year,'' Ketelsen said.
   Each bidder for Tenneco Oil gets one week to review the
information, available through Aug. 25. The first round of bids is
due Sept. 30.
   ``We've been very encouraged by the interest,'' James L.
Ketelsen, chairman and chief operating officer of Tenneco, said
during a news conference.
   Ketelsen said potential buyers may bid on major segments or as a
whole. He declined to disclose names of the bidders, who signed
confidentialty agreements.
   When Tenneco announced plans to sell Tenneco Oil, it said it
would use the proceeds to help pay its hefty $8.5 billion debt.
Analysts have estimated that the sale could fetch between $5
billion to $7 billion.
   For the second quarter, the Tenneco Oil unit recorded net income
of $147 million, compared with $76 million for the same quarter in
1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
